<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thruway official: losing canals would be way around toll hike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - While not exactly endorsing a proposal to give
another agency the responsibility for the state canal system, the executive
director of the Thruway Authority says the idea sounds intriguing.
<P>
	   John Platt noted Wednesday that giving away the canal system would save
roughly the same amount of money the Thruway Authority had planned to raise
through an unpopular toll increase plan.
</P>
<P>
	   And, Platt conceded that the authority lacks the money to maintain and
promote the canals in a style the historic waterways deserve.
</P>
<P>
	   "We really don't have the assets and resources to make that (the canal
system) the economic development engine that we could," Platt told a state
Assembly hearing on the proposed Thruway toll increases. "That is one of our
dilemmas."
</P>
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority has had responsibility for the 524 miles of state
canals, including the remaining portions of the venerable Erie Canal, since
1992. Platt said it costs the authority $55 million to $60 million a year to
maintain and operate the waterways, but he acknowledged that's not nearly enough
funding to do the kind of improvements and beautification to make the canal a
premiere recreational boat route and tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority is also hampered in maintaining the canal system by
long-ago-reached cap on how much it can borrow for canal projects, Platt said.
All maintenance on the system must be done on a pay-as-you-go basis.
</P>
<P>
	   "The need for rehabilitation continues year in and year out," he said. "This
is a system that is in some cases more than 100 years old. It's held up very
well considering its age."
</P>
<P>
	   State Assembly Republicans on Tuesday proposed turning the canal system over
to the state Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation. That, in
effect, means all New York taxpayers would pay for the canals instead of
motorists on the New York State Thruway.
</P>
<P>
	   Platt, echoing Tuesday's comments by Thruway Authority Chairman Lou Tomson,
said the canal divestment proposal merits "careful consideration."
</P>
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority's board on Jan. 27 approved a previously unannounced
plan for what it called annual toll "adjustments" - toll hikes - based on
increases in a 20-city Construction Cost Index. The first-year increase would
have been 1.8 percent under that plan, to have gone into effect on June 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Thruway officials said they need the extra money to pay for roadway
improvements over the next five years, from lane additions in some urban
stretches to things like a "flyover" at the Thruway's busiest exit, No. 24 in
Albany. The flyover would be a special link between the Thruway and Interstate
87 only for E-ZPass users.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. George Pataki, legislative leaders and business groups criticized the
toll increase plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Platt said the Thruway needs $216 million more over five years to pay for
road maintenance and new projects. Coincidentally, giving away fiscal
responsibility for the canal system would save the Thruway Authority roughly the
same amount of money.
</P>
<P>
	   Or perhaps that is no coincidence, suggested state Assemblyman Paul Tonko, a
Montgomery County Democrat.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the sequence of events since Jan. 27 - a previously unknown toll
hike plan coming to light, criticism from state leaders including Pataki of a
toll hike and the emergence of the canal divestment proposal - might look to
"some cynics" like "orchestrating" to get the Legislature to go along with a
shift of responsibility for the canals.
</P>
<P>
	   Platt said the idea of giving up the canals because they are a financial
drain on the Thruway has been talked about since the Thruway Authority took them
over from the state Department of Transportation as a Cuomo-era financial
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is something that's been discussed for a number of years," Platt said.
"I don't see how this is a late development. It's been discussed all along."
</P>
<P>
	   Platt demurred Wednesday when pressed by legislators whether the toll
increase plan is dead.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have a board that makes that decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Tolls last increased on the Thruway in 1988, by 31 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0005 </TRAILER>
