<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three generations of black family see different Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Rev. Timothy Mitchell has led the fight for
civil rights most of his 69 years. Today, he finds the trial of four white
police officers accused of killing a black man is bringing back those most
heated conflicts, while bringing three generations of his family together.
<P>
	   For his son, the trial in the death of Amadou Diallo is a touchstone to the
early civil rights movement as well as tragic evidence of the serious threat to
younger black men like himself.
</P>
<P>
	   For the minister's grandson, the death was a tragic mistake.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think this was about racism," 12-year-old Preston Mitchell said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The three generations are part of the vigil outside the trial of New York
City officers charged with murder for gunning down Diallo one year ago in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   Timothy Mitchell, through gospel song, powerful oratory and sheer will, has
on most freezing days of the trial led groups from a dozen Harlem school
children to more than a hundred black and white adults from New York City to
Albany.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's justice, why I'm here" the grandfather roared to Wednesday's growing
lunchtime crowd. "These racists will kill you ... (and) who do they kill? Black
me!"
</P>
<P>
	   He's walked this road before. In the 1960s he preached and marched for civil
rights, drawing black men and women along the way in the movement's early days.
Now he's drawing on that experience, helping to organize Albany churches to feed
and house Diallo supporters bused from New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have the same spirit," he said on the last day of testimony. "That's how
we can win."
</P>
<P>
	   His son, the Rev. Timothy Immanuel Mitchell, 40, bristles at even the
tearful testimony of the police officers this week.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe the tears were legitimate, but they were tears of guilt, tears
of remorse," he said. "We have sympathy for the (Diallo) family and we do have a
sense of sympathy for the police out of love of God - what we learned from Dr.
King was to love our enemies."
</P>
<P>
	   But he says the enemy is beyond the four police officers who fired 41 shots
at Diallo - hitting him 19 times - outside his home.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't just blame the officers," he said. "What needs to be looked at and
what I don't see enough attention over is racial profiling."
</P>
<P>
	   The criminal justice system, he insists, should be on trial. He said New
York City's street crime units, of which the officers were part, see a black man
reach for a wallet, as Diallo apparently did, and police think it's a gun. A
white man reaches for his wallet and police think it's a wallet, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Preston Mitchell said he also wants justice served in the 22-year-old's
death. "But it's still sort of Amadou's fault, too. He should have stopped" when
the plainclothes police approached him, he said. "But they still didn't need to
gun him down."
</P>
<P>
	   "It wasn't about racism, it was a big mistake," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0006 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
