<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Forbids Pregnancy for Woman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- A woman convicted of endangering her unborn child by
taking drugs was ordered Wednesday not to get pregnant for ten years.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of her sentence, Dawn Marie Spinkle of Helena was instructed by
District Judge Dorothy McCarter to take a pregnancy test every two months. If
she tests positive, the judge said Sprinkle could be jailed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't want another damaged baby born because we didn't do enough to
supervise that woman,'' the judge said. ``If she wants to drug herself to death,
fine. But we can't have her taking drugs when she's pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sprinkle, 29, was given a three-year deferred sentence by McCarter last year
after she gave birth to a boy at St. Peter's Community Hospital in 1998. A urine
test conducted on the newborn indicated amphetamines in his system.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors claim Sprinkle violated several conditions of her sentence,
including not paying fines nor completing chemical dependency treatment, and
testing positive for drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   Had Sprinkle abided by the conditions imposed by the original sentence, the
conviction would have been wiped from her record.
</P>
<P>
	   The sentence imposed Wednesday puts Sprinkle under the supervision of the
Montana Department of Corrections for ten years with five years suspended. She
is expected to spend a portion of that time in boot camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
