<DOCNO> APW20000217.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philip Morris Starts Awareness Ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris USA, the nation's largest cigarette maker,
has begun a series of newspaper ads on tobacco related issues, such as underage
smoking and smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
	   "These ads are part of our company's ongoing commitment to communicate more
openly, honestly and directly with the American people about tobacco-related
issues," Philip Morris, which makes about half of the cigarettes sold in the
United States and is facing growing legal challenges, said in launching the ads
in major newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The maker of Marlboro and other brands said tobacco marketing was
"fundamentally changed" by the industry's 1998 multibillion-dollar settlement
agreement with the states over the costs of treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe opening this dialogue will help bring us more in accord with
public expectations of a responsible company in a changing world," the ad said.
</P>
<P>
	   The ads which occupy about a half page will appear frequently in The New
York Times, The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Post and USA Today as well
as in papers in major cities, the company said.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokeswoman Mary Carnovale declined to say how much money was being spent on
the ads, but said the company would like them to appear opposite the editorial
page.
</P>
<P>
	   The campaign is separate from a $100 million annual effort the tobacco
company started last year to deter youth smoking.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Morris Cos., the parent of Philip Morris USA, Kraft Foods and Miller
Brewing, started a separate $100 million campaign last October aimed at
improving its corporate image by reporting how it has helped disaster victims,
the hungry and abused women.
</P>
<P>
	   Tobacco companies remain the target of lawsuits by smokers, farmers and the
federal government, despite agreements to pay the states $246 billion over 25
years to settle claims for reimbursement for treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
	   A jury in state court in Florida has been asked to determine what damages
should be assessed against major tobacco makers after ruling last July that the
industry fraudulently conspired to produce a dangerous and defective product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
