<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccine Panel Changes Recommendation  </HEADLINE>
    By JAMES PILCHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- In a sign that cost is becoming a factor in making
immunization policy, a government advisory committee has changed its
recommendation to require fewer children to receive an expensive vaccine that
fights illnesses such as ear infections and meningitis.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center for Disease Control and Prevention's Advisory Committee on
Immunization Policy recommended Wednesday that the vaccine Prevenar should be
administered to all children under 2 and those under age 5 who are at high risk
of contracting the diseases.
</P>
<P>
	   In October, ACIP had voted to recommend Prevenar, which costs $232 per
four-dose series, for all children under 5.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only the second time the committee has ever debated the potential
economic impact of a vaccine, marking a potential shift in what medical experts
consider before making a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're having to look at cost more and more," said Dr. John Modlin,
committee chairman and a professor of pediatric medicine at Dartmouth
University.
</P>
<P>
	   But Dr. Paul Offit, a committee member who is chief of infectious diseases
at The Children's Hospital of Philadelphia, said, "That's basically trying to
find relative values in human life, even though everyone could benefit from it.
We need to recommend it first and figure out how to pay for it second."
</P>
<P>
	   That doesn't change the realities faced by the public and private sector
alike, especially with the hefty price tag, other committee members argued. The
federal government pays for about half of all immunizations.
</P>
<P>
	   Food and Drug Administration approval of the vaccine is expected this week,
and its manufacturer, American Home Products, will begin marketing it this
spring.
</P>
<P>
	   Prevenar fights the bacterium streptococcus pneumoniae -- the leading cause
of pneumonia, meningitis and the millions of ear infections that lead to crammed
pediatrician waiting rooms every year.
</P>
<P>
	   According to a study, the vaccine reduced ear infections by 9 percent.
Doctor visits by those who were diagnosed as having chronic ear infections and
took the vaccine were down 20 percent, and there was a 20 percent reduction in
the number of children who needed tube implants to fight the infections.
</P>
<P>
	   Paul Paradiso, vice president for scientific affairs for the division of
American Health that makes the vaccine, said that the sweeping scope of the
first set of guidelines was not expected and that the company is pleased with
the new recommendation.
</P>
<P>
	   "The numbers show that this is cost effective, since it reduces surgeries
and doctor's visits," added Paradiso, adding that the company has been working
on this vaccine since 1986.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Eric France, assistant chief of preventive medicine for the American
Association of Health Plans, said he believes that all managed care
organizations will cover the new vaccines despite the cost.
</P>
<P>
	   "But the membership of the ACIP needs to understand that cost is a factor
and needs to be taken into consideration along with safety and effectiveness,"
France said. "We need to make it part of the discussion before the initial
recommendations are made."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0058 </TRAILER>
