<DOCNO> APW20000217.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police officer cleared in shooting of teen-ager  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - On the last day of his life, 14-year-old Aquan
Salmon set out with three friends to buy yo-yos, but they instead purchased a
pair of gun-shaped cigarette lighters.
<P>
	   Police say those lighters were aimed at a mugging victim in the early
morning hours of April 13, 1999. A short time later, Officer Robert Allan
followed a car he believed was carrying armed suspects into a dark driveway in
the city's North End.
</P>
<P>
	   Eighty-eight seconds later Allan had shot Salmon dead. On Wednesday, after a
10-month investigation a special prosecutor ruled the shooting was justified.
</P>
<P>
	   "The shooting was over in a matter of seconds," said New London State's
Attorney Kevin Kane, who conducted the investigation. "To say the situation
Officer Allan was in was tense, uncertain and rapidly evolving is an
understatement."
</P>
<P>
	   Under state law, Kane said, Allan did not have to see Salmon with a weapon -
only to reasonably believe that his life was in danger when he fired one shot at
Salmon.
</P>
<P>
	   Although cleared of state charges, the officer's legal entanglements are far
from ended.
</P>
<P>
	   Kane's 200-page report has been turned over to the FBI's civil rights
division and the U.S. attorney for Connecticut. The city also is conducting its
own review.
</P>
<P>
	   Salmon's family would not comment. Allan could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a tragedy for (Salmon's) family, his friends and the entire
community," Kane told a news conference Wednesday at the State Armory. "People
chose sides quickly, and hopefully they will pause and examine the facts
presented in this report today."
</P>
<P>
	   Some paused to pray. A dozen North End residents gathered near the shooting
site Wednesday afternoon to reflect near the remnants of a makeshift memorial.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Cornell Lewis, pastor of the North End Church of Christ, led the
residents in prayer. Lewis, who is also a substance abuse and anger management
counselor, said people need to "vent" in a constructive way.
</P>
<P>
	   Kane and Public Safety Commissioner Henry Lee, a noted forensic expert,
outlined in detail the final minutes leading up to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Alone in his patrol car in the early morning hours of April 13, Allan was on
the lookout for a white Cadillac carrying suspects in the mugging. Witnesses
reported seeing four black males and two guns.
</P>
<P>
	   Allan spotted the car at 2:09 a.m. The Cadillac became hung up on a pile of
asphalt and the occupants began running from the car.
</P>
<P>
	   Allan, who said he thought he heard gunshots, gave chase. He said he saw
that the fleeing driver appeared to have a gun in his hand.
</P>
<P>
	   The gun-shaped cigarette lighters were recovered, one on the front seat of
the Cadillac and the other in the lot where Salmon was shot.
</P>
<P>
	   Salmon, a back seat passenger, was among the last to leave the car. He
approached Allan from behind, and began running past him on the right.
</P>
<P>
	   The officer ordered Salmon to stop and said the teen made a quick sweeping
motion toward his waistband. Allan fired one shot. Salmon was struck in the
upper left side of his back.
</P>
<P>
	   Allan's account of hearing gunshots could not be substantiated. Lee
concluded there was enough debris in the lot that anyone running across it could
make popping sounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the report was made public, investigators discussed the findings with
Salmon's family and community officials. Outside that meeting, a small group of
protesters chanted, "No justice, no peace."
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a lynching," said Kuba Assegai, a black businessman in the city. "We
want a police force who are there to serve the community, not bully the
community."
</P>
<P>
	   Allan has been on desk duty since the shooting. Acting Police Chief Deborah
Barrows would not comment on the report, but City Manager Saundra Kee-Borges
said Allan still faces a police review board and will remain on desk duty until
that probe is completed.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Mike Peters said deep wounds are still healing.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have to take a look at our procedures, sensitivity training and how we
approach situations like this so it doesn't happen again," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0101 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community unhappy, but not surprised, by exoneration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The city's blighted North End became a forum to
vent outrage over the results of a report that cleared a white police officer in
the shooting death of a 14-year-old black mugging suspect.
<P>
	   Before making public the findings Wednesday, state and city officials met at
a neighborhood church to brief the family of Aquan Salmon and selected community
leaders about why Officer Robert Allan was found innocent of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Hartford police department has to be changed because Officer Allan is
going back on the street," said the Rev. Henry Price. "He's been found not
guilty."
</P>
<P>
	   In the lot where Salmon was killed, a dozen people gathered during the
afternoon for an impromptu prayer.
</P>
<P>
	   They sought spiritual guidance - and expressed frustration over the decision
of special prosecutor Kevin Kane.
</P>
<P>
	   Carmen Melendez brought her 5-year-old daughter, Catalina, and her nieces
and nephews to what remains of a makeshift memorial to Salmon. Candles, a teddy
bear, broken statues and plastic flowers lay amid snow and mud. Spray-painted on
a brick wall were tributes to "Quanny."
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's messed up how the cop got off, because he's only a kid. He's
somebody's brother; somebody's baby," said Melendez, who lives in the
neighborhood where Salmon was killed on April 13.
</P>
<P>
	   The children placed their palms together and bowed their heads as they
recalled a boy they never met.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Cornell Lewis, pastor of the North End Church of Christ, came to
the scene "just trying to find certain people and let certain people find me to
offer counseling."
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis led the group in prayer.
</P>
<P>
	   "I pray also, Father, in the days and months to come, that if Officer Robert
Allan is guilty that you judge him," said Lewis. "We pray, Father, in your
divine justice that you not let this man go if he is guilty."
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis and others were frustrated at being kept out of a meeting earlier in
the day between investigators and Salmon's family. Had they been allowed inside,
they could have shared the information with others, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're asking the community to act crazy because they're shutting them
out," said Wendy Moore. "They create a who's-who. Everybody should be a
who's-who. It makes a difference when people can learn it for themselves."
</P>
<P>
	   Later in the evening, about two dozen people returned to Phillips
Metropolitan CME Church, where the morning meeting was held.
</P>
<P>
	   Other churches and a mosque in the North End opened their doors Wednesday
night as social workers joined clergy in an effort to address the needs of
residents.
</P>
<P>
	   City police were prepared for the worst, though no problems were reported
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Officers formed small teams to patrol the city. Cruisers were manned by a
driver, a supervisor, a video technician and a specially trained
disorder-control or emergency-response officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
