<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Businessman points to pressure to fund campaigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The Rowland administration says there is no truth
to a Mystic businessman's claim that he was pressured to give $30,000 to a "high
ranking" state Treasury official in exchange for a state business loan.
<P>
	   John Haggerty gave few details to the Legislature's Government
Administration and Elections Committee during a public hearing on campaign
finance reform Wednesday, but said the payoff was to be funneled to political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he never handed over the money and was denied the loan by the
Department of Economic and Community Development.
</P>
<P>
	   DECD spokesman Jim Watson said the agency worked with Haggerty and decided
not to give him financial assistance. He dismissed Haggerty's accusation of a
political quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
	   "His accusation is without any merit and not based on fact," Watson said.
"It's well known that this agency does not operate in that fashion."
</P>
<P>
	   Haggerty said that after meeting with Department of Economic and Community
Development Commissioner James Abromaitis on Feb. 16, 1999, he was "introduced
to a former high ranking state treasury official."
</P>
<P>
	   He refused to identify the official, and said he has not shared his
accusation with any law enforcement agents.
</P>
<P>
	   "In that meeting, this person told me I would need to supply $30,000 so he
could get Gov. (John G.) Rowland to approve the project," Haggerty said. "He
said the money would be used to fund campaigns. I was also told how the funds
should be handled. I am not suggesting that this individual was acting on
instruction from the governor. However, I was shocked, disgusted and afraid."
</P>
<P>
	   Haggerty is the former owner of C.C. Bagel Company, a chain which had
several stores throughout New London County. He applied for state aid in 1997 to
market several products under the Mystic Seaport name - including soda, beer and
clam chowder.
</P>
<P>
	   Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani said Haggerty's claims are without merit.
</P>
<P>
	   "The governor would not be involved in approving a project like this,
anyway," Pagani said. "It would be done at the agency level. It doesn't make
sense. What he's saying happened wasn't even in an election year."
</P>
<P>
	   About seven months after Haggerty's meeting with Abromaitis, former state
Treasurer Paul Silvester pleaded guilty to federal racketeering and
money-laundering charges related to his failed 1998 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Silvester admitted to investing state pension money with companies in
exchange for kickbacks to himself, his family and his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The Legislature is considering two campaign finance reform plans which call
for different campaign spending caps. Both plans would allow residents to fund
campaigns through checkoffs on their state income tax return. The system would
take money away from the individual's refund, rather than use money out of the
state's General Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   Both plans call for public financing of races for governor and
constitutional offices such as attorney general and treasurer. Neither plan
includes public financing of legislative races.
</P>
<P>
	   Some leading Republicans say it will be impossible to publicly fund
campaigns with voluntary checkoffs, and argued that capping campaign spending
infringes on free speech.
</P>
<P>
	   "I really think they are all attempts to limit political speech, which I
find too precious," said House Minority Leader Robert Ward, R-Northfield. "The
weighing and balancing ought not to be focused on limiting free speech."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0103 </TRAILER>
