<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Want U.N. Peacekeepers  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- African nations are lobbying to get thousands of U.N.
peacekeepers on the ground quickly to support a shaky cease-fire in Congo -- but
many council members first want to be certain that fighting has stopped and
there really is a peace to keep.
</P>
<P>
	   French U.N. Ambassador Alain Dejammet said prospects for getting thousands
of peacekeepers into Congo in the near future ``are dim.''
</P>
<P>
	   The rebel campaign to oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila has drawn in
six countries and has threatened the stability of central Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a cease-fire signed last summer in Lusaka, Zambia, by supporters and
opponents of Kabila, both sides have been accused of repeated violations. And
there have been no moves to withdraw foreign forces from Congo as called for in
the Lusaka accord.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't think there is a great deal of enthusiasm to see a U.N.
peacekeeping force deployed to -- how shall I put it -- anchor an invading force
in the country,'' said Canada's U.N. ambassador, Robert Fowler.
</P>
<P>
	   He was referring to troops from Uganda and Rwanda who are supporting rebel
forces in parts of eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
	   As an initial step, the Security Council last August authorized the
deployment of 90 military liaison officers to countries involved in the
conflict: Congo and its backers -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- as well as
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
	   But it took months to get 79 officers in the field, and they have been
barred from key sites, especially in government-held areas.
</P>
<P>
	   Next week, the Security Council is almost certain to approve a long-delayed
second step to cool the Congo conflict -- sending 500 military observers and
over 5,000 logistics and security personnel to support them. The vote is
expected on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S.-sponsored resolution calls for observers to monitor implementation
and lay the groundwork for possible deployment of a much larger U.N.
peacekeeping force, which is called for in the Lusaka agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   But there is still uncertainty about when the military observers will arrive
in Congo. And the Security Council was very vague about possible deployment of
peacekeepers, saying in late January that it intends to consider preparations
``at the appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lobbying Congress on Tuesday to support the military observer mission, U.S.
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said deployment would begin only when key
conditions are met, including security, access, and the parties' cooperation
with U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
	   Approval of a follow-up peacekeeping force ``is not automatic,'' he
stressed, and will depend on the parties observing the Lusaka accord and
withdrawing forces from confrontation lines, as well as progress on a ``national
dialogue'' in Congo.
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke reiterated that U.N. peacekeepers would not enforce the Lusaka
accord or forcibly disarm the rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   Echoing his concerns, Russian U.N. Ambassador Sergey Lavrov said ``a lot
depends on the willingness of the parties -- which should be demonstrated -- to
abide by the Lusaka agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   Dejammet said ``the real, rational, logical'' action after a cease-fire is
secured would be for the United Nations to try to establish a buffer force along
the borders between Congo and Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But it would cost money. It would require a lot of people. And at this
very moment, if we are realistic, it's obvious that it's uneasy to foresee such
a development in a not too far away time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Senior U.N. officials said last August that a minimum of 25,000 soldiers
would be needed for a peacekeeping force in Congo, which is the size of the
United States east of the Mississippi River. The U.N. peacekeeping department is
reported to be working on scenarios with different force sizes, but no numbers
have been released. African leaders say a large force is needed to restore
peace.
</P>
<P>
	   Congolese U.N. Ambassador Andre Kapanga said Wednesday that his government
wants a U.N. buffer force on its border -- but it also wants U.N. troops to help
move Rwandan and Ugandan forces out of the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Namibia's U.N. ambassador, Martin Andjaba, believes once the U.N. observer
mission arrives, the Security Council will have to increase it to a full
peacekeeping operation in order to restore peace to central Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting Holbrooke's focus on Africa, and especially the Congo, in January, he
said ``Africans want the United States to take the lead'' in getting a Congo
peacekeeping force quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0105 </TRAILER>
