<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Korean Stamp Barred From Show  </HEADLINE>
   By AMALIE YOUNG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The federal government has canceled plans by an
international stamp dealer to sell rare postage stamps for the North Korean
government at a collectors' show.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the Trading with the Enemy Act, selling stamps from the communist
nation in the United States is illegal, according to the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These stamps are subject to the embargo'' against Communist North Korea,
said an agency spokeswoman, who declined to give her name. ``There is no
exception.''
</P>
<P>
	   The stamp dealer, Mark Dianda of Oakland, Calif., says the American
Philatelic Society gave him permission to sell the stamps at its three-day show
this weekend in Portland.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, North Korea appointed Dianda its agent to sell stamps in the
United States. Since then, he has been selling them over the Internet for 75
cents to $2 each.
</P>
<P>
	   Dianda said that under his agreement, the North Korean government gets some
of the proceeds and he gets the rest. He did not provide the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
	   Dianda said he has sold North Korean stamps in the United States before, and
he doesn't understand the fuss this time.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's not like I'm trading nuclear secrets,'' he said Wednesday. ``It's
really annoying that I can't sell them.''
</P>
<P>
	   Dianda says he will display the stamps at the Portland show, but he won't
try to sell them. The stamps depict sports events in preparation for the Sydney
Olympics; animals including ducks, cats and butterflies; and a copy of a 10th
century Korean mural to commemorate the Year of the Dragon.
</P>
<P>
	   Dianda said he thought he could sell the North Korean stamps because he had
seen press releases and newspaper articles that indicated trade sanctions
against the country had been relaxed.
</P>
<P>
	   Although President Clinton eased some sanctions against the Asian nation in
September, it is still a closed nation, and commercial sales of its stamps are
forbidden in this country.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's kind of a disappointment; I like that sort of stuff myself as a
collector,'' said Bob Lamb, executive director of the philatelic society. ``I'd
like to get some, but I'm not going to break the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
