<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamaican Parliament Approves Deal  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Jamaica's parliament approved the end of the
island's telephone monopoly, but opponents threatened to block the deal in
court, saying the planned deregulation is too slow.
</P>
<P>
	   The parliament passed legislation Wednesday night finalizing a deal struck
by the government with Cable and Wireless Jamaica for opening the
telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the deal, full competition will be instituted in phases over three
years in all areas, including international calls. During the transition, the
government will heavily regulate sectors where the British-based Cable and
Wireless remains dominant.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement, reached in September, voids a 1988 deal that granted the
company's government-owned predecessor a 25-year monopoly with guaranteed annual
profits of 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Debate over the deal has been a focus of interest for other former and
current British Caribbean territories with Cable and Wireless monopolies.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents -- including local Internet companies, consumer groups and a local
civil rights group -- charge the long transition stifles competition by giving
Cable and Wireless an insurmountable head-start over potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
	   During two days of parliamentd debate, opposition Labor Party lawmakers
echoed those complaints.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It gives this multinational, United Kingdom company privileges and bonuses
that are incomprehensible'' said Labor Party leader Edward Seaga, who called the
agreement ``a sweetheart deal.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will challenge it in court,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmaker Andrew Holness said the bill allowed ``industrial espionage'' by
giving Cable and Wireless the right to inspect equipment used by competitors to
transmit data overseas to ensure that it is not being used illegally for
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
	   Industry, Commerce and Technology Minister Philip Paulwell brushed aside the
charges. ``This bill represents a tremendous leap into the technological
world,'' he said. ``We are going to see the tremendous benefits from competition
that will flow.''
</P>
<P>
	   Paulwell said it paves the way for foreign investment worth millions of
dollars that will create thousands of jobs for the economically depressed
island.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said the agreement would bring telephones to isolated communities
and would allow the government to provide Internet access in every post
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0039 </DOCNO>
