<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Fail To Dent Belfast Deadlock  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The prime ministers of Britain and Ireland have vowed to
steer Northern Ireland's feuding politicians back into government together, but
admit they don't yet know how.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not going to pretend that this is not a difficult situation, because
it is,'' British leader Tony Blair said Wednesday night after he and Irish Prime
Minister Bertie Ahern spoke to key politicians in the province's suspended
power-sharing Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
	   The diplomacy inside Blair's London residence failed to move either the
IRA-linked Sinn Fein party or the province's major Protestant party, the Ulster
Unionists. They remained entrenched on opposite sides of an argument over when,
if ever, the outlawed Irish Republican Army should disarm in support of the
province's 1998 peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ball is still firmly in their court,'' said Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sinn Fein can't make peace on our own,'' countered Gerry Adams, the
party's leader.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ulster Unionists in November accepted an American-brokered deal that
required them to form the four-party Cabinet in expectation that the IRA would
disarm in response. But the outlawed group offered no firm commitments to a
disarmament commission last month, triggering the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain, determined to forestall the Cabinet's total collapse, took powers
away from the coalition Friday and resumed direct control. The move deterred the
Ulster Unionists from resigning their posts, as they had threatened.
</P>
<P>
	   It also provoked the IRA -- which had offered a vague but promising proposal
to the province's disarmament commission -- to retaliate by retracting that
submission and breaking off contact with the commission.
</P>
<P>
	   That has left Northern Ireland's peace process in the familiar Catch-22 that
blocked the Cabinet's formation for more than a year. The IRA and Ulster
Unionists are both demanding the other side make the next painful move.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair pledged that in the coming days of negotiations in Belfast, Dublin and
London the dilemma would be untangled.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The one thing I am sure of, having met all the parties, is that none of
them really wants to see this agreement fall. All of them know it is the only
way forward,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``None of us wanted to suspend the institutions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair was referring to the Cabinet, the 108-member Belfast legislature from
which it was drawn, and six policy-making committees that linked the governments
in Northern Ireland with the Irish Republic. All were stripped of power Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, President Clinton said it was unfortunate that the IRA hadn't
maintained contact with the disarmament commission. He conceded that the peace
process faced ``a rough patch'' with no clear outcome.
</P>
<P>
	   But Clinton cited the apparent strength of the IRA's 1997 cease-fire as a
bright spot.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The IRA has given no indication whatever that they will revert to
violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sinn Fein's Adams warned that other parties were taking his influence over
IRA policy for granted at a dangerous moment.
</P>
<P>
	   He said it had proved extremely difficult to persuade the IRA to open
disarmament talks at all, ``and the IRA's voluntary initiative was thrown back
in its face.''
</P>
<P>
	   As long as Britain withheld powers from the Cabinet in Belfast, Sinn Fein
``cannot play a useful and constructive role in resolving the arms issue,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
