<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvia Wants Extradition Treaty  </HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN C. JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RIGA, Latvia (AP) -- Latvian prosecutors are pushing to conclude an
extradition treaty with Australia to speed the handover of 86-year-old Nazi war
crimes suspect Konrads Kalejs if he is indicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Jewish groups have pressured Latvia to extradite Kalejs -- accused of
involvement in atrocities during Germany's 1941-44 occupation of Latvia -- for
trial after he was found by Nazi hunters in a retirement home in Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs, who was deported from the United States and Canada in the 1990s for
lying about his wartime record, returned in January to Australia, where he has
had citizenship since 1957.
</P>
<P>
	   Latvian officials have said they do not have sufficient witnesses or
evidence to indict Kalejs and invited investigators from the United States,
Canada, Australia, Great Britain, Germany and Israel to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can promise that we will see to it that all war criminals are called to
liability,'' Justice Minister Valdis Birkavs said Wednesday as the conference
opened. ``Latvia has a strong political will for this.''
</P>
<P>
	   Jewish leaders, who have criticized Latvia for not convicting a single Nazi
since it gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, welcomed the
conference but said they remained skeptical and were disappointed that they had
not been invited.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our feeling is that this might be a very positive step but the jury is
still out,'' said Efraim Zuroff, director of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
	   In Moscow, Russian foreign ministry officials also complained that they
weren't invited, saying the talks should involve all parties that suffered from
Nazism, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Latvian officials said they asked Australia to help overcome
``bureaucratic delays'' on both sides that were hampering agreement on an
extradition treaty, foreign ministry spokesman Janis Silis said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We intend to do all we can to sign an extradition treaty, but we need
efforts from both sides,'' he said, adding that agreement could be reached in
four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Jewish groups say Kalejs was involved in World War II massacres as a
lieutenant in the Arajs Kommando, a notorious Nazi-sponsored death squad staffed
mainly by Latvians. The unit is said to have murdered some 30,000 Latvian Jews.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs has said he was ordered by German officers to head an Arajs Kommando
unit, but he has denied being present when civilians were shot.
</P>
<P>
	   In total, 80,000 Jews perished during the Nazi occupation, most within the
first year of German rule. Germans planned and ordered the massacres, but
Latvian Nazis often carried out the actual killings.
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks ago, the Simon Wiesenthal Center, which tracks people accused of
atrocities against Jews, provided Latvian officials with the names of seven
former Arajs men who could testify against Kalejs.
</P>
<P>
	   Zuroff said testimony from these men would be key in indicting Kalejs. He
also said the center was examining new evidence linking Kalejs to a labor camp.
</P>
<P>
	   After regaining independence from Moscow following the 1991 Soviet collapse,
Latvia vowed to pursue and prosecute alleged agents of Nazi- and Stalinist-era
crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   But while Latvia has indicted or convicted nearly a dozen men for Stalinist
crimes, mainly for participating in mass deportations to Siberia, no alleged
Nazis have been tried. The Soviet Union did execute several hundred Nazi war
criminals in Latvia immediately after World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
