<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-bank exec, husband plead guilty in Russian money-laundering  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Russian bankers whose clients wanted to escape taxes and
erase the trail of their income set up an illegal bank in the United States with
the help of an executive of the Bank of New York, the executive says.
<P>
	   Before U.S. law enforcement authorities shut it down, the four-year
operation had processed more than $7 billion from Russia, including $300,000 in
ransom money for a kidnapping in Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucy Edwards, 41, and Peter Berlin, 46, admitted they arranged one of the
biggest money laundering schemes in U.S. history as they pleaded guilty to
federal charges Wednesday in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   The pleas were the first major admissions of wrongdoing since the
investigation caused an international scandal last August and strained relations
between Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis D. Schiliro, assistant director of the FBI's New York office, called
the pleas a significant development but said "much remains to be done" in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Standing side by side, the couple each told a federal judge how they used
Edwards' position as a vice president in the bank's Eastern European division to
help Russian bankers launder the money.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators believe most of the money came from Russian importers trying
to avoid taxes, though they are looking into whether some came from Russian
mobsters. The matter was not directly addressed in court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But a prosecutor mentioned the ransom money, and Edwards said the bankers
she teamed up with in 1995 at the Russian bank DKB had some sinister
connections.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was aware that personnel for DKB were on occasion in fear of their
customers and afraid to leave the bank because they said customers with machine
guns were waiting for them," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards also said Russian banking officials were accomplices in the scam.
The administration of former President Boris Yeltsin has called the Bank of New
York allegations a creation by the West to tarnish Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards and Berlin, a Russian businessman, surrendered to the FBI on Tuesday
after flying to New York from London, where they had been living.
</P>
<P>
	   They could face up to 10 years in prison at sentencing on May 3 but could
get lesser sentences by identifying others involved. They also agreed to
surrender more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
	   T. Barry Kingham, an attorney for Edwards and Berlin, said the couple will
keep cooperating with investigators. "They are anxious to fulfill their
obligations here and resume a normal life," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dressed in black and smiling frequently during the hearing, Edwards
described creating an illegal banking network for Russians - without required
licenses - that was run through accounts at the Bank of New York. The Bank of
New York was not accused of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Money laundering involves moving deposits through a series of accounts to
disguise their illicit source. In this case, Edwards and her husband set up
accounts at Bank of New York and then sifted the money through shell companies
in New York City and Jersey City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   The bank provided the companies with software that was then used by the
Russians to transfer money, cheating the Russian government out of customs
duties and tax revenue, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards said she "suspected the accounts were being used by many people for
illicit purposes."
</P>
<P>
	   In exchange, Edwards and her husband were paid $1.8 million, a percentage of
the money being moved, she said. "We were paid substantial commissions for doing
very little work," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   They said they shifted the money to offshore accounts to avoid reporting the
income and paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards also said that after the couple moved to London in 1996, they paid a
Bank of New York employee, Svetlana Kudryavtsev, $500 a month to make sure the
accounts were operating properly.
</P>
<P>
	   Kudryavtsev was indicted last month on perjury charges for allegedly lying
to a federal grand jury about whether she or her husband had ever received money
or loans from Edwards. Kudryavtsev's lawyer has said any money she received was
a product of her friendship with Edwards.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards also admitted she used her position at the Bank of New York to help
hundreds of Russians, most of them affiliated with the Russian banking industry,
to enter the United States illegally.
</P>
<P>
	   The couple pleaded guilty to charges including conspiracy to commit money
laundering and operating an unlawful banking business. Each will remain free on
$500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
	   An alleged accomplice in the money transfers, Aleskey Volkov, remains a
fugitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
