<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Both Parties Push Seniors' Concerns  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress is rushing to pass legislation allowing Social
Security recipients over age 65 to work and keep all their benefits. Democrats
and Republicans are bickering over Medicare prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   There is little doubt both parties view the elderly vote as crucial to their
electoral success in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The senior vote is the battleground for who gets control of the House,''
said Dan Maffei, spokesman for Democrats on the House Ways and Means Committee.
Republicans hold a 222-211 majority in the current House, with two independents
-- one in the Republican orbit, the other aligned with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   The odds appear long that Congress will make progress on the biggest of
senior citizen issues: ensuring the long-term financial solvency of Medicare and
Social Security and giving people new options to invest for retirement. So
lawmakers are focusing on lesser steps that would demonstrate some
accomplishment for voters or provide a campaign issue if compromise is not
possible.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Everybody knows somebody who can't afford prescription drugs,'' said Rep.
Ronnie Shows, D-Miss.
</P>
<P>
	   After languishing for years, bipartisan legislation ending the Social
Security earnings limit is on the fast track in the House, and President Clinton
is promising to sign it into law. The bill would scrap a Depression-era law that
takes away $1 in benefits for every $3 a person age 65-69 earns over $17,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
	   One reason that elimination of the earnings limit has never passed before is
that sponsors of broader Social Security reform wanted to use it as a
``sweetener'' to attract more support for that effort. Now, the bill is expected
to reach the House floor in March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At least we are moving some Social Security reform forward,'' said Rep. E.
Clay Shaw, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
	   But some lawmakers question this approach -- similar to what House GOP
leaders are doing with a series of tax cuts -- of moving only one popular item
through Congress instead of tackling the larger problem head-on.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It essentially represents an 'eat-dessert-first' approach to reform,''
said Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, who nonetheless supports the bill. ``Congress
should be grappling with the tough choices of how to extend Social Security
solvency.''
</P>
<P>
	   While the Social Security earnings limit bill has a good chance of becoming
law, Republicans and Democrats seem less likely to settle on a Medicare
prescription drug benefit. Republicans believe Democrats will oppose any
compromise, preferring to use costly prescription drugs as a potent political
issue.
</P>
<P>
	   But House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said Wednesday that the ``health of
Americans is more important than politics'' and accused GOP leaders of using the
election as an excuse for no action.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Instead of just looking toward our own campaigns, we need a campaign for
seniors' health care,'' the Missouri Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic leaders on Wednesday began trying to force House consideration of
two bills intended to lower the costs of prescription drugs through group
purchasing power and to add an outpatient drug benefit for the 39 million people
who now receive Medicare. Democrats would have to get 218 signatures on
petitions to get the bills to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
	   But the bills are opposed by some Democrats and most Republicans, as well as
by a coalition led by the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America
-- the lobbying group responsible for the television ad campaign featuring
``Flo,'' the bowler who urges a bipartisan solution. Critics say the Democratic
bills amount to government-imposed price controls and a costly burden on the
already-faltering Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
	   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has asked the Commerce and Ways and
Means committees to work on a solution, but the GOP is divided on whether to
hold out for broader Medicare reform or concentrate on the prescription drug
issue alone.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're working on it. We haven't made that decision yet,'' Hastert said in
an interview. ``We want to find the best way to do it. I'd prefer that we have a
bipartisan effort.''
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans say any prescription drug measure should avoid putting Medicare
in further financial jeopardy, be targeted to help the neediest senior citizens
and avoid putting the government in charge. But Democrats say such restrictions
could make the bill meaningless.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would be so focused, and so surgical, that it doesn't help many people
at all,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- The Medicare bills are H.R. 664 and H.R. 1495. The Social
Security earnings limit elimination bill is H.R. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
