<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standards Fall in S. Carolina Race  </HEADLINE>
   By LEIGH STROPE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- If negative campaigning consists of two Republican
presidential candidates sniping and swiping and pointing fingers over who is
more unpleasant, then politics South Carolina-style must resemble the World
Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain compares Gov. George W. Bush to President Clinton --
considered the ultimate insult among Republicans. Bush suggests McCain is more
like Clinton. Each accuses the other of distorting positions on taxes and Social
Security and breaking promises.
</P>
<P>
	   But this is the state where, in 1998, a U.S. senator told an opponent who
called for a courteous campaign to ``kiss my fanny.'' That same year, the
campaign for governor was inundated with cash from gambling interests as charges
flew about who was beholden to the industry.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This presidential primary looks like a kindergarten show,'' said Clemson
University political scientist Dave Woodard, a Republican consultant. ``They're
talking about the fact that they've really gone negative -- and they're talking
about economic plans.''
</P>
<P>
	   In an abrupt change of strategy last week, McCain pulled ads critical of
Bush after advisers determined they were hurting his image as a reformer. McCain
urged Bush to do the same. He refused, saying the Arizona senator's suggestion
was a ``bait-and-switch trick.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite all of the talk about taking the high road, both men bickered
through a debate Tuesday, which prompted Alan Keyes -- who sat between them --
to remark on their ``pointless squabbling.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush complained about a McCain ad comparing him to Clinton. McCain
complained about a Bush supporter who accused him of abandoning veterans. Bush
said McCain's tax plan represented the Washington mentality. McCain shot back
that his plan was ``the grown-up mentality.''
</P>
<P>
	   All this in happening in a state where two years ago Sen. Ernest ``Fritz''
Hollings, D-S.C., told then-Rep. Bob Inglis where to stick his idea of a
courteous campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He finesses all around,'' Hollings said. ``He is Jack be nimble, Jack be
quick. He's all around the damn clock, so oozing and goozing and such a nice
little choirboy and so pleasant, and everybody's rude, and he wants to be
courteous. He is a ... damn skunk. I can tell you that right now.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hollings was re-elected to his seventh term.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor's race wasn't much nicer. Incumbent Republican David Beasley
accused Democratic challenger Jim Hodges of being a tool of gambling interests
and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
	   Those gambling interests, angry that Beasley wanted to ban video poker,
showered Democrats with cash and mounted their own campaign against the
governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Beasley lost his bid for a second term.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Legislature has battled bitterly for years about whether to remove
the Confederate flag from atop Statehouse. One state senator recently called the
NAACP, which is pushing a tourism boycott of the state until the flag comes
down, ``the National Association for Retarded people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Back in 1978, a congressional campaign turned ugly when a third-party
candidate criticized Democrat Max Heller, an Austrian-born Jew, for not
believing in Jesus Christ. Voters also were asked in a poll paid for by former
Gov. Carroll Campbell, who was running for the seat, to choose from six
characteristics that best described the men. Among them, ``a Jewish immigrant''
and ``a native South Carolinian.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is nothing,'' Lucinda Stephens, a Mount Pleasant teacher, said of the
presidential politics. ``We've seen some real mudslinging.''
</P>
<P>
	   In New Hampshire, Bush and McCain called each other friend. They shook hands
in Michigan, promising they would not run negative ads.
</P>
<P>
	   But that was all before Bush's big loss to McCain in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Playing into Bush's newly aggressive strategy is probably the realization
that ``going negative'' in South Carolina isn't necessarily a bad thing, Woodard
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, South Carolinians like a good fight for their votes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't like wallflowers,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., a McCain
supporter. ``We want people to defend their positions, to go at it, boys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
