<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Optimistic in South Carolina  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FLORENCE, S.C. (AP) -- Despite spending more money than he had hoped to and
watching Sen. John McCain pick up endorsements from his former supporters, Gov.
George W. Bush is exuding confidence as he heads toward Saturday's pivotal South
Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You see, it's the beginning of the end of the Clinton era in Washington,''
the Republican presidential front-runner said Wednesday night in a warmly
received speech before about 3,500 people at the University of South Carolina at
Aiken.
</P>
<P>
	   But looking down the road to replacing President Clinton may be premature.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to the Texas governor acknowledged his campaign had burned through $50
million of its unprecedented $70 million campaign kitty by the end of January.
Since Bush's loss to the Arizona senator Feb. 1 in New Hampshire, the campaign
has been spending more than $3 million per week.
</P>
<P>
	   He had $20 million remaining as of Jan. 31 -- double the amount in McCain's
warchest. But McCain's campaign said it was trying to close the money gap and
was raising $150,000 to $200,000 every day through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Bush watched as the former governor of Washington state,
the highest elected Republican officeholder in California and former
presidential rival Gary Bauer all jumped on McCain's bandwagon. Another backer
said he was rethinking his support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In Washington state, former Gov. Dan Evans said he switched from Bush to
McCain, a former Senate colleague, because of negative attacks from Bush's camp
and McCain's ``courageous fire.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- In California, Secretary of State Bill Jones said he switched because
some South Carolina Republicans were sending the message that ``your vote
doesn't count as an independent or crossover unless you vote for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- In South Carolina, Bauer, who quit the race two weeks ago, endorsed
McCain at a rally at Furman University, saying he was the GOP's ``best shot'' at
winning the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also was dealt a blow by Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., who said he was
``reconsidering my support'' because of Bush's appearance at Bob Jones
University. The school bans interracial dating and its leadership has harshly
criticized the Catholic church, actions that King said were hard to defend and
made Bush seem ``almost blind to Catholic sensibilities.''
</P>
<P>
	   Addressing the switch by Jones, Bush said: ``If he's interested in being on
the team that's going to win the Republican nomination, he made the wrong
decision.''
</P>
<P>
	   The candidate, and some staffers, expressed a stay-the-course optimism.
Aides were planning a series of fund-raisers next month to replenish their
campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush himself said: ``I know we're on plan. We've got a strategy that's
working. But my intense focus is on turning out a vote here in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, who has sworn off negative ads, began airing a campaign-closing TV
spot designed to convince Republicans here that he can defeat both Bush and the
Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
	   The upbeat ad features adoring crowds, patriotic images and a voiceover
calling McCain ``a Republican like Ronald Reagan who can win.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, whose campaign has grown increasingly aggressive, began a new ad
accusing McCain of unfounded negative attacks and waffling on public financing
of congressional elections, which both candidates say they oppose.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain rolled through inland South Carolina from town meeting to town
meeting, beaming confidence and arguing that he'll press ahead regardless of the
outcome Saturday. He said ``the polls show us in the margin of error'' and he
hoped for a backlash against Bush's negative ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Tom Trammell of Greenville, where McCain went for a book signing event, said
the campaigning had prompted him to change from Bush to McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was a Bush supporter until a couple of weeks ago, but I got turned off
by all the negative campaigning,'' he said. ``I'm impressed by McCain's
character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0141 </TRAILER>
