<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill Helps Small Businesses  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House has voted to protect small businesses from
crippling lawsuits, but like other product liability bills approved in the past
it faces an uncertain future in the Senate and a promised presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
	   Voting mainly along party lines, the House on Wednesday approved a bill,
221-193, under which small businesses would have to pay no more than $250,000 in
punitive damages, or three times compensatory damages, whichever is less, in
most civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   Exceptions are made to the cap when the defendant purposely tries to cause
harm or the misconduct involves such acts as violent crime, terrorism or civil
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill also exempts small businesses from joint and several liability,
where one defendant only partially liable for non-economic damages such as pain
and suffering can end up paying all damages. And all retailers, big and small,
are free from legal responsibility for defective goods they receive from
manufacturers but do not alter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For too long, America's small businesses have lived under a cloud of
fear'' of frivolous lawsuits, said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif. the bill's chief
sponsor. He cited a survey finding that 20 percent of small businesses decide
against expanding services or hiring new employees out of fear of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need this kind of national standard to return the courts to being
agents of justice instead of lotteries for trial lawyers looking to hit the
jackpot,'' said Mike Baroody, senior vice president at the National Association
of Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
	   Rogan's bill focused on small businesses in hopes of avoiding the fierce
opposition that broader product liability bills have faced from trial lawyers
and consumer groups, two key Democratic constituencies. President Clinton in
1996 vetoed a major product liability bill crafted as part of the GOP ``Contract
with America.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the White House, in a statement, said Clinton's senior advisers would
recommend a veto because, despite the narrow scope suggested in its title, it
would bring about sweeping changes to state laws and ``strand a large number of
injured plaintiffs.''
</P>
<P>
	   It said the limits on joint and several liability would ``fall most harshly
on the poor, the elderly and children -- those persons likely to suffer less
economic harm and more non-economic harm from the wrongful conduct of others.''
</P>
<P>
	   Before getting to the president's desk the bill must still win passage in
the Senate, where Democrats have been more successful in blocking changes to
liability law.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the ranking Democrat on the House Judiciary
Committee, also faulted the bill for defining a small business only by number of
employees, not revenue. Some companies with fewer than 25 employees do hundreds
of millions or billions of dollars in business, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   A Conyers amendment that would have confined the bill to businesses making
less than $5 million annually and applying product liability protections to only
small business retailers was defeated, 237-178.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., also argued that the legislation would protect
some gunmakers, including the makers of the guns used in the Columbine high
school shootings, from lawsuits. Rogan said his bill would do nothing to stop a
claimant from seeking economic damages -- or non-economic damages if there is an
intentional wrong -- from a gun manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITORS' NOTE -- The bill number is H.R. 2366.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Die in Calif. Cargo Plane Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOWARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RANCHO CORDOVA, Calif. (AP) -- A DC-8 cargo plane crashed into an automobile
wrecking yard while trying to make an emergency landing Wednesday, bursting into
flames and killing the three crew members aboard the aircraft, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Those on board the Emery Worldwide plane were dead by the time fire crews
arrived at the site about 1 mile east of Mather Field, said fire Capt. Dan
Haverty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was no chance of rescue,'' Haverty said.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane carried three crew members: the pilot, first captain and a flight
engineer, all believed to be Emery employees, said company spokesman James
Allen.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot reported unsecured cargo shortly after the plane took off, Haverty
said. The plane's manifest listed clothing, automatic transmission fluid and a
small amount of unknown detonating devices, he said. The airline said the
devices were 0.009 kilograms of fuses used to activate automobile air bags.
</P>
<P>
	   The crash set as many as 200 cars on fire and caused explosions over a
200-yard-long area.
</P>
<P>
	   Flight 17 had taken off at 7:50 p.m., bound for Dayton, Ohio, and the pilot
immediately called back to the airfield's departure control and told them he had
a severe problem with balance of the aircraft, said Jim Whitehead, manager of
the Federal Aviation Administration's regional operations center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane hit the ground ``in a ball of fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Motorist Ernie Killinger said the plane hit belly-first.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was like he was crash-landing,'' said Killinger, who was on his way
home. ``I saw the front half of the fuselage come out of the flames and the
cockpit was straight up and it just rocked back and forth until it was engulfed
by the flames.''
</P>
<P>
	   There were no immediate reports of injuries on the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   FAA investigators, a bomb squad and a hazardous materials team were among
those on the scene.
</P>
<P>
	   The McDonnell Douglas DC-8 has two engines mounted on each wing. The model
went into service in 1959 and production ended in 1972.
</P>
<P>
	   Mather Field was once known as Mather Air Force Base, which was closed as a
military operation in 1993. Since then, it has become a civilian airport and the
region's air cargo hub. It is located about 10 miles east of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   Emery, based in Redwood City, specializes in transportation services for
business shippers of heavyweight cargo, the company says on its Web site. The
$2.4-billion company is a subsidiary of CNF Inc., a $5.6-billion diversified
transportation company based in Palo Alto, the site states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0145 </TRAILER>
