<DOCNO> APW20000217.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Looks to India, Pakistan Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is leaving the door open -- slightly --
to making a visit to Pakistan and offering to help mediate the volatile Kashmir
dispute Pakistan has with India.
</P>
<P>
	   Since India never has accepted outside intervention, the president's offer
at a news conference Wednesday to intercede as he has in the Arab-Israeli
dispute and in Northern Ireland is probably academic.
</P>
<P>
	   But asked whether he would be willing, Clinton responded, ``absolutely, I
would,'' and then said ``unless we are asked by both parties to help, we can't
get involved.''
</P>
<P>
	   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over disputed Kashmir. Their
simmering dispute over the part of the Himalayan state controlled by India is
considered even more dangerous now that they both have exploded nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton intends to visit India, the world's largest democracy, and also
Bangladesh in March, but has made no decision on Pakistan. This week, Sandy
Berger, his assistant for national security affairs, met with several experts on
the region at the White House to discuss the pros and cons of a presidential
visit.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he would base his decision on what would best serve U.S.
interests in trying to stop ``a nuclear arms race.''
</P>
<P>
	   There is a precedent for going to India and not to Pakistan. President
Carter did that in 1978.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that Pakistan is under military rule and is suspected of supporting
terrorist groups that attack Hindus in Kashmir weighs against a presidential
visit.
</P>
<P>
	   Pakistan sent a cabinet minister, Omar Asghar Khan, here this week to try to
neutralize U.S. concerns about terrorism and anti-democratic trends.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Pervez Musharraf, Pakistan's military ruler, urged Clinton earlier this
month not to bypass his country, saying a visit would go a long way toward
easing tensions with India.
</P>
<P>
	   But Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., said Wednesday that ``it would be the wrong
signal to send.''
</P>
<P>
	   At a House International Relations Committee hearing, Gejdenson criticized
Musharraf for undercutting the country's court system and for preparing to try
former President Nowaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Obviously, many of us in Congress have felt tremendous frustration, first
with the coup, second, now, with the assault on the judiciary, the connection,
at least, with some elements of terrorists and obviously the connection with the
Taliban,'' Gejdenson told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who was
testifying. The Taliban that controls most of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright told the committee, however, that ``we have to remember the very
important relationship that we have had with Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said it had been interrupted, and that the Clinton administration
consistently had urged Musharraf ``to move in terms of some measurable
milestones of a return to civilian government.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are watching that very carefully -- how he reforms the electoral
commission on the parties and holds local elections,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
