<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors seek lesser-charge options for Diallo jury  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Jurors in the trial of four police officers accused
of murdering an unarmed Bronx man in a hail of 41 bullets could have the option
to convict the defendants on less serious charges.
<P>
	   With testimony in the Amadou Diallo case completed after just nine days,
prosecutors asked the judge to allow the jury to consider manslaughter and
criminally negligent homicide in addition to the original second-degree murder
charges. The defense did not object.
</P>
<P>
	   Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi reserved decision on the request, which
came moments after the defense rested. The judge denied a defense motion to
throw out the murder charges. He then adjourned the trial until Tuesday, when
the jury will hear closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28, Richard Murphy, 27, Sean Carroll, 37, and Edward McMellon,
27, have pleaded innocent to charges of intentional murder, depraved
indifference murder and reckless endangerment. If convicted of murder, they face
a maximum sentences of 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors refused to say why they sought to include the lesser charges.
</P>
<P>
	   But both sides appeared to be hedging their bets - the prosecution against a
complete exoneration of defendants in a high-profile case, the defense against
the specter of harsh prison terms for their clients. Second-degree murder
carries a minimum 15-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
	   Privately, defense attorneys said their clients had given them permission to
acquiesce to a lesser charge motion long before the defense case was over. But
Stephen Worth, McMellon's attorney, insisted to reporters that despite the
decision, the officers expected to be cleared.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't concede for a moment that it's anything but not guilty," Worth
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this week, the officers testified they fired 41 bullets at Diallo on
Feb. 4, 1999 because the unarmed Guinean immigrant refused to stop for
questioning, retreated to his Bronx building and pulled out what appeared to be
a gun; he was hit 19 times. The object Diallo pulled turned out to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution contends the officers never yelled any warnings before
cornering Diallo and opening fire. Backed by autopsy findings, prosecutors also
say most of the bullets hit Diallo while he was going down or flat on his back.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting of an unarmed black man by four white officers resulted in
enough pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread police abuse of
minorities that an appeals court decided to move the case to Albany. Before the
change of venue, attorneys had predicted the trial would last at least six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Teresi's ruling upholding the murder charges, the defense argued they
were too severe. Attorney Bennett Epstein claimed the case marked the first time
in state history a depraved indifference charge had been brought against "police
officers, public servants, on duty on the streets of New York risking their
lives, who made a mistake."
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Eric Warner countered that the fact Diallo had been trapped and
killed by a "wall of lead" would "more than suggest depraved indifference to
human life."
</P>
<P>
	   With the prosecution request, the jury could face a much more complex set of
decisions about the conduct of each officer.
</P>
<P>
	   The alternatives to the intentional murder charge would be first-degree
manslaughter - intent to cause injury resulting in death - which carries a
maximum sentence of 12 1/2 to 25 years.
</P>
<P>
	   For depraved indifference, options would be second-degree manslaughter -
recklessly causing death - which carries a maximum sentence of 5 to 15 years, or
criminally negligent homicide - failing to perceive the risk of death - which
carries a maximum of 1 1/3 to 4 years.
</P>
<P>
	   A conviction on the murder charges or the first-degree manslaughter charge
would guarantee some jail time for the officers. The lesser charges allow for
probation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0151 </TRAILER>
