<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another year, another court fight over St. Patrick's parade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Four years after a gay Irish organization sued the city,
a Manhattan federal jury was considering whether the Giuliani administration
violated the group's First Amendment rights by rejecting its application to
march on St. Patrick's Day.
<P>
	   The jury, which deliberated for about two hours after closing arguments on
Wednesday, was expected to resume its work this morning.
</P>
<P>
	   An attorney for the Irish Lesbian and Gay Organization, speaking in U.S.
District Court, blamed the decision to keep the group from marching before the
official St. Patrick's Day Parade on a "backroom political process."
</P>
<P>
	   But a city attorney, comparing ILGO to party crashers, argued that the
Giuliani administration violated no one's rights by refusing to grant the
demonstrators a permit to march.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the lawsuit, the city violated ILGO's First Amendment rights to
free speech by refusing to allow it a permit to march up Fifth Avenue
immediately prior to the nation's oldest and largest St. Patrick's Day Parade.
The city did so in 1996, 1997 and 1998, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
	   If a federal jury agrees, ILGO could receive financial damages and U.S.
District Court Judge John G. Koeltl could issue a ruling allowing them to march
before this year's parade.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawyers swapped charges in closing arguments after a three-week trial,
the end result of the 1996 lawsuit filed against the city by ILGO.
</P>
<P>
	   The court battle over the group's inclusion at the parade has become an
annual event since ILGO first surfaced in 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   City attorney Virginia Waters said the city's decision was not tied to
ILGO's politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, she cited a 1993 court order barring ILGO from marching in the main
parade; traffic and other problems caused by granting a permit; and the city's
offer to let ILGO march somewhere off Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
	   "ILGO claims it is flexible, as long as it can march where it wants and when
it wants," said Waters, comparing the group to "an uninvited guest" at a party.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ancient Order of Hibernians, which oversees the parade, predictably
agreed with the city. They had successfully argued that ILGO could be banned
because the parade was a private, not public, event.
</P>
<P>
	   "When it's a private parade," said Ernest Mathews, attorney for the
Hibernians, "the government can't tell you who can march or what your message
must be."
</P>
<P>
	   But ILGO attorney Diane Knox said the city's excuses were "smoke. There's no
good reason why ILGO can't have a march of 2,000 people. There's no reason at
all."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile-Defense Deadline Approaches  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Meeting President Clinton's timetable for a summer
decision on whether to deploy a limited national missile defense system will be
tough but attainable, suggests the Air Force general who oversees the program.
</P>
<P>
	   But Lt. Gen. Ronald T. Kadish said that any further test failures, like the
one in January, could significantly set back the program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a difficult program with high visibility,'' he told two House Armed
Services subcommittees on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   He conceded there was heavy political pressure for a decision, but said he
did not feel it constituted ``undue pressure.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish's testimony came after the Defense Department's senior weapons
tester, Philip E. Coyle, suggested earlier this week that the Pentagon was
facing undue pressure to meet the administration's timetable for a decision on
deploying such a system.
</P>
<P>
	   For now, Defense Secretary William Cohen plans to review the readiness of
the missile defense project in June. On the basis of that review, Cohen is to
recommend to the president whether to move ahead with deployment.
</P>
<P>
	   In a report to Congress and Cohen, Coyle wrote that the current timetable
ignored major technological problems with the program, particularly in light of
a test failure in January.
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish, director of the Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense Organization,
told lawmakers he thought the current timetable could be met.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, he said, ``If we have a failure, we may not meet that
schedule on time. We have a very aggressive schedule that we're meeting. I won't
promise that we won't have problems along the way.''
</P>
<P>
	   As envisioned by the Pentagon, the system would use a network of radars and
silo-based interceptor missiles to detect, track and shoot down long-range
ballistic missiles outside Earth's atmosphere. Congress has required the
administration to deploy such a system as soon as technology allows.
</P>
<P>
	   So far two tests have been staged of the system's ability to intercept a
target missile in space. The first, last fall, succeeded. The second, in
January, failed.
</P>
<P>
	   The next test, scheduled for April before the January failure, has now been
rescheduled for May, Kadish said.
</P>
<P>
	   It must be successful for the president's timetable to be met, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish said the January failure is still being investigated, but appears to
have been due to either a leak or a constriction in a pipe that cools infrared
sensors. ``We believe it can be fixed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., chairman of the House Armed Services subcommittee
on research and development, said it was important for the administration to
move ahead as quickly as feasible on the system to shoot enemy warheads out of
the sky.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've already passed the threat threshold,'' Weldon said, citing ballistic
missile programs by North Korea, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans in Congress have long pressed for development of such a system,
a smaller-scaled version of the missile defense shield envisioned by Ronald
Reagan in the 1980s and derided by critics as ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Rep. Norman Sisisky, D-Va., argued that the timetable shouldn't be
forced. ``This is rocket science,'' he said. ``Technology, not politics, should
rule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Die in Calif. Cargo Plane Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOWARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RANCHO CORDOVA, Calif. (AP) -- A DC-8 cargo plane crashed into an automobile
wrecking yard while trying to make an emergency landing Wednesday, bursting into
flames and killing the three people aboard the aircraft, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
	   Emery Worldwide Flight 17 took off at 7:35 p.m., bound for Dayton, Ohio,
from Mather Field when the pilot immediately reported trouble, said company
spokesman James Allen.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane turned around and crashed about 1 mile east of Mather, he said.
Those on board were dead by the time fire crews arrived, said fire Capt. Dan
Haverty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was no chance of rescue,'' Haverty said.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane carried three crew members: the pilot, first captain and a flight
engineer, all believed to be Emery employees, said Allen.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot reported unsecured cargo shortly after takeoff, Haverty said. The
plane carried clothing, automatic transmission fluid and a small amount of fuses
-- 9 grams, or about a third of an ounce -- used to activate automobile air
bags, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Whitehead, manager of the Federal Aviation Administration's regional
operations center in Los Angeles, said the pilot reported a severe problem with
the balance of the aircraft. The plane hit the ground ``in a ball of fire,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane crashed into the Insurance Auto Auctions salvage yard, setting as
many as 200 cars on fire and causing explosions over a 200-yard-long area.
</P>
<P>
	   Motorist Ernie Killinger watched the plane strike belly-first.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was like he was crash-landing,'' said Killinger, who was driving home
at the time. ``I saw the front half of the fuselage come out of the flames and
the cockpit was straight up and it just rocked back and forth until it was
engulfed by the flames.''
</P>
<P>
	   There were no immediate reports of injuries on the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   FAA investigators, a bomb squad and a hazardous materials team were among
those on the scene.
</P>
<P>
	   The McDonnell Douglas DC-8 has two engines mounted on each wing. The model
went into service in 1959 and production ended in 1972.
</P>
<P>
	   Mather Field was once Mather Air Force Base, which was closed as a military
operation in 1993. Since then, it has become a civilian airport and the region's
air cargo hub. It is located about 10 miles east of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   Emery, based in Redwood City, specializes in transportation services for
business shippers of heavyweight cargo, the company says on its Web site. The
$2.4-billion company is a subsidiary of CNF Inc., a $5.6-billion diversified
transportation company based in Palo Alto, the site states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Power Impacts Colombia Rebels  </HEADLINE>
   By JARED KOTLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) -- As swarms of guerrillas rushed the tiny police
post and officers inside radioed frantically for help, a pilot high in the skies
flicked on his night-vision equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Staring into the glow of an infrared screen, the air force captain uttered a
prayer and then rained .60-caliber bullets on Colombia's southern savannah.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I said God, my protector, help me. And then I fired'', recalled Arturo,
the man who was flying the Vietnam-era AC-47 gunship, a plane Colombian
guerrillas have nicknamed ``The Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
	   The attack in July was part of a Colombian military resurgence that
observers credit at least partly to improved night capabilities, communications
and intelligence-sharing provided by the United States since President Andres
Pastrana took office 19 months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The government's air advantage would grow enormously if the U.S. Congress
approves a $1.6 billion anti-narcotics plan the Clinton administration has
proposed for the South American nation that could come to a vote as early as
March.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack that Arturo described killed about a dozen guerrillas in Puerto
Rico, one of the towns attacked during a leftist offensive. The military
reported 300 rebels killed during the campaign -- mostly from the air.
</P>
<P>
	   The heaviest guerrilla losses in nearly four decades of conflict were also a
stunning reversal for a military that had been repeatedly humiliated in ground
combat on the rebels' jungle turf.
</P>
<P>
	   Government planes and helicopters had similar success in clashes that
followed -- cutting down insurgents crossing fields, blowing up guerrilla
convoys on highways, and even blasting rebel riverboats out of Amazonian
tributaries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The air force is a very powerful weapon, with great capacity for
destruction,'' boasted its commander, Gen. Hector Velasco. ``We've used only a
minimal portion of what we have.''
</P>
<P>
	   Military analysts believe air power could be crucial to turning the tide in
Colombia's long-running civil conflict -- a factor that might discourage the
large-scale attacks that rebels began mounting successfully in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   The new U.S. plan before Congress includes 30 Black Hawk and 33 Huey
helicopters, an RG-8A reconnaissance plane, air base and radar enhancements and
further upgrades to add night-vision systems to aging planes.
</P>
<P>
	   The helicopters would escort unarmed planes that fumigate drug crops and
ferry troops from two new U.S.-trained army battalions into guerrilla-infested
jungles.
</P>
<P>
	   The aid is earmarked for use against drug traffickers or rebels from the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, who protect the drug
operations. But U.S. officials admit it won't be easy to prevent Colombia from
using its new planes and helicopters in standard counterinsurgency operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Velasco said aircraft donated or sold with Pentagon approval for
counternarcotics purposes have also been used effectively against the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to 18 U.S.-built Black Hawks, Velasco said the air force has
sent into combat A-37 ``Dragonflies'' and OV-10 ``Broncos'' -- Vietnam-era
tactical fighters acquired principally for downing drug-smuggling planes.
</P>
<P>
	   During Pastrana's tenure, the Pentagon has trained pilots to fly in the dark
and outfitted some of these aircraft with night-vision goggles and
Forward-Looking Infrared sensors that can detect a rebel's head from several
thousand feet aloft.
</P>
<P>
	   After the air force spent much of its ammunition beating back last year's
FARC offensive, the U.S. military replaced the stock.
</P>
<P>
	   While U.S. officials say Americans are only training Colombian troops and
pilots, some Democratic lawmakers in Washington have expressed concern U.S.
soldiers could be drawn into combat.
</P>
<P>
	   Those fears grew last year when a U.S. Army reconnaissance plane crashed
over rebel territory, killing five Americans who the Pentagon said were on a
routine counterdrug mission. U.S. reconnaissance planes still regularly fly over
Colombia, the military says. None are known to have been shot at by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. and Colombian military officials are watching closely to see whether
the FARC will try to neutralize the aerial threat with surface-to-air missiles
-- so far absent in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   Velasco said the FARC has offered its fighters $2,500 for every military
pilot they assassinate -- which explains why Arturo, the AC-47 pilot, asked that
his last name not be published.
</P>
<P>
	   Concerns exist, meanwhile, that more strafing and bombing will put civilians
at risk. U.N. human rights monitors believe air force bullets and rockets caused
the December 1998 deaths of 16 villagers in a town near the Venezuelan border.
</P>
<P>
	   Pilots at a Black Hawk base near Medellin said they have strict instructions
to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   One swaggering airman -- identifiable by his code name, Rhinoceros, and the
words ``Born to Fly'' taped on his helmet -- said it is gratifying to be hitting
back at the rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A year ago, they had us running ragged, attacking bases, kidnapping
soldiers and police,'' he said. ``That's changed a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0208 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
