<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore To Meet AFL-CIO Leaders  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The AFL-CIO's endorsement of Al Gore for president does
not mean labor leaders will go soft on a key point of disagreement with him this
year: China's trade relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we have to take on a fight on this issue, we're going to fight on this
issue,'' said AFL-CIO President John Sweeney of the labor federation's
opposition to a Clinton administration push for Congress to give China permanent
normal trade status, which Gore supports.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore was scheduled to meet with AFL-CIO leaders here today for the first
time since the federation's endorsement of him last fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney says Gore will be backed, no holds barred, by a massive political
campaign by unions to line up votes for him. Today, the AFL-CIO president
planned to introduce Gore to Louisiana workers at the Avondale shipyard, where
unions recently won a six-year organizing fight.
</P>
<P>
	   But Gore's closed-door meeting with union leaders is not expected be all
handshakes and slaps on the back.
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president will face the leaders of two major unions that so far
have not joined the others in endorsing him, largely because of trade issues --
the Teamsters and the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, who met labor leaders on Wednesday, said she
told them the administration is working hard to keep lines of communication open
and ``not to have trade ... become a polarizing issue,'' this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately Wednesday, AFL-CIO leaders, in a shift in stance toward
immigrants, called for the repeal of a 1986 law they say has made it hard to
unionize or improve conditions for undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
	   The new stand also commits unions to press for amnesty for the estimated 5
million to 6 million workers and their families who are here illegally or have
only temporary legal status.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The current system of immigration enforcement in the United States is
broken and we must fix it. We believe the AFL-CIO can lead on this issue,'' said
AFL-CIO executive vice president Linda Chavez-Thompson.
</P>
<P>
	   The AFL-CIO is still committed to opposing increases in the number of
immigrants allowed to come here to work legally.
</P>
<P>
	   But it is calling for new immigration laws that would protect those already
here working illegally from firing or deportation if they try to unionize or
complain to the government about violations of labor laws, including the minimum
wage and safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   The AFL-CIO wants the new rules to replace the 1986 law that set up the
current system of enforcing immigration laws through employers, holding over
companies the threat of punishment if they hire undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
	   The labor movement originally supported that law, but now says it is being
used by employers to intimidate illegal immigrants who try to join unions or
otherwise try to improve their wages or working conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
