<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Ideology Becomes Issue  </HEADLINE>
   By WALTER R. MEARS AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush is trying to build a barricade on the
right against Sen. John McCain, but it may be a shaky one. There's a new dent
now that a conservative dropout candidate has endorsed McCain as the best
Republican bet to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's campaign has been working to rally support from religious,
social-issue conservatives, and the Christian right is a powerful bloc in South
Carolina, where the GOP rivals collide in a pivotal primary on Saturday. But the
movement's influence has waned in this campaign. They are generally with Bush,
but without the activism of past campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   And there is no clear line between Bush and McCain on conservative ideology.
It's a matter of degree, according to the Texas governor. ``I'm more
conservative on certain issues,'' he said Tuesday night in their South Carolina
debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Bauer, the conservative activist who abandoned his campaign after
getting less than 1 percent of the vote in New Hampshire, now is backing McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He is the best shot we have to end the era of Bill and Hillary and Al
Gore,'' Bauer said Wednesday in Greenville, S.C. He said McCain doesn't stand
for ``a money-bags democracy'' but for civility, decency and honor.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer's endorsement is a helpful message for McCain against suggestions that
he is a sort of closet moderate, not the proud conservative of his self
description.
</P>
<P>
	   The Christian conservative vote is ``still very critical,'' said Ralph Reed,
a Bush strategist and veteran of that movement. ``The vote was cannibalized by
multiple candidacies.''
</P>
<P>
	   Reed said the religious conservative vote will determine who wins the South
Carolina primary. But that could change should turnout swell significantly
beyond the Republican base.
</P>
<P>
	   The primary is open not only to independents -- who delivered McCain's
landslide margin over Bush in New Hampshire -- but to Democrats, too. So both
campaigners have been looking toward the center, while at the same time trying
to persuade conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   Nothing so simple as in the long-past era when Republican campaigns were
waged between the right and center-left wings of the GOP. The lines are blurred
now. Bush's conservative allies are trying to draw them again, against McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Pat Robertson, the Christian Coalition founder, backs Bush and has
said McCain is unfit to be president. He says religious conservatives would walk
away from a McCain ticket in the fall, undermining the Republican base.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a state that embraces conservative values,'' Bush said in South
Carolina. ``I'm the conservative candidate.''
</P>
<P>
	   Steve Forbes tried to claim that role, but quit for lack of votes. He said
the contest had become one of personalities and charisma, and that his message
of issues never got through.
</P>
<P>
	   That, essentially, was Bauer's explanation when he dropped out, too.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Forbes and Bauer said they had pushed the campaign to the right.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we really have had tremendous clout,'' said Rep. Bob Barr of
Georgia, who had backed Forbes. He said the issues Bush and McCain are talking
about, ``even the language they are using, makes clear that they are hearing the
conservative message.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``How anyone can say McCain's New Hampshire victory translates into an
epitaph for the right is baffling,'' says Edwin Feulner, president of the
Heritage Foundation. ``Each one of this year's contenders, even the dropouts, is
running as a self-proclaimed conservative.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They may argue over how conservative ideas should be applied to today's
issues, but the heir to Bill Scranton and Nelson Rockefeller is nowhere to be
found,'' Feulner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Governors Rockefeller of New York and Scranton of Pennsylvania were two
pillars of the liberal Republican establishment, rivals in turn to Barry
Goldwater, the Mr. Conservative GOP presidential nominee in 1964. That liberal
wing is no longer a factor in Republican campaigns. Ronald Reagan moved the
agenda to the right and conservatives dominate the GOP majorities in Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said 'No' when asked in the debate whether he was trying to imply that
McCain is too liberal. He said he considers the Arizona senator a conservative.
</P>
<P>
	   But at rallies, he says McCain's ideas on taxes and other issues are
comparable to President Clinton's, and that while ``I wouldn't call John a
liberal,'' he does have some Democratic positions.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's campaign financing plan is one point of contention with
conservative interest groups, who object to its restrictions on issue ads, which
are a factor in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Right to Life Committee is using radio ads and mailings in the
state's most conservative areas backing Bush and opposing McCain on abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's campaign is pressing the issue although both men oppose abortion,
albeit with subtle differences. Among conservatives, and especially on abortion,
the fine print counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0219 </TRAILER>
