<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Comments on 2000 Races  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says American voters have the pick of
four good candidates to take his job, and that the daily sniping on the campaign
trail is just politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, at a news conference Wednesday, also rejected calls for a national
moratorium on capital punishment, while urging the nation's governors to ``look
very closely'' at their death penalty systems to make sure innocent people are
not executed.
</P>
<P>
	   During the hourlong meeting with reporters, his first of the new year,
Clinton took questions on presidential politics with relish, even as he said he
is trying to stay above the day-to-day political fray.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You've basically got four people running for president now who are people
of accomplishment, people who have certain convictions, people who have, I
think, pretty clear philosophies and records,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   While Clinton wants to see Vice President Al Gore succeed him, he declined
the opportunity to bash any of the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd like to think I'm casting a little sunshine'' over the race, Clinton
said to laughter. ``I keep trying to build these fellas up, you know. I'm being
nice and generous and all that.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also said the country has ``a good choice'' among the leading contenders,
and seemed to downplay the current fracas over negative campaigning that has led
to finger-pointing among both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have never seen a tough race where people fought with each other, where
they didn't have different interpretations of each other's record and each
other's positions,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Illinois Gov. George Ryan was courageous to impose a freeze on
executions last month, after the exoneration of 13 death row inmates in his
state over two decades. Clinton said death penalty supporters -- including
himself -- have ``an especially heavy obligation'' to make sure there is no
question of guilt for condemned prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton refused to say whether he will challenge ethics complaints seeking
to strip him of his Arkansas law license because of his conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he paid $850,000 last year to settle a related case -- the sexual
harassment suit of Paula Jones -- only to prevent it from being a distraction to
his presidency. He said the suit ``had absolutely no merit.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he has not ruled out a visit to Pakistan next month when he
visits its neighbor and nuclear rival, India. He said his decision would hinge
on whether stopping in Islamabad could halt the regional arms race, promote
democracy in military-ruled Pakistan and resolve the India-Pakistan conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   He also announced the release of $125 million in federal money to help needy
families buy home heating oil in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   The president also said he would seek $600 million in emergency funds to
deal with the current crisis and problems likely to occur later this year in
areas suffering from extreme heat.
</P>
<P>
	   On other subjects, Clinton:
</P>
<P>
	   --Said Republican presidential hopefuls John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas have ``got a tough job'' in running against the Clinton record of peace
and prosperity. ``I have a lot of sympathy with them,'' he said, a day after
sharp criticism from Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   --Said Democratic rivals Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore were
``right to condemn'' Clinton's nomination of Republican Bradley Smith to the
Federal Election Commission. Clinton said Smith ``hates campaign finance''
legislation but that he nominated him anyway simply to fill a Republican
vacancy, and Smith was the candidate favored by Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
	   --Refused to cast blame for the deepening crisis in the Northern Ireland
peace process. ``I don't think you can Monday morning quarterback that,'' the
president said. He said the current crisis was ``a very unfortunate
development'' but that the IRA ``has given no indication whatever that they will
revert to violence.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``And so that means that they still think, no matter what the rhetoric says,
that all the parties really believe that they ought to find a way to work this
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
