<HEADLINE> Funerals Held for Tornado Victims  </HEADLINE>
   By ERIN McCLAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PELHAM, Ga. (AP) -- In the tiny Baptist church where the Rev. Jackie
McClelland delivered his sermons, church members struggled to make sense of the
tragedy caused by deadly tornadoes that swept through southwest Georgia this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   McClelland and his wife Mary Ann, both 64, were killed Monday when twisters
struck their rural farm house. Mrs. McClelland, director of the Grady County
Health Department, was just one month shy of retirement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's difficult to stand here and try to express to you that God is a God
of love,'' the Rev. Cleston Brooks told mourners. ``But do not let this harden
your heart. It's not for you and I to choose when our time will come.''
</P>
<P>
	   Union Hill Primitive Baptist Church couldn't fit all of the mourners inside
its church, which seats 200. Speakers were set up outside so others could hear
the tributes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were people that other people cherished,'' said Junior Peeples, a
relative. ``And they went together -- to go with the one you shared your life
with, that's a special meaning.''
</P>
<P>
	   The tornadoes touched down in four counties. Authorities reduced the death
toll from 22 to 18 Wednesday, saying confusion in the aftermath of the storms
led to four victims being counted twice.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitchell County, which had 11 dead, was worst hit. Winds reached as high as
200 mph and cut a 10-mile path of devastation.
</P>
<P>
	   Families in the small Mitchell County town of Camilla, about 40 miles from
the Georgia-Florida border, met with insurance adjusters Wednesday to assess
what they had lost and how long recovery would take.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, who assessed regional damage by helicopter, also
toured Camilla for a firsthand look.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What do you guys make of all this? Pretty scary, wasn't it?'' Gore asked
one family, who sat on a plastic-covered mattress in what would have been their
front yard.
</P>
<P>
	   The Insurance Information Institute put the total Georgia storm damage at
$25 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal, state and local authorities planned to set up a temporary housing
park with 40 units for displaced families early next week, Georgia Emergency
Management Agency spokesman Jeff Jellets said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile Wednesday, about 150 people attended a funeral for Gloria Jean
Miller Eglinton, 54, a bank teller in Cairo, about 20 miles south of Pelham.
</P>
<P>
	   Her friends recalled her love for all living things.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some people can love the unlovable. Jeannie liked frogs,'' the Rev.
DeWayne Atkinson said. ``God gave her this personality -- this outgoing, bubbly
personality. She was a friend to everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
