<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1907 Campaign Finance Law Attacked  </HEADLINE>
   By BILL BERGSTROM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The growing number of ``soft money'' donations by
businesses and unions proves that a 93-year-old law banning corporate
contributions to federal candidates is woefully ineffectual, a lawyer argued.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney Floyd Abrams urged the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on
Wednesday to strike down the ban since ``spending of large amounts of soft money
destroys the purpose of the campaign finance law, which is to deter corruption
and the appearance of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
	   The term ``soft money'' refers to contributions made to political parties to
be used for business-related expenses, not for a particular candidate's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Abrams represents Renato P. Mariani, former president of Empire Sanitary
Landfill, who was indicted in a wide-ranging campaign finance probe that led to
a prison sentence for state Rep. Frank Serafini.
</P>
<P>
	   Mariani has sued the federal government, contending the ban on corporate
contributions to candidates is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics say the law permits parties to spend millions of dollars on
so-called ``issue ads'' that make veiled attacks on candidates without directly
advocating their defeat.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This statute does not work,'' Abrams told the court.
</P>
<P>
	   The chief judge of the appeals court, Edward Becker, said such arguments
were understandable when ``you have soft money that is off the charts'' and
``issue ads in which the difference may be gossamer between addressing an issue
and supporting a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
	   But attorney David Kolker of the Federal Elections Commission said it is up
to Congress, not the courts, to change the law if they think it needs
improvement.
</P>
<P>
	   Overturning the ban and allowing corporations to make secret contributions
directly to candidates, he said, would ``throw the baby out with the bath
water.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mariani and other former Empire officials were charged with funneling
corporate money from the landfill to candidates for federal office, including
President Clinton and Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
	   While that case was pending, Mariani sued the to overturn the corporate
contributions law.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Thomas Vanaskie sought an appeals court ruling, saying
in a 144-page memorandum in October that he found many of Mariani's arguments to
be valid.
</P>
<P>
	   Soft-money contributions and loopholes have ``essentially rendered the
contributions and spending limits meaningless,'' Vanaskie wrote, questioning
whether the 1907 ban still meets the legal standard that it serve a
``significant state interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0254 </TRAILER>
