<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Premier To Testify  </HEADLINE>
   By ALVIN UNG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's prime minister said today he would
testify in the sodomy trial of his ousted deputy if a judge rules that he must
-- even though he suspects it would be a ``political stunt.''
</P>
<P>
	   High Court Judge Ariffin Jaka was expected to hear arguments today in a
Kuala Lumpur courtroom on whether Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad should be
forced to take the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it is relevant, I suppose I will have to go,'' Mahathir told reporters
after inaugurating a meeting of freight operators. ``That is the law, and there
is nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
	   But he added, if it is not relevant ``then it will be a kind of political
stunt.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mahathir said the desire to drag him to court appeared to be driven more by
politics than by law. ``I don't know much about the case,'' he said. ``But
apparently there is some political nuance in the desire to put me on the
stand.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mahathir fired Anwar Ibrahim as deputy prime minister in September 1998, and
his administration put the former politician on trial for abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
	   Anwar is serving a six-year jail term for corruption and faces another 20
years if found guilty of sodomy, a crime in this predominantly Muslim country.
</P>
<P>
	   Anwar claims the charges are part of a political conspiracy launched by
Mahathir to end his challenge to the prime minister's 18-year rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Anwar's defense wants Mahathir to answer questions about the allegations he
has made against his former deputy. But prosecutors have cited a rarely used law
under the Southeast Asian country's Evidence Act to argue that Mahathir's
testimony would not be relevant to the sex trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Karpal Singh accused Mahathir of setting a bad example by
``dragging his feet'' about testifying. A court appearance by the leader would
send a message about the fairness of Malaysia's judiciary, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In this country even the king can be taken to court ... and Mahathir is no
king,'' Karpal said, as onlookers at the courthouse broke into applause.
</P>
<P>
	   Ariffin said at the close of Wednesday's hearing that the prime minister
should be prepared to come to the court at any time. He is expected to give his
ruling on whether the prime minister must testify after hearing arguments from
both defense and prosecution lawyers.
</P>
<P>
	   Dozens of people hoping to see Mahathir face-to-face with Anwar for the
first time since Anwar was fired gathered outside the courthouse early today to
grab a seat in the public gallery. There were no signs of extra security.
</P>
<P>
	   Anwar and his adopted brother are accused of forcing Anwar's former family
driver, Azizan Abu Bakar, to have sex with them between January and March 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Azizan has accused Anwar of repeatedly sodomizing him, claiming he became
Anwar's ``sex slave'' more than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   A defense witness has testified that Azizan and others were paid money by
Mahathir's political secretary to come forward with the false allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0256 </TRAILER>
