<DOCNO> APW20000217.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villagers skeptical of safety claim after steam release  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BUCHANAN, N.Y. (AP) - While many people might choose to live somewhere
other than near a nuclear power plant, George Kiljarian said he has grown used
to it.
<P>
	   "I'm a fatalist," said the Ossining man, a retired attorney who lives near
the Indian Point 2 nuclear reactor. "I made it through World War II. ... If
they've never had a problem in 26 years I guess that's all right."
</P>
<P>
	   But other neighbors are concerned about being so close to Indian Point 2
because they weren't notified Tuesday night when the plant leaked a small amount
of radioactive steam - the most serious accident in its 26-year history.
</P>
<P>
	   In response, a group of local activists plan to rally this afternoon at
Indian Point's front gate in opposition of the plant reopening ever again.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm definitely afraid," said Regina Erben, just four doors from the plant
entrance. "I'm afraid to brush my teeth. I'm afraid to make the coffee."
</P>
<P>
	   Plant officials said the steam was barely radioactive, describing its escape
from the nuclear reactor as "momentary and minuscule." They added there was no
health danger, no need to warn nearby residents, no reason to keep the kids home
from school.
</P>
<P>
	   But some remained upset that a hazardous response effort was undertaken
without any notice being given to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
	   "Where were the sirens?" asked David Coviello, 55, who lives two doors from
the plant gate. "I have a 7-year-old son, an 18-year-old daughter."
</P>
<P>
	   Salvatore Simone said officials should notify residents of any accident,
regardless of its seriousness. "I should decide for myself," he said. "I might
have gotten into the car with my family and gotten away."
</P>
<P>
	   Officials in four counties agreed that the accident was too small to merit
sounding warning sirens, said Westchester's deputy county executive, Jay
Hashmall. County Executive Andrew Spano was in Los Angeles, coincidentally to
examine that city's emergency operations center.
</P>
<P>
	   Guidelines from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission "call for the sounding of
sirens only when some protective action is needed," such as evacuations or
stay-inside orders, Hashmall said.
</P>
<P>
	   No such measures were needed Tuesday because the radioactivity released was
"completely unmeasurable," said Con Ed Vice President Steve Quinn.
</P>
<P>
	   Nevertheless, Con Ed declared an alert, a first for the plant, located on
the Hudson River about 35 miles north of Times Square and with 15.5 million
people within a 50-mile radius. An alert is one of four categories of nuclear
events identified by the NRC. In order from least serious to most serious they
are: unusual event, alert, site area emergency and general emergency.
</P>
<P>
	   The only general emergency at a U.S. nuclear plant was the March 1979
accident at Three Mile Island in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
	   Mindy Landau of the NRC said an average of three or four alerts are declared
a year among the nation's 103 operating reactors.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's alert was lifted just before 7 p.m. Wednesday, when water
temperatures cooled to below 200 degrees. Workers were then to begin
investigating the cause of the leak and determining how long the plant would be
idle.
</P>
<P>
	   Quinn said the leak was in a tube carrying hot, slightly radioactive water
through a pool of cooler water, which is thereby turned into steam. The steam is
used to turn a turbine, generating electricity. The plant produces about a
seventh of the power Con Ed supplies to its 3 million customers.
</P>
<P>
	   Because the hot water was under high pressure, it turned into steam as it
escaped from the tube at about 7:30 p.m. It was vented through the building's
roof, but a radiation detector in the vent sounded an alarm and automatically
sealed the vent, so the slightly radioactive steam escaped into the air for only
a few seconds, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Measurements taken around the plant found normal background radiation, Quinn
said, and workers were not exposed to anything above what they get in a normal
workday. No one was injured, he said, and "There is no danger to the health and
welfare of the general public."
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Jacobs, executive director of the Westchester People's Action
Coalition, said the Indian Point plants are old and failing and should be
investigated independently of the NRC.
</P>
<P>
	   NRC spokesman Neil Sheehan said steel-alloy tubes like the one that leaked
"have been known to develop leaks from time to time." Con Ed's Robert Leonard
said the tubes at Indian Point 2 were the originals from 1974. In the past, when
leaks were found, a tube might simply be plugged and not used because the
generator does not need all of the 200 tubes it has, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   A slight increase in the generator's normal leakage - about a half-gallon a
day more than the normal 2 gallons a day in comparable generators - was detected
several weeks ago, The New York Times reported today. But NRC inspectors
permanently stationed at the plant never indicated that the increase was serious
enough to warrant shutting the plant, James Baumstark, Con Ed's vice president
for nuclear engineering, told The Times.
</P>
<P>
	   The nearby Indian Point 3 reactor, owned by the state Power Authority, has
been tentatively purchased for $806 million by Entergy Corp. of New Orleans,
which said Monday that it was also interested in buying Indian Point 2. Con Ed
has said it is seeking a buyer for Indian Point 2. Entergy spokesman Carl
Crawford said Wednesday that Tuesday's leak had no effect on either deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 0300 </TRAILER>
