<DOCNO> APW20000217.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Feb. 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Fight Navy in Puerto Rico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Residents of the Puerto Rican island of Vieques say they
will continue acting as human shields to try to stop the Navy from dropping
unarmed bombs on a military training ground. A delegation of protesters met with
lawmakers Wednesday and protested outside the White House. They charged that
President Clinton's order last month to allow the Navy to resume dropping dummy
bombs in Puerto Rico demonstrates a cavalier and undemocratic disregard for
residents who want the military to leave immediately. "We want the Navy out of
there," said Carlos Zenon, a fishermen who has organized demonstrations against
the Navy. "They could bomb Staten Island if they want or Martha's Vineyard."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Funerals Held for Tornado Victims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PELHAM, Ga. (AP) -- In the tiny Baptist church where the Rev. Jackie
McClelland delivered his sermons, church members struggled to make sense of the
tragedy caused by deadly tornadoes that swept through southwest Georgia this
week. McClelland and his wife Mary Ann, both 64, were killed Monday when
twisters struck their rural farm house. Mrs. McClelland, director of the Grady
County Health Department, was just one month shy of retirement. Union Hill
Primitive Baptist Church couldn't fit all of the mourners inside its church,
which seats 200. Speakers were set up outside so others could hear the tributes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
3 Die in Calif. Cargo Plane Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   RANCHO CORDOVA, Calif. (AP) -- A DC-8 cargo plane crashed into an automobile
wrecking yard while trying to make an emergency landing Wednesday, bursting into
flames and killing the three crew members aboard the aircraft, investigators
said. Those on board the Emery Worldwide plane were dead by the time fire crews
arrived at the site about 1 mile east of Mather Field, said fire Capt. Dan
Haverty. "There was no chance of rescue," Haverty said. The plane carried three
crew members: the pilot, first captain and a flight engineer, all believed to be
Emery employees, said company spokesman James Allen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Looks to India, Pakistan Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is leaving the door open -- slightly --
to making a visit to Pakistan and offering to help mediate the volatile Kashmir
dispute Pakistan has with India. Since India never has accepted outside
intervention, the president's offer at a news conference Wednesday to intercede
as he has in the Arab-Israeli dispute and in Northern Ireland is probably
academic. But asked whether he would be willing, Clinton responded, "absolutely,
I would," and then said "unless we are asked by both parties to help, we can't
get involved."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Internet Racism Concerns U.N.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GENEVA (AP) -- The United States could do more to curb the use of the
Internet for racist material while upholding freedom of speech, experts said
Wednesday at a U.N. meeting. Speakers noted the legal challenges of controlling
Internet content in, and originating from, the United States, where the First
Amendment of the constitution guarantees freedom of speech. Although the U.S.
government cannot ban racist speech outright, it could impose "reasonable
restrictions," such as requiring a permit that would force publishers to
identify the content of their sites, Swiss-based information technology law
expert David Rosenthal argued.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reinforcements Arrive in Kosovo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.N. police reinforcements began
arriving in this ethnically divided town on Wednesday, following two weeks of
violence that left nine people dead and dozens injured. A total of 300 officers
are to be sent to Kosovska Mitrovica, top U.N. administrator Bernard Kouchner
said. With the upsurge in violence, more reinforcements were needed, and not
just in Kosovska Mitrovica, but throughout the province of Kosovo, U.N.
Assistant Secretary-General Hedi Annabi told the Security Council on Wednesday
at the United Nations. A rocket attack on a U.N. bus which killed two Serb
civilians on Feb. 2 sparked the latest round of violence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stocks Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices closed higher Thursday. The Nikkei, which
was down some 70 points early in the session, gained 192.22 points to close the
day at 19,791.40. In New York Wednesday, the Dow ended down 156.68 at 10,561.41.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mighty Ducks Defeat Flames 6-5 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Fredrik Olausson tied it with a late power-play and
Oleg Tverdovsky won it in overtime as the Anaheim Mighty Ducks beat Calgary 6-5
Wednesday night, extending the Flames' winless streak to 10 games. Steve Rucchin
had two goals and an assist for the Ducks and Paul Kariya had a goal and four
assists. Kevin Haller ended a 41-game goal drought and Teemu Selanne extended
his point-scoring streak to 12 games with a pair of assists, including his 700th
NHL point.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
