<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Rips Sydney Organizers  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- A top IOC official accused Sydney organizers today of
undermining their own corporate sponsors and misleading the public by describing
the marketing programs for the 2000 Games as a failure.
</P>
<P>
	``Is there anything about the word `success' you don't understand?''
International Olympic Committee vice president Dick Pound said in an unusually
blunt public criticism of an Olympic organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
	Pound blasted Sydney organizers for their ``dysfunctional relationship'' with
local sponsors and described the committee's frequently raised revenue targets
as ``nuts.''
</P>
<P>
	Michael Knight, president of the Sydney organizing committee (SOCOG), retorted
by suggesting that Pound's outburst marked the start of his political campaign
to succeed Juan Antonio Samaranch as IOC president.
</P>
<P>
	``If one candidate has a point of departure, that's politics,'' Knight said.
``I'm never surprised by anything Dick says. I've known him for quite a while.
We've had our moments from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
	The sharp exchanges came as SOCOG announced another $22.8 million in budget
cuts, and as UPS -- one of the games' major sponsors -- was dropped as Sydney's
Olympic ticket distributor in Australia.
</P>
<P>
	With only seven months until the start of the Sydney Games, Pound's remarks
were sure to put further pressure on an organizing committee that has been
reeling from a series of recent controversies over ticketing, budget shortfalls
and political disputes.
</P>
<P>
	Pound, who negotiates the IOC's television and marketing deals, said Sydney's
marketing program was the most successful in Olympic history -- generating total
global revenues of $2.6 billion in three years.
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG has repeatedly cited a shortfall in sponsorship revenues, including a
latest figure of around $63 million out of its total budget of $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	``They insist on calling it a failure and a marketing shortfall,'' Pound said.
``There simply is no marketing failure.''
</P>
<P>
	``We don't understand whether they don't understand or whether there is some
other agenda to be bad mouthing a very successful program. You can't undermine
your private sector and sponsors like this.''
</P>
<P>
	Sydney's original local sponsorship target was $207 million, and the program
has so far generated more than $300 million. But SOCOG, confident of being able
to raise much more money, has raised the revenue target several times -- to a
peak of $460 million.
</P>
<P>
	Pound chided SOCOG for treating sponsorship dollars as a ``milk cow that could
be returned to again, again and again.''
</P>
<P>
	``The first time (SOCOG raised the revenue target) we thought it was wildly
optimistic,'' Pound said. ``The second time we thought it was foolishly
optimistic. The third time we knew it was nuts and said so. It proved to be
right.''
</P>
<P>
	Pound said sponsors had approached the IOC to complain about SOCOG's attitude.
</P>
<P>
	``What you see from a distance is a dysfunctional relationship between the
organizing committee and the sponsors,'' Pound said. ``There's got to be a
bridge built to make sure these games are a success for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
	Pound said his remarks were directed at the ``highest level of SOCOG,''
including Knight.
</P>
<P>
	``I think Michael Knight has done a great job, but not in everything,'' he
said. ``For some reasons I don't understand, he says the marketing program is a
failure, and that's the reason they had to cut back and the IOC is taking all
this money away from SOCOG. It's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the New South Wales government agreed to forego $19 million
and the AOC $7 million to help SOCOG's budget-cutting efforts.
</P>
<P>
	``Making a profit is not the objective,'' Pound said. ``Our advice is: Wait
until the end of the games before you spend profits.''
</P>
<P>
	Knight, meanwhile, said that today's cuts would balance SOCOG's budget without
eliminating any jobs or affecting sports venues or operations for the games.
</P>
<P>
	``There has been no radical surgery here,'' he said. ``It's nip and tuck rather
than amputations.''
</P>
<P>
	Knight also announced that UPS, the American delivery service company, had been
dropped from the role of distributing Olympic tickets to Australian customers.
</P>
<P>
	Knight said UPS declined to meet SOCOG's requirements for delivering all
tickets door-to-door. SOCOG was negotiating with three other companies to step
in, he said.
</P>
<P>
	UPS will continue to deliver tickets from the printer to designated
distribution points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccine Panel Changes Recommendation  </HEADLINE>
    By JAMES PILCHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- In a sign that cost is becoming a factor in making
immunization policy, a government advisory committee has changed its initial
recommendation and will require fewer children to receive an expensive vaccine.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center for Disease Control and Prevention's Advisory Committee on
Immunization Policy recommended that the vaccine Prevenar be administered to all
children under 2 and those under 5 who are at high risk of contracting illnesses
such as meningitis.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee voted in October to recommend Prevenar, which costs $232 per
four-dose series, for all children under 5.
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday's 7-4 vote in favor of changing the recommendation came after a
lengthy discussion of cost implications that included a presentation from a
representative of health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to children under 2, the committee recommended vaccinations for
children from 2 to 5 who have had frequent ear infections, are socially or
economically disadvantaged or attend group child care. Children older than 2
only need one dose, which costs $58.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only the second time the committee has ever debated the potential
economic impact of a vaccine, even while some committee members felt the matter
shouldn't even be considered.
</P>
<P>
	   "This could save lives no matter what the age or the cost, and the
discussion about at what price this becomes reasonable is indecipherable to me,"
said Dr. Paul Offit, chief of infectious diseases at The Children's Hospital of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to recommend it first and figure out how to pay for it second," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other committee members argued about realities faced by the public and
private sector alike, especially with the hefty price tag of the vaccine. The
federal government pays for about half of all immunizations.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're having to look at cost more and more," said Dr. John Modlin, the
committee's chairman and a professor of pediatric medicine at Dartmouth
University. "We know (Prevenar) will be expensive in the short term, but over
the long haul ... we could see a lowering of pediatric health costs as a result
of this."
</P>
<P>
	   Federal approval of the vaccine is expected this week. Manufacturer American
Home Products Inc. plans to begin marketing Prevenar this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   Prevenar fights the bacterium streptococcus pneumoniae -- the leading cause
of pneumonia, meningitis and the millions of ear infections that lead to crammed
pediatrician waiting rooms every year.
</P>
<P>
	   According to a study, the vaccine reduced ear infections by 9 percent.
Doctor visits by those who were diagnosed as having chronic ear infections and
took the vaccine were down 20 percent, and there was a 20 percent reduction in
the number of children who needed tube implants to fight the infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0331 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
