<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Heating Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is asking Congress for $600 million in
emergency assistance to help people meet heating oil costs and releasing an
additional $125 million for more immediate help to low-income families.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Americans have always pulled together to help their fellow citizens in
time of need,'' Clinton said Wednesday at a news conference. ``Now the families
of the Northeast need our help too, and we must act.''
</P>
<P>
	   His announcement came as Energy Secretary Bill Richardson met in Boston and
Bangor, Maine, with New England state energy officials and oil industry
representatives.
</P>
<P>
	   New England officials had been lobbying the president to release the
remaining low-income, or LIHEAP, assistance funds. The administration already
had released $200 million, distributed nationwide. The latest money was being
earmarked for hardest hit states, mostly in the Northeast where people rely
heavily on oil to heat their homes.
</P>
<P>
	   There are between 10 million and 14 million homes that are heated by oil,
according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
	   Northeast lawmakers also have urged the administration to release oil from
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, but Richardson has said repeatedly he has no
such intentions. The reserve is designed for supply disruptions and not to
influence prices, administration officials have maintained.
</P>
<P>
	   There is also concern that if the strategic reserve were tapped it would
make it more difficult to convince OPEC oil producers to increase production
when they meet next month to consider future production strategies. OPEC
producers a year ago agreed to reduce production by 4.3 million barrels a day,
triggering prices to soar to $30 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he ordered the release of the last $125 million in the Low
Income Home Energy Assistance Program for this year. While the money is
earmarked for the poor, Clinton said states facing the biggest heating oil
problem could adjust the requirements so some middle income families also might
qualify.
</P>
<P>
	   The LIHEAP funds are normally available to people whose incomes are no
higher than 150 percent of the poverty line, or 60 percent of the medium income
in their states.
</P>
<P>
	   But Clinton said middle income families also ``are really hurt by an
increase of $200 to $300 a month in their home heating bill'' and should be
considered eligible for assistance. States can raise the income limits, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0502 </TRAILER>
