<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Business Care Plans Under Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House-passed bill intended to make it cheaper for small
businesses to provide health insurance actually would boost premiums for some
and do little to trim the number of uninsured Americans, according to a
Congressional Budget Office report.
</P>
<P>
	   James Baumgardner, the nonpartisan CBO's acting deputy assistant director
for health policy, told the House Small Business Committee on Wednesday that the
bill would have little impact on the 43 million Americans who do not have health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   ``On balance, about 330,000 more people would be covered through small-firm
employment than would otherwise have been the case,'' he said. ``That represents
a 1.3 percent increase in coverage through small firms.''
</P>
<P>
	   The measure's chief supporter, Rep. Jim Talent, R-Mo., called the study ``an
insult to the intelligence of small business.''
</P>
<P>
	   When the bill was introduced last year, supporters said it would allow small
firms to band together to pool risks and curb costs while expanding health care
coverage for the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
	   But the report said new plans would attract healthier workers and leave
sicker individuals in the existing pool, increasing costs for those left in the
traditional insurance market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
