<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faith Groups OK'd in Federal Program  </HEADLINE>
   By ANJETTA McQUEEN AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposed changes in federal literacy programs would not
only guarantee that religious groups could participate, but ensure they wouldn't
have to cover up sacred images at program sites or hire staff that didn't adhere
to their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
	   The $500 million Even Start program, which offers tutoring to preschoolers
and literacy and job training for their parents, was approved by the House
Education and the Workforce Committee on Wednesday. The bill approved by a voice
vote was the latest in a line of recent ``charitable choice'' measures that
would permit religious groups to participate in federally funded social service
programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Trying to totally separate the faith of a society from any form of
influence is ridiculous,'' said Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., who sponsored the
changes approved by the committee.
</P>
<P>
	   He said religious groups often have the community ties to deliver social
programs such as day care, drug treatment, welfare-to-work and, in this case,
family literacy.
</P>
<P>
	   But critics say such proposals would reverse 250 years of separation of
church and state and would be tantamount to giving certain faiths governmental
approval and making religious belief public policy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The courts have never allowed churches to get tax dollars to run
educational programs,'' said Barry W. Lynn, executive director of Americans
United for Separation of Church and State. ``It is particularly appalling that a
congressional committee thinks it is OK to fund programs that practice religious
discrimination in hiring.''
</P>
<P>
	   Backers of such measures won their first major victory during the 1996
overhaul of federal welfare laws. Religious groups were allowed to deliver
services to the poor. Other programs have followed. The juvenile justice bill
that is tied up in a congressional dispute over gun control would allow
faith-based organizations to participate in programs for troubled teens.
</P>
<P>
	   Souder says the changes in the literacy bill would make groups more
comfortable in providing the services without fear of being sued or threatened
by the main program provider. For example, a Catholic church could leave a
crucifix up on a wall during tutoring or a synagogue would not have to hire
non-Jewish staff to get funding, Souder said.
</P>
<P>
	   There has been no definitive Supreme Court ruling on whether religion-based
employers are subject to federal anti-bias laws when they are making decisions
based on the tenets of an applicants' faith.
</P>
<P>
	   Some opponents worry that giving groups more leeway to practice their faiths
can have undue religious influence, particularly over children.
</P>
<P>
	   But Rep. Robert Scott, D-Va., an education committee member who opposed the
measure, said, ``The practice of federally sanctioned religious discrimination
is wrong for children, it's wrong for adults. It's so wrong, I don't think you
need to differentiate.''
</P>
<P>
	   The literacy programs were one of two renewed Wednesday under the $15
billion federal law that governs programs for children from kindergarten though
12th grade. A funding program for school districts that lose property tax
revenue to federal lands such as military bases was also sent to the full House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 0958 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gay activists cheer Bradley in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Presidential candidate Bill Bradley, criticized by some
abortion rights advocates for attacking rival Al Gore's mixed record on
abortion, stepped up his offensive today with an ad across the country
suggesting the vice president tried to straddle the issue.
<P>
	   Designed to appeal to women voters, the TV spot begins with a female
announcer saying Bradley is the only presidential candidate who "has been
pro-choice for everyone, all the time." It includes images of women at a rally
and Bradley mixing with crowds.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the kind of issue that you can't straddle," Bradley says in the ad.
"You can't be on both sides. You have to decide which side you're on. Are you
anti-choice or are you pro-choice."
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., a Bradley supporter who unveiled the ad in
Washington, said it would begin airing Friday in all the states voting on the
two biggest presidential primary days - March 7 and March 14. They include New
York, California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League gave
its endorsement to Gore, breaking its tradition of neutrality during the
primaries. The group's leaders said both Democratic candidates support abortion
rights but complained that Bradley was using abortion as a political wedge to
divide voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Eshoo acknowledged that Gore supports abortion rights but said he came to
that position years behind Bradley. In a core Democratic issue like abortion,
she said, "the clarity, the consistency is important."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley is also challenging Gore for gay voters, picking up support during
two days of barnstorming New York state.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Bradley has pushed the envelope on gay rights to the top of the
mainstream political dialogue in this nation," said Ethan Geto, a popular mentor
to New York gay activists, who introduced Bradley Wednesday evening at the
Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   He cited Bradley's early opposition to President Clinton's "don't ask, don't
tell" policy on gays in the military, his call for adoption rights for gay
couples and his proposal to expand protections of the 1964 Civil Rights Act to
include sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley was taking his campaign bus to Massachusetts, Rhode Island and
Connecticut as well as making additional stops in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Addressing 200 people packed into a meeting room and watching on video in an
overflow room, Bradley detailed Wednesday evening why he believes openly gay
people should be able to serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you're a gay American, you can serve openly in the Congress, in the
judiciary, in the Treasury Department, in the White House," Bradley said. "You
ought to be able to serve openly in the military."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore called in December for an end to the current policy on gays in the
military. He also last week picked up the endorsement of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian rights group. On Wednesday, Gore
was endorsed by a New York gay rights group, Empire State Pride Agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, running as an anti-Washington outsider despite 18 years in the
Senate, asked reporters rhetorically whether that group is based in Washington.
It is.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley continues to accuse Gore of using "scare tactics" to discredit his
health care plan. Gore says Bradley's plan to replace Medicaid with a system of
subsidies would leave thousands of people with diseases such as AIDS without
coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   In visits to Buffalo and Rochester earlier Tuesday, Bradley said Gore
ignored western New York and other places left out of the economic boom while
courting voters elsewhere for the big March 7 primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   Going all out in New York, one of the biggest March 7 prizes, Bradley
portrayed Gore as a latecomer to an area that has not shared deeply in the past
decade's economic good times.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley told students in Rochester that federal formulas should be adjusted
so New York gets a better return on its tax dollar. But shifting formulas to
help New York could reduce federal funding to places in the South and West -
including California, the biggest delegate target on March 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
