<HEADLINE> Volpe to testify as defense begins Louima trial case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The prosecution today rested its case against three
police officers who allegedly obstructed an investigation into the brutal Abner
Louima assault, setting the stage for the victim's torturer to testify.
<P>
	   Justin Volpe, the ex-police officer and now prison inmate, was due on the
stand later today as the leadoff witness for the defense, said defense attorney
Ronald Fischetti.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution ended its presentation in U.S. District Court by focusing on
phone records showing the contacts between the accused officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad briefly recalled an FBI agent who has
testified that the trio made an unusual number of calls to each other in the
days after Volpe sodomized the Haitian immigrant with a broken broomstick in a
precinct bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Brought from prison, where he is serving 30 years for violating Louima's
civil rights, Volpe is expected to say - as he did after his sentencing last
year - that Charles Schwarz was not the "second officer" in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, 34, Thomas Bruder, 33, and Thomas Wiese, 36, are accused of
conspiring to obstruct justice by claiming Schwarz was never in the bathroom
when Volpe assaulted Louima. Schwarz was convicted last year of violating
Louima's civil rights by holding him down during the attack. Wiese says it was
he who entered the room briefly during the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   FBI agent Joseph Foelsch testified there were 59 calls involving the trio
and a few other officers in the four days after the Aug. 9, 1997, incident -
more than seven times as many contacts as they had by phone in the previous 10
weeks. The number of calls reached 150 over the next 2 1/2 months, Foelsch said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors contend that the three defendants, seeking to conceal Schwarz's
role, coordinated their stories in a private meeting and the many phone calls,
while appealing to other 70th Precinct cops to keep silent.
</P>
<P>
	   Police union trustee Michael Immitt testified earlier that he urged cops at
several roll calls not to discuss the case, but denied trying to impede the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   As one of its last witnesses, the prosecution called Anthony Abbate, a
former stationhouse crony of Schwarz who was fired from the police department in
1996 for verbally abusing a female officer during an argument and then lying
about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
	   Abbate, a participant with Schwarz or Wiese in 36 calls on the FBI list,
said he was trying to give support to Schwarz as a friend, but denied suggesting
that they concoct a scenario that put Wiese in the bathroom in the bathroom with
Volpe and Louima, instead of Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   Abbate acknowledged telling a federal grand jury in early 1998 that Schwarz
had told him that he, Schwarz, escorted Louima to the lavatory. But he quoted
Wiese as having "repeated, over and over, that Schwarz was never in the
bathroom."
</P>
<P>
	   Abbate, who now works as a construction laborer, said he had been falsely
accused in the incident that led to his being dismissed from the force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
