<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 14.56 After 110-Point Gain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices swung sharply in early trading today after
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said inflation is still a threat to the
economy. Greenspan made his warning despite a government report that indicated
inflation is under control.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 14.56 at 10,549.74 after having been up 110 points soon after
the market opened.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were slightly higher. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 16.56 at 4,428.89, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 0.57 at
1,376.44.
</P>
<P>
	   Stock prices initially rose after a government report today said wholesale
prices held steady in January as a sharp decline in cigarette prices offset
rising costs for gasoline, heating oil and other energy products. The
performance was a better showing on inflation than analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Dow fell immediately after Greenspan said the economic expansion
could not last unless its grow rate slows.
</P>
<P>
	   Presenting the Fed's twice-a-year report on the economy to Congress,
Greenspan said economic conditions are remarkable, with the nine-year-long
expansion turning in exceptionally rapid growth that has driven unemployment to
a 30-year low of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Greenspan attributed to his worries about the economy to the tight labor
markets and fears that workers will begin to demand higher wages that could set
off inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The market interpreted his comments as implying that the central bank is
likely to raise interest rates again-- it has already done four times since
June.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 135.8 million shares, down from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index rose 5.95 to 553.71.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1 percent. In afternoon trading,
Germany's DAX index was up 1.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.6 percent,
and France's CAC-40 was up 2.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
