<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani heads to far north to press oil price issue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, running for the Senate
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, says he will continue touring the state and
blasting her husband until he turns on the taps to the nation's oil reserves to
reduce home heating oil prices.
<P>
	   Giuliani headed to New York's frigid, far north Wednesday to continue his
attack on President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to take this message throughout the state of New York." the New
York City mayor said. "We're going to keep it up every day until he eventually
releases some of the oil reserves."
</P>
<P>
	   "What's happening right now to our home heating oil prices is outrageous,"
Giuliani told a group of Republican officials and supporters at a Plattsburgh
restaurant as snow fell outside and the temperature hovered in the 20s.
</P>
<P>
	   "He could stand up to OPEC and he's refusing to do that," Giuliani added.
</P>
<P>
	   Beginning last weekend, Giuliani began lambasting the president for refusing
to dip into the nation's strategic oil reserves to ease the price crunch on
consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, the mayor's campaign team unveiled a radio ad to run statewide
in which he says: "Mister President, why don't you feel our pain? Release the
oil."
</P>
<P>
	   The radio ad was supposed to have ended this week, but the mayor's team has
decided it will continue to run until at least the middle of next week, possibly
augmented by a new version.
</P>
<P>
	   While the first lady has also called for using some of the oil reserves to
help reduce prices, Giuliani aides believe that by attacking her husband they
can boost the mayor's standing while hurting Clinton's Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is an example of an issue that really unites the entire state. It
affects people in Brooklyn and in Buffalo," Giuliani campaign manager Bruce
Teitelbaum said. "We've seen the mayor doing his job, advocating for the people
of the city - that's his responsibility now - but also advocating on behalf of
people all across the state."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani said that with oil prices rising, the OPEC countries were reaping
huge profits.
</P>
<P>
	   "Think of where that money is coming from. It's coming from you," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott Tetreault, owner of Hitchcock's restaurant where Giuliani's
Plattsburgh event was held, said the rapidly rising cost of fuel oil had "hurt
our business. A lot of our patrons, who typically pay $200 a month (for fuel
oil) are now paying $280, $320 or $350. That one or two nights a week they come
out for happy hour or dinner, they're not coming out."
</P>
<P>
	   Tetreault, who opened his restaurant in June, said that while he was a
political independent who tried to stay neutral in politics, "I would vote for
Rudy over Hillary ... I'm just uncomfortable with the fact that she's coming to
an area she's never lived in before to run for Senate."
</P>
<P>
	   "This may be Clinton County, but we vote Republican and we'll do that again
in November," state Assemblyman Chris Ortloff, a local Clinton County
Republican, said as he introduced Giuliani to the more than four dozen on hand
for the mayor's appearance.
</P>
<P>
	   Following his news conference with Republican officials in Plattsburgh, just
south of the Canadian border, Giuliani flew to Syracuse for a similar event.
</P>
<P>
	   With OPEC countries limiting production, the cost of home heating oil in New
York has risen from a statewide average of 90.6 cents a gallon in February of
last year to $2.01 a gallon as of last week. It had dipped to about $1.71 a
gallon on average by early this week as East Coast supplies improved somewhat.
The Northeast has been hardest hit by the price increases.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton announced Wednesday, just before Giuliani's event, that he
was making another $120 million available to help poor people nationwide pay
their heating oil bills. Of that, $36.6 million goes to New York where his wife
is running for the Senate. In all, Clinton has released $325 million of such
funding since the heating oil crisis began, $73.6 million of which has gone to
New York.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani said such action would help the poor, he said it would also
serve to further line OPEC's pockets and "will not help the middle-class."
</P>
<P>
	   The administration has thus far refused to tap into the strategic oil
reserves despite calls for it to do so from a bipartisan group of state
officials and members of Congress, including Sen. Charles Schumer, a New York
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
	   The president said Wednesday that he wouldn't rule out using the petroleum
reserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
