<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton and Gore to campaign together  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore will campaign
together in New York for the first time this year as they appeal Sunday to the
state's minority voters who could be crucial to them both, aides said today.
<P>
	   The two will appear together at a church service Sunday morning that is a
highlight of the annual weekend gathering in Albany of the state Legislature's
black and Hispanic legislative caucus. Both are expected to speak at the
service.
</P>
<P>
	   The caucus weekend annually brings together hundreds of the state's top
black and Hispanic leaders. The minority community in New York is an
increasingly powerful voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
	   A big test of that minority voting power comes in the state's March 7
presidential primary, considered a major showdown for Gore and former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley. Both have launched major appeals to minorities in their bids
for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that presidential candidate Gore and Senate candidate Clinton
haven't yet campaigned together in New York has raised some eyebrows. It
prompted a front-page article in today's editions of The New York Times that
carried the headline: "Gore and Mrs. Clinton Keeping A Wary Distance as
Candidates."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said today that there was no
intentional distancing of the two candidates. Aides to Gore said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, one Gore adviser, speaking on condition of anonymity, said today
that "for the next 19 days (until the New York primary), she helps us
tremendously. Her numbers are just off the charts with Democratic primary
voters."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked recently why they hadn't been campaigning together, Gore told one
television interviewer that, "It's a matter of scheduling. Not just me, but also
her."
</P>
<P>
	   Both have made it clear that they feel they must step out of the shadow of
President Clinton. As part of that effort, Hillary Rodham Clinton has become
simply "Hillary" in campaign posters and news releases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
