<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 14.56; Nasdaq Up 56.14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks fell today after Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan indicated the central bank will raise interest rates again to
slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   But technology stocks were unmoved, and headed close to record territory.
</P>
<P>
	   At midmorning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down
14.56 at 10,549.74.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index was up 56.14
at 4,483.89, just 5 points shy of its record close set a week ago. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.01 at 1,386.66.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial stocks were hurt by the prospect of higher interest rates. Dow
component American Express fell 5 7/16 to 148. Wal-Mart, the nation's biggest
retailer, was down 4 to 48 3/4.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow initially rose more than 110 points on a smaller-than-expected rise
in wholesale prices, but dropped immediately after Greenspan said the nation's
economic expansion could not last unless its grow rate slows.
</P>
<P>
	   Presenting the Fed's twice-a-year report on the economy to Congress,
Greenspan said the Fed's four quarter-point increases in the federal funds rate
over the past eight months have had little impact in slowing the economy.
Greenspan attributed his concerns about the economy to the tight labor markets
and fears that workers will begin to demand higher wages that could set off
inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The market interpreted his comments as implying that the central bank is
likely to raise interest rates again-- it has already done four times since
June.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had good news on inflation front but Mr. Greenspan's commentary sure
indicated there more than one interest rate hike to come and that's not what
market wanted to hear," said Barry Hyman, chief market strategist at Ehrenkrantz
King Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
	   But while interest rate sensitive stocks on the Dow and the S&AMP;P were hurt by
Greenspan's comments, Hyman noted the technology-dominated Nasdaq kept rising.
"The Nasdaq is a different ball game. It's not a credit sensitive sector," he
said
</P>
<P>
	   Greenspan's comments came after a government report today said wholesale
prices held steady in January as a sharp decline in cigarette prices offset
rising costs for gasoline, heating oil and other energy products. The
performance was a better showing on inflation than analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 324.8 million shares, up from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index rose 5.17 to 552.93.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
