<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Offers Help on China Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BEIJING (AP) -- With the chief of the World Trade Organization offering to
facilitate China's entry into the free-traders' club, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
hoped Thursday for a breakthrough in negotiations with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
	   WTO chief Mike Moore and Zhu agreed that China's absence from the WTO left
the world trade body incomplete, Chinese state media reported.
</P>
<P>
	   China is in the closing stages of a 14-year effort to join world trade's top
rule-making body, but still needs to needs to finalize agreements with several
nations and the European Union before it can join. EU and Chinese negotiators
will reopen talks Monday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
	   "We hope that the two sides can reach an understanding during the talks,"
the Xinhua News Agency quoted Zhu as telling Moore.
</P>
<P>
	   On his arrival in Beijing, Moore said his goal was to bring all sides closer
together.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are facilitators here. The decisions are made by the members of the WTO,
but we believe it will be a splendid thing for the world. It will be good for
China and good for everybody," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
