<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain the choice of Republicans in March, all voters in November  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) - A new poll shows Sen. John McCain is the big
favorite among Connecticut Republicans and Al Gore is tops with state Democrats
less than three weeks before the state's presidential primary.
<P>
	   The Quinnipiac College poll released today found that among likely
Republican primary voters surveyed, McCain led Texas Gov. George W. Bush 52
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Among Democrats who said they were likely to vote in the March 7 primary,
Gore leads former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, 49 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll indicates that among all registered voters, McCain is the favorite
in matchups for the presidency in November.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was favored 55 percent to 33 percent over Gore, and 50 percent to 34
percent over Bradley, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
	   "McCain clearly got a big bounce out of New Hampshire," poll director
Douglas Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwartz said Gov. John G. Rowland's endorsement of Bush hasn't carried much
weight with voters, a trend that he's noticed in other states.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's very tough for governor's to have an impact," he said. "The
governors don't carry as much weight as is often attributed to them."
</P>
<P>
	   In matchups pitting Bush against the Democratic candidates, Gore edges out
the Republican candidate 45 percent to 42 percent while Bradley tallies 48
percent to Bush's 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The survey of 1,365 Connecticut registered voters was conducted Feb. 9-15
and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points. The survey
includes 426 likely Democratic primary voters with a margin of error of 5
percent, and 333 likely Republican primary voters with a margin of error of plus
or minus just above 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
