<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Cited in Nazi Labor Talks  </HEADLINE>
   By COLLEEN BARRY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- U.S. and German envoys leading talks on establishing a $5
billion fund for Nazi-era forced and slave laborers reported significant
progress today toward an agreement on how to divide the money.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief German negotiator Otto Lambsdorff and U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Stuart Eizenstat expressed confidence that negotiators could reach an agreement
during the next round of talks in Washington in March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are on the brink of achieving something truly historic,'' Eizenstat
said. ``We all agreed on the importance of accelerating the discussions'' to
ensure that aging survivors receive compensation.
</P>
<P>
	   Estimates of the number of people who could benefit from the fund run to as
many as 2.3 million people, mostly non-Jews from eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   All sides agreed that the bulk of the fund will be reserved for compensating
forced and slave laborers, although Eizenstat said serious differences remained
on how the funds would be divided.
</P>
<P>
	   The German government is recommending that $3.85 billion be reserved for
slave and forced laborers, $500 million be used to compensate people whose
property was seized by the Nazis and an equal sum to establish a foundation for
future academic and humanitarian projects and exchanges. The balance, about $150
million, would go toward administrative and legal fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Lambsdorff defended the $500 million for the foundation in an interview
Wednesday with Der Tagesspiegel newspaper, and industry leaders also said that
amount was not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
	   Manfred Gentz, chief financial officer at DaimlerChrysler and the industry's
lead negotiator, was quoted by the newspaper as saying that the foundation was
possibly even more important than the payments to individuals because it would
be ``in the future directed at hindering offenses against human rights.''
</P>
<P>
	   German industry and the government agreed in December to contribute equal
shares to the $5 billion fund to compensate long-forgotten Nazi victims. Though
the agreement was hailed as a breakthrough, negotiations to actually launch the
project have been painstaking.
</P>
<P>
	   The eastern and central European governments that are in the talks have
generally accepted that the entire fund will not be used for compensating forced
laborers, however they have expressed concern about the size of the fund for
academic and humanitarian projects.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter released Wednesday, the governments of Belarus, Poland, Russia,
Ukraine and the Czech Republic warned U.S. and German envoys that money must not
be taken away from the remaining $4.5 billion for other claims.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Any decrease in that amount would mean that the payments to slave and
forced laborers would become even less than symbolic or that some categories of
victims would have to be excluded from payments,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Eizenstat appealed to a German parliament committee Wednesday to pass a law
creating the compensation fund in accordance with the agreements reached by the
negotiators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1215 </TRAILER>
