<HEADLINE> NATO Cmdr. Warns Congress on Troops  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States should brace for keeping its troops in
Bosnia and Kosovo indefinitely as long as Slobodan Milosevic holds power in
Yugoslavia, the outgoing supreme NATO commander cautioned Congress today.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Wesley Clark brushed off repeated questions on when Americans might
expect to see the peacekeeping troops brought home for good.
</P>
<P>
	   Except for being driven from Kosovo, Milosevic's forces and military
equipment suffered little damage from last year's 78-day NATO bombardment, Clark
said. Now, Milosevic is seeking to consolidate his authority and should be
regarded as continuing to pose a threat to the Balkans, the general added.
</P>
<P>
	   Until Milosvevic is removed from power and brought to trial on war crime
charges, ``We're not going to see a resolution of the problem,'' Clark told the
House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark said he did not want to suggest there wouldn't be further troop
reductions in both Bosnia and Kosovo but he declined to voice any optimism for
ending the U.S. military presence in either place.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me go out on a limb and give you my personal opinion,'' the retiring
four-star general said. ``We're not going to be able to complete that mission
and wipe our hands of responsibility until that regime in Belgrade is replaced
by a democratic government.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. troops have served in Bosnia since late 1995 and now number about
5,600. Two deadlines set by President Clinton for the return of the troops have
come and gone, and there is no longer a target date for their departure. All
told there are about 24,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia, mostly from NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 50,000 peace implementation forces in Kosovo, about 6,000 are
Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark is leaving his European post in April, two months earlier than
planned, to accommodate his successor, Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston, who would
have had to retire had he not taken the promotion by May.
</P>
<P>
	   Members of Congress have been increasingly critical about the open-ended
U.S. commitment in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The introduction of ground forces to a peacekeeping operation in Kosovo
and the continuing mission in Bosnia has had a significant negative impact on
the Army,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., the committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark would not add his voice to rising complaints by U.S. policy- makers --
including Defense Secretary William Cohen -- that European allies haven't been
shouldering enough of the financial burden for the defense of Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a political imperative on both sides of the Atlantic that Europe do
more to share the burden,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said European countries are willing to pay more in the future -- and
already contribute the majority of peacekeeping troops in both Bosnia and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   Furthermore, he said, the United States continues to have ``vital interests
in Europe. That's the reality. We learned that lesson after World War II.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
