<HEADLINE> Dow Down 104.86; Nasdaq Up 41.66  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks fell sharply today after Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan indicated the central bank will raise interest rates
again to slow the economy. Technology stocks were unmoved, and headed higher.
</P>
<P>
	   At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 104.86 at
10,456.55.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was up 41.66 at 4,469.31, just 16 points shy of
its record close set a week ago. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 7.30
at 1,380.37.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow initially rose more than 110 points on a smaller-than-expected rise
in wholesale prices, but dropped immediately after Greenspan said the nation's
economic expansion could not last unless its grow rate slows.
</P>
<P>
	   Presenting his twice-a-year report on the economy to Congress, Greenspan
said the Fed's four quarter-point increases in the federal funds rate over the
past eight months have had little impact in slowing the economy. Greenspan
attributed his concerns about the economy to the tight labor markets and the
possibility that workers will begin to demand higher wages that could set off
inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The market interpreted his comments as implying that the central bank is
likely to raise interest rates again-- as it has already done four times since
June.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had good news on inflation front but Mr. Greenspan's commentary sure
indicated there more than one interest rate hike to come and that's not what
market wanted to hear," said Barry Hyman, chief market strategist at Ehrenkrantz
King Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial stocks were hurt by the prospect of higher interest rates. Dow
component American Express fell 7 3/16 to 146. Wal-Mart, the nation's biggest
retailer, was down 4 to 48 3/4.
</P>
<P>
	   But while interest rate sensitive stocks were hurt by Greenspan's comments,
Hyman noted the technology-dominated Nasdaq kept rising. "The Nasdaq is a
different ball game. It's not a credit-sensitive sector," he said
</P>
<P>
	   Intel, up 2 9/16 to 110 and biotech giant Amgen, up 3  1/2 to 73, powered
the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
	   Greenspan's comments came after a government report today said wholesale
prices held steady in January as a sharp decline in cigarette prices offset
rising costs for gasoline, heating oil and other energy products. The
performance was a better showing on inflation than analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 460.6 million shares, up from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index, reflecting the performance of smaller-company
stocks, rose 5.14 to 552.90.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
