<HEADLINE> Ahern: Britain Got Arms Proposal  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Just hours before Britain withdrew powers from Northern
Ireland's new administration, the British government had received a disarmament
proposal from the IRA, Ireland's prime minister said today.
</P>
<P>
	   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern said his government received details of a
secret Irish Republican Army proposal about 12 hours before Britain announced it
would reimpose ``direct rule'' in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he passed those details immediately to British Prime Minister Tony
Blair in London, contradicting claims Britain did not know about any IRA
disarmament hints in advance of suspending the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
	   Ahern's remarks added to the controversy surrounding Britain's decision last
week to disable the 2-month-old power-sharing Cabinet in Belfast, the intended
centerpiece of the 1998 Good Friday peace accord.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain has defended its action on the grounds that the IRA had not yet
pledged to disarm in line with a deal that formed the Cabinet in December.
</P>
<P>
	   The coalition's essential Protestant participant, the Ulster Unionists, had
threatened to resign its posts within the four-party Cabinet unless action was
taken.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not going to pretend that this is not a difficult situation, because
it is,'' Blair said Wednesday night after he and Ahern spoke together to key
Northern Irish parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Their diplomacy inside Blair's London residence failed to move either the
IRA-linked Sinn Fein party or the Ulster Unionists, both of whom remained
entrenched on opposite sides of an argument over when, if ever, the outlawed IRA
should disarm in support of the Good Friday agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ball is still firmly in their court,'' said Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble, who departed today for several days of speaking engagements in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sinn Fein can't make peace on our own,'' countered Gerry Adams, that
party's leader.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ulster Unionists agreed in November to drop their demand for some IRA
disarmament in advance of the Cabinet's formation -- but only in expectation the
IRA would disarm in response. The outlawed group offered no firm commitments to
a disarmament commission last month, triggering the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's reaction provoked the IRA -- which had offered a vague but
promising proposal to the commission -- to retaliate by retracting that
submission and breaking off contact with disarmament representatives.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview published today in the weekly IRA-Sinn Fein newspaper,
Republican News, an IRA spokesman said it was unlikely the group would reopen
disarmament talks.
</P>
<P>
	   The unidentified spokesman also declined to spell out what the IRA's
last-minute offer had been.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked whether the IRA would resume talks with the disarmament commission,
the spokesman was quoted as saying, ``What is the point engaging with a body
which the British government has rendered irrelevant?''
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, President Clinton said it was ``very unfortunate'' the IRA
hadn't maintained contact with the commission, but cited the apparent strength
of the IRA's 1997 cease-fire as a bright spot.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The IRA has given no indication whatever that they will revert to
violence,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
