<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccine Panel Changes Recommendation  </HEADLINE>
    By JAMES PILCHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- In a sign that cost is becoming a factor in making
immunization policy, a government advisory committee has changed its initial
recommendation and will require fewer children to receive an expensive vaccine.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center for Disease Control and Prevention's Advisory Committee on
Immunization Policy recommended that the vaccine Prevnar be administered to all
children under 2, and given to those who are now age 2 to 5 only if they are at
high risk of contracting illnesses such as meningitis.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee had originally voted in October to recommend Prevnar for all
children under 5. Wednesday's 7-4 to change the recommendation came after a
lengthy discussion of cost implications that included a presentation from a
representative of health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
	   The recommendation for at-risk children affects those who are 2 to 5 now,
but eventually all children, except for those who slipped through the cracks,
will have received the shots by their second birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee recommended that black, native American or Eskimo children who
are now 2 to 5 be added to mandatory schedules because they are at higher risk.
It also recommended that the vaccine be mandatory for children ages 2-5 who have
sickle cell anemia, HIV or other immunodeficient diseases.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee said doctors should consider vaccinations for children now 2
to 5 who have had frequent ear infections, are socially or economically
disadvantaged or attend group child care. But vaccinations would not be
mandatory for children in these categories.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only the second time the committee has ever debated the potential
economic impact of a vaccine, even while some committee members felt the matter
shouldn't even be considered.
</P>
<P>
	   "This could save lives no matter what the age or the cost, and the
discussion about at what price this becomes reasonable is indecipherable to me,"
said Dr. Paul Offit, chief of infectious diseases at the Children's Hospital of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to recommend it first and figure out how to pay for it second," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other committee members argued about realities faced by the public and
private sector alike, especially with the hefty price tag of the vaccine. The
federal government pays for about half of all immunizations.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're having to look at cost more and more," said Dr. John Modlin, the
committee's chairman and a professor of pediatric medicine at Dartmouth
University. "We know (Prevnar) will be expensive in the short term, but over the
long haul ... we could see a lowering of pediatric health costs as a result of
this."
</P>
<P>
	   Federal approval of the vaccine is expected this week. Manufacturer American
Home Products Inc. plans to begin marketing Prevnar this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   Prevnar fights the bacterium streptococcus pneumoniae -- the leading cause
of pneumonia, meningitis and the millions of ear infections that lead to crammed
pediatrician waiting rooms every year.
</P>
<P>
	   According to a study, the vaccine reduced ear infections by 9 percent.
Doctor visits by those who were diagnosed as having chronic ear infections and
took the vaccine were down 20 percent, and there was a 20 percent reduction in
the number of children who needed tube implants to fight the infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1257 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Indicate Hot GOP Contest  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When letter carrier Bill Wilson of Anderson, S.C., talks
to people on his rounds he hears lots of chatter about the state's GOP
presidential primary from Republicans, independents and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think there will be quite a bit of voting by independents and Democrats,
just from delivering mail and talking to people,'' said Wilson, a Republican.
``Just from walking the streets. I see a lot of McCain and Bush signs in the
yards.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson's perception is backed up by polls suggesting that turnout Saturday
will be the highest of any GOP presidential primary in the state. Polls and
campaign-watchers are finding plenty of enthusiasm for Sen. John McCain and an
energized GOP base for Gov. George W. Bush -- elements for a hot contest,
indeed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are ignited,'' Clemson University political scientist David Woodard
said of core Republicans rallying for Bush. ``They are glowing in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
	   State Republican officials have printed an additional 400,000 ballots to be
sure they have enough.
</P>
<P>
	   Turnout in the 1996 Republican primary was 276,000 and a third of the voters
identified themselves as independents or Democrats, according to exit polls.
State GOP director J. Sam Daniels said he expects more than 300,000 voters this
time, and possibly many more.
</P>
<P>
	   In polls out Wednesday and today, Bush had a solid lead among Republicans
while McCain held a slightly bigger margin among independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palmetto Poll by Clemson University released today showed the two in a
very close race. Bush led McCain 49 percent to 31 percent among core Republican
voters, described as those who voted in at least two of the past three GOP
primaries. But McCain was favored by likely Democratic crossover voters, 49
percent to 39 percent. The poll included 450 people in each of the voter groups
and had an error margin of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points, larger for
subgroups.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and McCain were in a dead heat in a Los Angeles Times poll out early
this week in which 45 percent of the respondents were non-Republicans. In polls
with a smaller sampling of non-Republicans -- 40 percent -- Bush has held a slim
lead or was in a dead heat with McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Among them, a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll had Bush slightly ahead and a Zogby
poll had them essentially tied.
</P>
<P>
	   An American Research Group poll of 600 likely voters gave Bush 47 percent
and McCain 41 percent, with 7 percent undecided. The poll, also with 40 percent
non-Republicans, was taken Sunday through Tuesday and had an error margin of
plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   A Mason-Dixon poll done for media outlets in South Carolina had the race
essentially tied, Bush with 45 percent and McCain with 42 percent with a 4 point
error margin.
</P>
<P>
	   The third candidate in the race, Alan Keyes, has been in single digits.
</P>
<P>
	   Woodard, co-director of the Palmetto Poll, said a question for McCain is
whether all the enthusiasm for him among non-Republicans will translate into a
strong turnout on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   Weather could be a big factor, he said, because McCain needs a high turnout
from those less accustomed to voting in a GOP primary. If it rains, ``then God
wants George Bush'' to win, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   While many non-Republicans are expected to vote, some say the negative turn
of the campaign has cooled their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
	   Shirley Walker, a 64-year-old Democrat and foster mother from Walterboro, is
still considering whether to vote and admits to being bothered by the campaign
tactics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If a person is capable and honest, they shouldn't have to do that if they
run for president,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservative Republican enthusiasm for Bush has grown along with that of
moderates, independents and some Democrats for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm a little concerned about the crossover Democrats trying to influence
the election,'' said salesman Guy Stanley Orr of Simpsonville.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When the campaign first started, I wasn't sure how I felt about Bush,''
Orr said. ``But as I listened to him, he has answered all the questions I have
at this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
