<HEADLINE> Descendant of Cinque to speak at Amistad launch  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MYSTIC, Conn. (AP) - The great-grandson of Cinque, the African who led a
revolt aboard the slave ship Amistad, will be the keynote speaker during the
launch of a replica of the schooner next month.
<P>
	   Amistad America Inc. chose Samuel H. Pieh over other prominent black leaders
to speak at the launch ceremony March 25, said the group's executive director,
R. Christopher Cloud.
</P>
<P>
	   "It just hit me. Why am I chasing people who would be appropriate but don't
have a relationship with this story?" Cloud said. "I said, 'Let's call him.' He
was honored to do it. Having him here will be terrific."
</P>
<P>
	   Pieh, 51, was born in Sierra Leone and now lives in Memphis, Tenn. He runs
Mid-South Africa Link, an organization that works to improve relations between
Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Pieh said Wednesday he is "very much humbled and honored" to have been asked
to speak.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would like to commend the American citizens who have recognized the good
in a human being no matter where they are from," he said. "The Connecticut
community has demonstrated over and over their belief and commitment to
tolerance, their great diversity and their commitment to human rights and
justice."
</P>
<P>
	   His ancestor was Singe Pieh, also known as Cinque, who in 1839 took over the
slave ship with 52 fellow Africans as they were being transported along the
coast of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   The Africans were eventually captured, taken to New London and then jailed
in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Supreme Court eventually agreed with a lower court decision that
the Africans who had survived the ordeal were free.
</P>
<P>
	   Director Steven Spielberg made the Amistad story into a movie in 1997. Pieh
portrayed the oldest captive in the movie and was a language coach for the other
actors.
</P>
<P>
	   At Mystic Seaport, a $2.8 million, 77-foot-long full-scale replica of the
Spanish ship is being built using some 19th-century tools and traditions.
Amistad America wants to use the ship as a floating laboratory to teach the
Amistad story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
