<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film, magazine report put staid Wesleyan to test  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) - Wesleyan University's image as something of a
staid liberal arts school is being put to the test with a campus pitch for a sex
film and a prominent mention in Hustler magazine.
<P>
	   Would-be student filmmaker Brian Brown recently proposed a "mockumentary"
about sex on campus, and figured on using local talent for his project.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown trolled for cast members with posters splashed around campus. The
posters said actors and actresses would "get paid to get laid."
</P>
<P>
	   Eleven students agreed to be part of the movie, including scenes with
explicit sexual content. The film's working title was "Wesporn."
</P>
<P>
	   Somebody else responded to the cast call, however - university President
Douglas J. Bennet.
</P>
<P>
	   After a tense meeting between Bennet and Brown, the would-be filmmaker
acceded to Bennet's request that he drop the project.
</P>
<P>
	   A university spokesman said Wednesday that Bennet had several concerns about
the project, including the possibility that the posters themselves represented a
threat to the safety of students.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown said he suspects Bennet's concern is more for the university's image.
</P>
<P>
	   "At some level," Brown said, "he may be right that 'Wesporn' isn't the best
publicity for the school."
</P>
<P>
	   However, the project may not be dead. On Wednesday, Brown said he would
revive the film if a poll in the college newspaper reveals broad student
support.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the latest edition of Hustler magazine carries a salacious salute
to Wesleyan.
</P>
<P>
	   The magazine, known for graphic sexual content, reports on a pornography
class that was offered to Wesleyan students last year.
</P>
<P>
	   An article in the April issue entitled "Porn 101" mentions the Wesleyan
course and classes offered at other major universities.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wesleyan course, entitled "Pornography: Writing of Prostitutes," was
taught last year by Professor Hope Weissman.
</P>
<P>
	   The course, which examined pornography as a cultural and political practice,
became talk show fodder because of its subject matter and a final project in
which students produced their own pornography.
</P>
<P>
	   The class is not being offered this year; Weissman is on sabbatical. She has
said she may offer it again when she returns to campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
