<HEADLINE> Report: Japan Cops Admit Kidnap Lie  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese police on Thursday admitted they lied in a press
release that said they found a woman who had been abducted and confined for nine
years, when in fact she was discovered by health workers, a news report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The police in Niigata, about 160 miles northwest of Tokyo, also acknowledged
they ignored requests for assistance from the workers who found the 19-year-old
woman in the home of her kidnapper, Kyodo News said.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, 37-year-old Nobuyuki Sato, was arrested on suspicion of
abducting Fusako Sano, now 19, and imprisoning her in his second-floor room.
</P>
<P>
	   Sano was a 9-year-old in 1990 when she was abducted off the street. She says
she never left the second floor of kidnapper's house during her captivity.
</P>
<P>
	   The Kyodo report said health officials went to Sato's home when they
received a call from his mother that he was being violent.
</P>
<P>
	   The officials called the police for help when they found Sano in the
second-floor room, but were told to deal with the situation themselves, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said in their press release that they found Sano after the two turned
up at a hospital, when in fact they had been taken there by the workers, Kyodo
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials were not available for comment on the report late Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
