<HEADLINE> Firefighter Held for Noshing Nude  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Restaurant owners trying to figure out who was stealing the
stock installed video cameras that allegedly caught their landlord downing
expensive food and wine in the place after hours -- in the nude.
</P>
<P>
	   Albert Hohmann, a city firefighter, has been suspended without pay after
being arrested on charges including burglary, petty larceny and criminal
mischief, Fire Department spokesman Michael Regan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Hohmann, 46, owns a picturesque 100-year-old house on Staten Island and
lives on the second floor, leasing the first floor and basement to the
Tottenville Inn.
</P>
<P>
	   Michelle Macula, a partner in the restaurant, said it had been having theft
problems since the restaurant opened. At first, she and her partner reviewed
only portions of surveillance tapes recorded during business hours.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Then, in August, we rewound the tapes too far and we saw him just walking
around naked,'' she said. ``He went behind the bar and made himself a drink.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said she turned over tapes of his late-night raids to police after a
complaint lodged to him by her lawyer didn't stop the problem.
</P>
<P>
	   After downing vintage wines and taking expensive cuts of meat and seafood,
Hohmann would commit minor acts of vandalism, Macula said. The last incident
happened Friday when he was videotaped turning on water taps and flooding the
restaurant. Hohmann, a 10-year fire department veteran, was arrested later that
day.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Hohmann was the landlord, he had no legal right to be in the
restaurant when it was closed, the district attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hohmann could not immediately be reached for comment Thursday morning. No
one answered the phone at his home.
</P>
</TEXT>
