<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House To Summon Tax-Scheme Suspects  </HEADLINE>
    By LARRY NEUMEISTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A former Bank of New York executive and her husband pleaded
guilty to helping Russian bankers launder more than $7 billion in one of the
biggest such schemes in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucy Edwards, 41, and Peter Berlin, 46, each told a federal judge Wednesday
how they used her position as a vice president in the bank's Eastern European
division to help setup illegal accounts for Russian bankers whose clients wanted
to escape taxes and erase the trail of their income.
</P>
<P>
	   The pleas came a day after the couple surrendered to the FBI after flying to
New York from London, where they had been living.
</P>
<P>
	   They could face up to 10 years in prison at sentencing May 3 but could get
lesser sentences by identifying others involved. They also agreed to surrender
more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington today, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, said he planned to subpoena Edwards and Berlin to testify about the
flow of money out of Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bank of New York case "represents a verifiable incident where the
financial system has been corrupted," Leach said in a statement. "It is critical
to review whether this is an (aberration) ... or symbolic of an endemic problem
in the international banking system."
</P>
<P>
	   The Banking Committee held hearings on the case in September at which Bank
of New York Chairman Thomas A. Renyi defended the bank's reputation but
acknowledged "a lapse" by its internal supervisors in allowing questionable
accounts to stay open. Some key figures in the investigation have declined to
testify voluntarily before the panel.
</P>
<P>
	   T. Barry Kingham, an attorney for Edwards and Berlin, said the couple will
keep cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
	   "They are anxious to fulfill their obligations here and resume a normal
life," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Their pleas were the first major admissions of wrongdoing since the
investigation caused an international scandal last August and strained relations
between Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators believe most of the money came from Russian importers trying
to avoid taxes, though they are looking into whether some came from Russian
mobsters. No one directly addressed the matter in court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   However, a prosecutor said $300,000 of the laundered money was ransom for a
kidnapping in Russia and Edwards also said bankers she teamed up with in 1995 at
the Russian bank DKB had some sinister connections.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was aware that personnel for DKB were on occasion in fear of their
customers and afraid to leave the bank because they said customers with machine
guns were waiting for them," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration of former President Boris Yeltsin has called the Bank of
New York allegations a creation by the West to tarnish Russia. The Bank of New
York has not been accused of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis D. Schiliro, assistant director of the FBI's New York office, called
the pleas a significant development but said "much remains to be done" in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Money laundering involves moving deposits through a series of accounts to
disguise their illicit source.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards described creating an illegal banking network for Russians --
without required licenses -- that was run through accounts at the Bank of New
York. The accounts were set up for shell companies with offices in New York and
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   The bank provided the bogus companies with software that was used to
transfer money, cheating the Russian government out of customs duties and tax
revenue, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards said she "suspected the accounts were being used by many people for
illicit purposes."
</P>
<P>
	   In exchange, Edwards and her husband were paid $1.8 million, a percentage of
the money being moved, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards also said that after the couple moved to London in 1996, they paid a
Bank of New York employee, Svetlana Kudryavtsev, $500 a month to make sure the
accounts were operating properly.
</P>
<P>
	   Kudryavtsev was indicted last month on perjury charges for allegedly lying
to a federal grand jury about whether she or her husband had ever received money
or loans from Edwards. Kudryavtsev's lawyer has said any money his client
received was a product of her friendship with Edwards.
</P>
<P>
	   An alleged accomplice in the money transfers, Aleskey Volkov, remains a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards and Berlin pleaded guilty to charges including conspiracy to commit
money laundering and operating an unlawful banking business. Each will remain
free on $500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards also admitted she used her position at the Bank of New York to help
hundreds of Russians, most of them affiliated with the Russian banking industry,
to enter the United States illegally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
