<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Reopens Afghan Art Gallery  </HEADLINE>
   By AMIR SHAH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Four years after seizing the Afghan capital, the
ruling Taliban militia reopened the National Art Gallery on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Thirty paintings were on display, none with human figures -- according to
the Taliban's strict interpretation of Islam, human images are forbidden.
Photography is outlawed in the 90 percent of Afghanistan ruled by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We give importance to art and that's why we have renovated the National
Art Gallery which was destroyed in the civil war,'' said the Taliban's deputy
minister for culture, Abdur Rehman Hotakki. ``Afghanistan has a rich and old
tradition of paintings and calligraphy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Only Taliban officials were at the gallery to admire the paintings by
Afghanistan's two late masters -- Ghulam Mohammed Maimana and Behazadi. The
works on display show Afghanistan's historical monuments, mosques and
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
	   The gallery is open to the public and hopes to promote art, said Information
Minister Maulvi Qudratullah Jamal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will try to preserve their work and promote the new talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in 1979, Afghan artists
were among the best in Asia, Jamal said.
</P>
<P>
	   The gallery displayed all kinds of paintings and sculptures until the
Moscow-allied Afghan regime was ousted by Islamic fighters in 1991. The museum
was looted and wrecked when Islamic guerrillas captured the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Plans To Speed Up Adoptions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair will oversee a government drive to
overhaul Britain's adoption laws to remove the hurdles that leave some children
needlessly languishing in care.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair has been approached by couples wanting to adopt, complaining about
their frustrations, Alastair Campbell, the prime minister's spokesman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They feel they have got to justify their whole life, their whole
existence,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wide variations exist in the way local social services departments approach
adoption, so consideration will be given to drafting national guidelines, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Couples adopting children older than 5 now have an average wait of five
years before proceedings are complete, while it takes an average of eight months
to adopt newborns, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell noted Blair's move was not intended to be critical of the local
departments, which he said were doing a difficult job.
</P>
<P>
	   But, he added, ``Real hurdles are put in the way of couples who want to
adopt. There is work to be done by the Department of Health and the Home Office.
We want to see whether new adoption laws are required.''
</P>
<P>
	   The number of annual adoptions has fallen from 20,000 in the 1960s and '70s
to about 6,000 per year -- with half those involving the child's own parent or a
stepparent, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
	   The move to change the laws was partially motivated by a report issued this
week detailing two decades of sexual abuse in children's homes in north Wales,
Downing Street acknowledged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
