<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comedian David Brenner Returns  </HEADLINE>
    By LYNN ELBER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- David Brenner didn't win the network talk show, the
sitcom or the multimillion-dollar contracts that enriched a fair number of his
comedy peers. But he's still hoping for the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
	   The stand-up comic, who gained fame as a favored visitor to Johnny Carson's
"Tonight Show," is betting that his weekend HBO show from Las Vegas will
re-energize a career interrupted by family discord.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm gonna take my place back at the front of the parade," Brenner says in a
matter-of-fact tone.
</P>
<P>
	   He's not playing it safe. "David Brenner: Back with a Vengeance" (10 p.m.
EST Saturday), his first solo HBO special in two decades, is live. And the jokes
will be spontaneous: Brenner plans to riff on newspaper headlines of the moment.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm raising the wire up, high as I can get it, and I'm making it real
thin," said Brenner. "I'm going to walk a wire that few if any comedians would
dare to walk. ... This is my moment for people to say, 'Do you know anyone who
can hit the ball out of the park that way?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Brenner's cockiness, which could be off-putting, is instead engaging. Maybe
it's the mixed metaphors. Or the endearingly goony grin, unchanged despite his
54 years. Maybe it's the sympathetic response to a talented comedian who seems
to have suffered, ironically, from bad timing.
</P>
<P>
	   Or perhaps it's that, as Brenner tells it, he took a pass on stardom to put
his son's welfare first. A long, bruising custody battle forced him to curtail
his TV appearances and visibility beginning in the mid-1980s, when Brenner lived
in Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
	   "In a nutshell, I couldn't work more than 50 nights a year (out of town) or
I'd be an absentee father," he said. "That was when they were giving out the
talk shows, the sitcoms."
</P>
<P>
	   He finally won the fight with a girlfriend over their son Cole, now 17, who
lives with him in Los Angeles. Brenner and his companion of 12 years, artist
Elizabeth Slater, also are raising their two boys, ages 4 and 1.
</P>
<P>
	   No regrets over his decision?
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't even make a decision. I didn't even think about it. How could you
not do it? I don't mean to sound noble," Brenner replies. "Besides, I come from
the slums of Philadelphia and everything in my life is profit. My downside is
what most people would strive a lifetime to get to."
</P>
<P>
	   What he may have lost, however, would have to rankle. After appearing some
200 times as a "Tonight Show" guest and fill-in host, Brenner seemed in the '80s
the natural choice to replace Carson. But it was Jay Leno, after jousting with
David Letterman, who claimed the late-night throne in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Brenner's approach to comedy -- mining everyday events for laughs -- was
reflected in the routines of colleagues like Jerry Seinfeld and Paul Reiser.
That pair graduated to wildly lucrative sitcoms; Brenner stayed on the
comedy-club circuit that couldn't match such rewards.
</P>
<P>
	   He's not entirely blase about that.
</P>
<P>
	   "Someone said 'You must be so proud you opened the door for so many of these
guys, Seinfeld, (Garry) Shandling, that copied you.' I said, 'Lemme tell you
something: I'm still holding the door. I never went through. I'm an idiot."'
</P>
<P>
	   There were misfires in which timing was the culprit. In the late 1980s,
Brenner proposed a sitcom that would take a behind-the-scenes look at a talk
show and its comedian-host; networks rejected it, saying viewers wouldn't care.
</P>
<P>
	   In the '90s, a similar concept flew with Shandling's "The Larry Sanders
Show."
</P>
<P>
	   Back in the '70s, Brenner seemed on the verge of sitcom success with "Snip,"
loosely based on the movie "Shampoo" and from TV hitmaker James Komack ("Chico
and the Man," "Welcome Back Kotter.") With seven episodes filmed and unaired,
NBC pulled the plug.
</P>
<P>
	   "They made up all kinds of excuses, but the reason 'Snip' was pulled is we
had an actor who was gay and who played a gay part. They were afraid to have a
gay on television; this was before 'Soap.'
</P>
<P>
	   "Today, ironically, if you don't have a gay person on the show you don't go
on the air," Brenner concluded.
</P>
<P>
	   More than that has changed. Brenner, who always worked "clean" and still
does for corporate gigs, now allows off-color language in his club routines.
He's busy writing screenplays. And he knows Hollywood's current youth obsession
will shape his comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   Network executives "are not going to offer me 'The David Brenner Show.'
Those days are over. They say 'Oh, the demographic is different, we're looking
for young people.' But there's no reason I can't be a father, the neighbor, the
boss. There's no reason I can't be the Peter Boyle or George Segal of a series."
</P>
<P>
	   Maybe not the front of the parade, but closer.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
	   RAGS TO CARNEGIE RICHES: Andrew Carnegie, the self-made man who rose from
poverty to the role of captain of industry, is profiled on PBS' "The American
Experience" Monday, Feb. 21 (check local listings for time). Carnegie preached
the obligation of the wealthy to return money to society, an act which he said
"provides a refuge from self-questioning." Actor David Ogden Stiers narrates the
two-hour program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1314 </TRAILER>
