<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coke Officially Names Daft CEO  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN BACHMAN AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola's board of directors formally elected Douglas Daft
as the company's new chairman and chief executive today, hastening the departure
of former chief M. Douglas Ivester, who had already ceded control of the soft
drink giant.
</P>
<P>
	   The board also elected Jack L. Stahl president.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement released by the company, Ivester said he would retire
immediately because the transition to Daft's tenure had been completed.
</P>
<P>
	   "The board of directors had asked me to stay on through April to ensure a
smooth transition," Ivester said. "That transition is complete, and I am very
confident that the Coca-Cola Co. is in very good hands under the leadership of
Doug Daft and Jack Stahl."
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 5, the 52-year-old Ivester announced plans to retire after Coke's
annual shareholders meeting April 19. Daft was named his successor shortly
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
	   But in recent weeks, Daft has made several management moves, making it clear
that he was firmly in charge of the world's biggest beverage company and that
Ivester's term had effectively ended.
</P>
<P>
	   While analysts have praised Daft's selection, the company's stock has
continued to flounder. Coke shares were down $1.43 3/4 at $52.12 1/2 in early
afternoon trading today on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   During retirement, Ivester will serve as a company consultant "available to
Daft and other senior management as they deem appropriate," Coke spokesman Rob
Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
	   Daft, 56, began his career with Coke in 1969 in his native Australia. Last
month, he stunned Wall Street and company observers by announcing worldwide job
cuts of 6,000, including 40 percent of the work force at company headquarters.
</P>
<P>
	   Stahl, 46, has been with Coke since 1980 and has managed Coke's operations
in North America and Latin America and The Minute Maid Co.
</P>
<P>
	   The board also elected Minute Maid president and chief executive Don Knauss
a Coca-Cola vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1323 </TRAILER>
