<DOCNO> APW20000217.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aeroflex Leaving NYSE for Nasdaq  </HEADLINE>
    By DUNSTAN PRIAL AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A small high-technology company called Aeroflex Inc.
announced Thursday it will become the first publicly traded company to move its
shares from the New York Stock Exchange to the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   Companies often move from the Nasdaq to the NYSE as they grow in size and
value. For example, Qwest Communications International, a Denver-based
telecommunications company, jumped to the NYSE earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
	   But no company has ever left the Big Board for the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
	   The move reflects the shifting attitude of U.S. investors, who have become
increasingly infatuated with the growth potential of small tech-sector
companies, many of which are listed on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
	   Demand for those stocks fueled an unprecedented 86 percent rise in the
Nasdaq composite index in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Aeroflex President Michael Gorin said at a news conference in Manhattan that
the shift was made to capture the extraordinary valuations currently afforded
many Nasdaq listed tech companies and to boost Aeroflex's exposure.
</P>
<P>
	   All of Aeroflex's peers -- both in size and business model -- are listed on
the Nasdaq, Gorin said.
</P>
<P>
	   A typical NYSE listed company is currently worth about $5.3 billion. The
typical Nasdaq listed company is much smaller.
</P>
<P>
	   Aeroflex, of Plainview, N.Y., makes parts for high-tech communications
systems and has a stock market valuation of about $750 million. It first listed
on the NYSE in 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   "In 1983, the Nasdaq market was 'the other market.' Nasdaq is now at least
on a comparable plain with the NYSE. If we thought otherwise, we wouldn't have
made the change," Gorin said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors pushed Aeroflex's stock up $3.81 to $43.06 in midday NYSE trading.
Its shares will begin trading on the Nasdaq on March 21 under the symbol ARXX.
</P>
<P>
	   NYSE spokesman Ray Pellecchia said the exchange doesn't think the Aeroflex
move represents the start of a trend. Thirty companies have jumped to the NYSE
in the last six months -- 21 from the Nasdaq and nine from the American Stock
Exchange, which merged last year with the Nasdaq, according to Pellecchia.
</P>
<P>
	   Frank Zarb, chairman of the National Association of Securities Dealers,
which overseas the Nasdaq market, said high-profile moves by tech companies from
the NYSE to the Nasdaq will add value to the Nasdaq as it prepares for its own
shift to a for-profit company, a move expected by midyear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moody's May Downgrade Japan Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's efforts to reinvigorate the economy by taking on a
mountain of debt attracted another influential critic Thursday: Moody's
Investors Services.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. credit ratings agency said it may downgrade Japan's government bond
rating on fears the country can't afford to keep borrowing its way out of its
economic woes.
</P>
<P>
	   While most economists agreed just a year ago that massive public spending
was needed to lift the economy out of its worst recession in decades, many are
now saying the strategy is going to far. The government has even taken the
unusual step of turning to banks to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan, the world's second-largest economy, is also one of the most indebted.
Its public debt exceeds $5.5 trillion, or 128 percent of its gross domestic
product, making it the only major country apart from Italy with debt greater
than GDP. The U.S. national debt is half of GDP.
</P>
<P>
	   The credit rating agency said it will review its Aa1 rating, the second
highest, on bonds issued or backed by the Japanese government. If Moody's issues
a downgrade, it would be the agency's second in two years.
</P>
<P>
	   "The review is prompted by structural problems in Japan's economy that have
resulted in a level of public sector debt that will soon be the highest,
relative to GDP, among the advanced industrial economies," Moody's said.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's spending policy, who now include
prominent members of his own party, say the money is merely going to wasteful
public works projects that benefit bureaucrats and special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the structural reform needed to engineer long-term growth is
stalling and private demand remains stagnant.
</P>
<P>
	   Moody's said that the worst of the 1997-1998 economic downturn is probably
over, but that corporate retrenching and financial system reforms may not be
proceeding fast enough.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is unclear whether the reform and restructuring process will reach a
critical mass to propel Japan's economy into a higher potential growth path,
without which Japan's public-sector debt problem should continue to worsen,"
Moody's said.
</P>
<P>
	   Moody's review will examine whether Japan's economic recovery is sustainable
enough to help the government pare debt. It recognized that immediate efforts to
tackle the budget deficit might wreck the economic rebound.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts agreed with Moody's dark assessment.
</P>
<P>
	   "The government is continuing its fiscal stimuli but a recovery of
private-sector demand has not been in sight," Susumu Takahashi of the Japan
Research Institute, a private think tank, was quoted as saying by Kyodo News.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese officials said the Moody's review is unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't see any logic for downgrading the Japanese economy. Japan's
structural reforms are going on, proceeding as scheduled," said Haruhiko Kuroda,
Japan's vice finance minister for international affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week Japan's chief economic planner suggested in a televised interview
that the country's economy may have slipped back into recession. The official,
Taichi Sakaiya, said he expects to see a "considerably large negative figure"
when gross domestic product for the October-December quarter is announced next
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1328 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Eyes Deeper Scrutiny of Mergers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of the Federal Trade Commission said Thursday
that the agency's reviews of mergers and acquisitions were becoming stricter
because companies are striking bigger and more complex deals.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have seen more frequent proposals that are so extensive and complex that
it is impossible to predict with any confidence that competition will be
restored and consumer welfare will be protected," FTC chairman Robert Pitofsky
said in a speech before international antitrust lawyers in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky said the commission has already begun stiffening the requirements
placed on corporations that suggest spinning off assets and restructuring
companies to meet antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   Those plans should be created by the companies, and not the government,
Pitofsky emphasized.
</P>
<P>
	   "It should be clear that the burden of coming forward without restructuring
proposals should be on the sponsors of the merger," he said. "It's not our job
-- we're not the best people to do it. It's your job."
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, the commission voted 3 to 2 to block BP Amoco PLC's
acquisition of Atlantic Richfield Co., despite BP Amoco's offer to sell some of
its rights and operations in Alaska, where the company would dominate the
market.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky's comments come on the heels of a blockbuster year of mergers and
acquisitions around the world. There were a total of 31,528 deals last year
worth a total of $3.4 trillion, according to Thomson Financial/Securities Data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1329 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
