<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Attend Trade Meetings  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID THURBER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- They battled riot police on the streets of
Seattle, contributing to the breakdown of free trade talks in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, at this week's meeting of the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development,
free trade critics are attending most meetings and eating at the same
restaurants as the official delegates.
</P>
<P>
	   The citizens' groups say their inclusion has helped address their complaints
that ordinary people have been shut out of talks shaping the future of global
trade and development affecting the lives of billions of people.
</P>
<P>
	   Even protesters from groups without accredited status have been allowed to
approach the conference site, despite an initial plan to confine them to a park
about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think this will be a new pattern for discussions of this nature in the
future," Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said Thursday. "Everybody has to
be on board."
</P>
<P>
	   Each day since the conference began Saturday, different protest groups have
peacefully delivered petitions to conference secretary Awni Behnam.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, 500 Thai farmers opposed to trade liberalization gave him a
basket of organic vegetables; on Monday, 200 environmentalists gave him a red
Valentine rose.
</P>
<P>
	   Activists give much of the credit for their inclusion to Thai organizers and
to UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens Ricupero, who scheduled a pre-conference
caucus of non-governmental organizations to solicit their views.
</P>
<P>
	   The non-governmental organizations have been given a meeting room within the
conference building and are allowed to attend most sessions and hold briefings
and news conferences.
</P>
<P>
	   In Seattle, many activists were accredited to the WTO meeting and allowed
inside to rub elbows with trade ministers and journalists, though they were kept
out of closed negotiating sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   But outside the talks in Seattle, tens of thousands of people protested
globalization, some blocking roads and preventing trade ministers from getting
into meetings. A few people staged violent rampages downtown, prompting the
mayor to declare a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
	   Bangkok fretted over becoming Seattle, Round II. So Ricupero made including
citizens' groups "a priority task."
</P>
<P>
	   Although a two-hour formal discussion between citizens' groups and Ricupero
failed Tuesday to bridge many differences, the activists said they were
generally pleased.
</P>
<P>
	   "We must credit Mr. Ricupero for working hard to include NGOs in this
process," said Walden Bello, a Philippine activist who heads the Thai-based
Focus on the Global South and who was among peaceful protesters in Seattle. "It
certainly was a sincere process."
</P>
<P>
	   The most notable problem happened when a lone American protester got close
enough to International Monetary Fund chief Michel Camdessus to smash a pie in
his face.
</P>
<P>
	   But while activists praise UNCTAD's attempts at openness, they say they're
still largely locked out of the more powerful World Trade Organization, which
sponsored the trade talks that collapsed in December.
</P>
<P>
	   UNCTAD researches ways that trade can help poor countries. The WTO brings
government negotiators together to seek international agreements that regulate
trade.
</P>
<P>
	   "We still have to pry open the WTO," says Martin Khor, head of the
Malaysia-based Third World Network. "Although the situation is improving
somewhat, by and large NGOs are still in the dark regarding the WTO."
</P>
<P>
	   Worse, he says, is that officials from poor countries are often not included
in key WTO negotiations, which for efficiency typically involve only a few
members -- mostly from rich and powerful countries.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's totally unbelievable," Khor says. "The challenge is how to get our
ministers of trade into the negotiating rooms."
</P>
<P>
	   Of the WTO's 136 members, between 30 and 40 are unable to afford a mission
in Geneva, where the WTO is based, so they can't participate. Others have only
one representative, who cannot attend all meetings, even if invited.	   Thai
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpaki, who takes over the WTO's leadership
in 2002, says he hopes to find ways to make it more accessible.
</P>
<P>
	   Under consideration are faster declassification of documents and forums at
which citizens' groups can learn about the status of negotiations and express
their views.
</P>
<P>
	   But ultimately, they need to sway the governments that comprise both
organizations, Ricupero says. Governments are reluctant to make room, saying
it's their job to represent their citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1334 </TRAILER>
