<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmakers Target War Criminals  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers worried about the growing number of alleged war
criminals seeking refuge in the United States are considering a bill that would
expand guidelines blocking the entry of Nazi War criminals to include recent
human rights offenders.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill would cover persons who committed acts of torture in places like
Rwanda and Yugoslavia. A companion measure has already passed the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to slam the door shut on these thugs and rid our country of those
who have already managed to make their way here,'' said Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.,
and one of the bill's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
	   One of those alleged criminals, Carl Dorelien, lives in Foley's district.
Dorelien is the former head of personnel for the 7,000-member army that seized
power from Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide in 1991 and killed as many
as 4,000 civilians.
</P>
<P>
	   He now lives in a resort community in Port St. Lucie, Fla. and won $3.2
million in the Florida lottery in 1997. Last year, in an interview with The
Boston Globe, Dorelien said the U.S. military got him a five-year visa after the
corrupt Haitian army was forced from power in 1994 by 20,000 U.S. troops.
Fifteen other Haitian military officers have since joined him in the United
States and are living mainly in New York and Florida, according to Dorelien.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is ludicrous that the INS (Immigration and Naturalization Service)
denies citizenship or permanent residency to individuals whose only offense was
to cross the border, but grants citizenship and permanent residency to
perpetrators of human rights violations,'' said Richard Krieger, president of
the International Educational Missions Inc., a group which deals with the issue
of foreign war criminals and refugees.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill allows the Justice Department's Office of Special Investigations to
expand its operations to include provisions to bar admission and deport aliens
who engaged in acts of terror abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department supports the bill but also wants to include conduct
such as persecution, war crimes and crimes against humanity, said James
Castello, associate deputy attorney general.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- The bill is H.S. 3058.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
