<HEADLINE> U.S. To Israel: Avoid Civilians  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department urged Israel today to avoid hurting
civilians in its response to attacks by the militant Islamic group Hezbollah on
Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Everything must be done to prevent civilian casualties,'' spokesman James
P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We do not believe that Israeli attacks against civilian infrastructure and
populated areas will solve the problem.'' he said. ``Such actions only add to
the suffering of the people of Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first implied U.S. criticism of Israel's tactics in a
three-week-long duel with Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven Israeli soldiers were killed and more than three dozen Lebanese
civilians injured. Israel has attacked power facilities and other civilian
installations.
</P>
<P>
	   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last week that Israel was trying
to send a signal that it wanted the escalation of fighting to stop.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, Rubin said Albright had not approved Israel's tactics. He also said
``we have not changed our opinion.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``She was studiously neutral as to the question of our view of that,'' Rubin
said. ``She merely recounted what the Israelis say that they were doing. She
didn't say that was a good thing, she didn't say that was a bad thing. She
didn't say we supported it, we opposed it. She was noncommittal on that
subject.''
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. spokesman also reiterated criticism of Hezbollah, saying it
cynically launched attacks from civilian population areas. The latest escalation
in southern Lebanon is cynical, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This escalation, in the first instance, puts Lebanese civilians and the
interests of Lebanon at risk, in addition to undermining the prospects for peace
in the region and the pursuit of Arab-Israeli peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   A monitoring group was set up in 1996 by the United States, France, Israel,
Syria and Lebanon to protect civilians from shelling.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel pulled out of the group when Hezbollah killed the seventh Israeli
soldier, and Albright said the group could not meet amid escalating violence.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said today the American and French co-chairmen would confer in an
effort to shield civilians, but that the monitoring group had not been
dissolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
