<HEADLINE> Mannesmann Reports Strong Revenues  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Mannesmann, the German phone company recently
targeted in a heated takeover battle, reported preliminary results for 1999
Thursday that showcased strong results in wireless services -- the very business
coveted so badly by the ultimately victorious suitor, Vodafone AirTouch of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues from overall telecommunications services jumped 93 percent to $8.9
billion, while mobile phone sales accounted for $4.99 billion, growing 37
percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Vodafone valued Mannesmann's growing telecommunications division so much
that it agreed this month to pay $180 billion in stock for the whole company,
which includes an engineering and automotive branch, making it the largest
takeover in history. Vodafone plans to spin off the engineering and auto
businesses later this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann said net profit was roughly $490 million, below the 1998 level.
But cash flow climbed 37 percent to $4.21 billion while revenues rose 22 percent
to $22.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The preliminary 1999 results met expectations and prove the company was
worth the price tag, said Hermann Reith, a telecom analyst with BHF Bank in
Frankfurt. Still, he predicted that growth would slow this year after the
company merges with Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
	   Duesseldorf-based Mannesmann, which filed according to American accounting
principles, gave no comparative figures for 1998. More complete figures will be
available when the company releases its annual report on April 4.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann attributed the increase in telecom results to a surge in mobile
phone usage. Mannesmann's D2 service, the No. 1 mobile phone service provider in
Germany, more than doubled its number of customers to 10 million last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The results don't include Mannesmann's subsidiary Orange, a British mobile
phone carrier that must be sold off after Vodafone fully merges with Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
	   Mannesmann chief executive Klaus Esser repeatedly insisted during the 2
1/2-month dogfight with Vodafone that its strategy of fixed-line and mobile
phone services had better growth potential than Vodafone's mobile-only approach.
</P>
<P>
	   He agreed to the merger only after Vodafone came forth with a last minute
sweetened deal that gave Mannesmann a 49.5 percent stake in the combined
company, as opposed to an original offer of 47.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
