<HEADLINE> Group Says Chechen Refugees Tortured  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN IAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- A prominent international human-rights group alleged today
that Chechens are being tortured and abused by Russian soldiers at detention
camps.
</P>
<P>
	   Malcolm Hawkes, of the Human Rights Watch group, said that more than 1,000
Chechen males had been rounded up this month, after most rebels abandoned the
capital, Grozny, and were being detained in closed camps while Russians
investigated their possible ties with the militants.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The picture we are getting is a direct repetition of the first Chechen
war,'' Hawkes said. ``Chechen filtration camps are centers of wholesale abuse
and torture.''
</P>
<P>
	   The allegations were echoed by the World Organization Against Torture, which
issued a statement in Geneva today saying, ``We cannot ignore that the
filtration camps are indeed concentration camps where Russian soldiers are
committing the worst atrocities, in all impunity, against their prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
	   During the previous war in Chechnya, in 1994-96, there were many allegations
of mistreatment and torture in Russian-run detention camps. Fewer such reports
have emerged during the current campaign, but access to Chechnya for media and
humanitarian organizations is much more restricted this time.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The abuse is going on behind closed doors,'' Hawkes said. ``There is no
access for the Red Cross, the United Nations or international human-rights
monitoring groups such as ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hawkes gave no details of the torture described by Chechen refugees in
interviews with monitors in Ingushetia, a Russian region bordering Chechnya.
However, the French daily Le Monde recently published what it described as a
young Chechen's account of life in a detention camp in northern Chechnya called
Chernokozovo.
</P>
<P>
	   The man, identified only by the first name Moussa, said people in masks had
tortured and raped men, women, the elderly and children. Prisoners were given
three meals a week and little water, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Presidential aide Sergei Yastrzhembsky today reiterated previous denials of
reports of torture in Chernokozovo and at a briefing singled out Le Monde's
report that children were being held there.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All this is on your conscience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that European Union observers would be allowed into the camp to see
the situation for themselves, but gave no date of a possible visit or other
details.
</P>
<P>
	   The Council of Europe's human-rights commissioner, Alvaro Gil-Robles, is due
to arrive in Moscow on Feb. 24. His office could give no details of the trip
agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   In a move possibly aimed at deflecting criticism of Russia's human rights
record in Chechnya, acting President Vladimir Putin today appointed Vladimir
Kalamanov as his special representative on human and civil rights in Chechnya,
the Interfax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalamanov is head of the Federal Migration Service, which deals with
displaced people. It is one of the agencies that has been responsible for
accommodating the approximately 250,000 people who have fled Chechnya since
Russian troops entered in September.
</P>
<P>
	   NATO Secretary-General Lord Robertson told NTV television on Wednesday that
he had discussed the appointment of a human rights ombudsman for Chechnya with
Putin. Western criticism of Russia's offensive has focused largely on the
military's treatment of civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1342 </TRAILER>
