<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UPS Ordered To Add Full-Time Jobs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ATLANTA (AP) -- An arbitrator has ruled that United Parcel Service must
create 2,000 full-time jobs under the terms of its five-year contract with the
Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
	   In a decision released Wednesday evening, independent arbitrator George
Nicolau gave Atlanta-based UPS 90 days to add the full-time positions. UPS also
must pay back wages and benefits to those workers, who previously were
part-time.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of its 1997 contract with the Teamsters, UPS agreed to hire 2,000
new full-time workers per year for five years -- replacing part-timers -- if UPS
regained and surpassed shipping volume lost to a 15-day strike.
</P>
<P>
	   When package volume dropped because of the strike, UPS officials contended
that the job-creation language was void for the contract's first two years. The
Teamsters then filed grievances for 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday's decision covered the 1997 grievance; the 1998 dispute is
pending. With shipping volumes restored, UPS agreed to create 2,000 full-time
jobs for 1999. Teamsters spokesman Bret Caldwell said the union anticipates no
further disputes on that issue for the contract's remaining years.
</P>
<P>
	   UPS spokesman Norman Black said Thursday that the company plans to discuss
the 1998 grievance with union officials since the issues are identical.
</P>
</TEXT>
