<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-Man Will Rogers Show Ending  </HEADLINE>
    By CARL HARTMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After nearly 30 years of performances, a one-man show
impersonating cowboy humorist Will Rogers, who pioneered good-humored insults of
presidents and politicians, comes to an end Feb. 27 in historic Ford's Theatre.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Republicans nominated Warren Harding in 1920 because Ohio hadn't had a
president since (William Howard) Taft, and they were due one," quotes actor
James Whitmore, 78, chomping a wad of gum and fingering a lariat. "Look at the
United States. We ain't had one since Lincoln."
</P>
<P>
	   And he looks up at the restored box where Lincoln was shot 135 years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview, Whitmore said Rogers had once remarked of the grammar he
used on the stage: "I know a lotta people who don't say ain't, but they ain't
eatin'."
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers didn't actually speak that way outside the theater, Whitmore added.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitmore says all his lines come from those spoken or written by Rogers,
killed in an air accident in 1935. Rogers wrote a syndicated column as well as
doing rope tricks and poking fun at both major parties.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't belong to any organized party," is another of Rogers' lines. "I'm a
Democrat."
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers also took aim at legislators, saying that he didn't want a statue of
himself in Washington but if the sponsors insisted, he wanted it to face the
Capitol. That way he could keep an eye on what he once called "the best Congress
money can buy."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitmore has impersonated Presidents Truman and Theodore Roosevelt on stage.
Frankie Hewitt, producing artistic director at Ford's, said she was considering
the play "Inherit the Wind" with Whitmore in the part of attorney Clarence
Darrow. The play tells the story of the trial of a high school teacher for
expounding the theory of evolution, with three-time presidential candidate
William Jennings Bryan as the lawyer opposing Darrow.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Rogers, Will's grandson and a professional polo player, presented a
"communicator" award to Whitmore at the official opening Wednesday night of the
final run of "Will Rogers' U.S.A." Whitmore performed it first in 1970, also at
Ford's.
</P>
<P>
	   "Will never got one of those awards, so I don't know what to say," Whitmore
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The award was given by the Will Rogers Memorial Commission, which runs a
Will Rogers museum on a 400-acre ranch in Oklahoma, where he was born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1428 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
