<HEADLINE> Former GOP hopeful stumps state for George W. Bush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Former presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole
stumped for an old rival Thursday, telling a crowd of regional business,
community and political leaders that Texas Gov. George W. Bush would attract
more women to politics, cut taxes and bolster education.
<P>
	   "I believe we must have a president for all Americans," Dole said. "We need
a president who has vision and executive experience. I believe that person is
Gov. George Bush."
</P>
<P>
	   In her remarks to about 200 people at a Metro-Hartford Chamber of Commerce
luncheon, Dole said Bush - who was born in New Haven, while his father was a
student at Yale University - has what it takes to beat Al Gore in the general
election. But she never mentioned Bush's main rival for the GOP nomination,
Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Connecticut, California, New York and other states hold their presidential
primary March 7. A Quinnipiac College poll released Thursday found McCain
favored over Bush among likely voters in Connecticut's Republican primary, 52
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll also found that among all registered voters, McCain is the favorite
in matchups for the presidency in November.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was favored 55 percent to 33 percent over Gore, and 50 percent to 34
percent over Democrat Bill Bradley, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
	   Dole praised Bush's proposal for a tax cut, which has drawn fire from
McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average worker is working five months for the government just to pay
his taxes. Isn't it time to give people a break and let them invest?" Dole said.
</P>
<P>
	   She also said Bush's platform will increase competition in education by
allowing local boards of education to take more control of their curricula.
</P>
<P>
	   "What you need is an increase in student performance, not paperwork," Dole
said.
</P>
<P>
	   And she said Bush would get more young people and women interested in
politics. She said two-thirds of the women in Texas voted for Bush in his
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   "This gender gap that we hear a lot about is going to turn itself inside
out," she said. "Women are going to help take George Bush to the White House and
Al Gore is going to be the one with the gender gap in the year 2000 election."
</P>
<P>
	   Later Thursday, Dole was scheduled to speak at Sacred Heart University in
Fairfield about involving women in politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
