<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda To Vote on Political Parties  </HEADLINE>
   By HRVOJE HRANJSKI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- He has been the darling of donors. He has been
championed by Western governments. But in his 14 years as Uganda's president,
Yoweri Museveni has never eased his tight grip on power.
</P>
<P>
	   That could all change soon, when Ugandans vote whether to scrap Museveni's
self-styled ``no-party democracy'' and permit political parties to run
candidates and to campaign freely in parliamentary and presidential elections
next year.
</P>
<P>
	   Museveni engineered the ban after leading a rebellion in 1986 that rescued
Uganda from two decades of bloodshed, factional turmoil and corruption. Many
view his rule as a model for dodging the political and ethnic conflicts that
have bedeviled Uganda's neighbors in central Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   But critics say ``no-party democracy'' has become less a tool to shield
Uganda from strife than to ensure Museveni's political domination. Now, five
years after the ban on official party activity was encoded in Uganda's
constitution, the system is facing a vote. Under the constitution adopted in
1995, the ballot must be held on or before July 2, but no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's about power. If Museveni wins, than Uganda becomes a one-party state
and he stays in power,'' said Paul Ssemogerere, leader of the opposition
Democratic Party, which is boycotting the vote. ``Museveni will use fear, money
and blackmail to manipulate people to secure a majority vote.''
</P>
<P>
	   Since overthrowing a military junta after a five-year bush war 14 years ago,
Museveni and his National Resistance Movement have been credited with
transforming one of the world's poorest, most volatile nations to a fast-growing
liberal economy with political stability.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, Museveni defeated Ssemogerere and won five years in office.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, like now, political parties were not allowed to campaign by party
affiliation. People run as individuals, and everyone is a member of the Movement
-- which acts like a political system. Political parties can exist in name but
cannot display their colors, hold conventions, campaign or run for office.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the question is whether the country, whose stability is seen as
crucial for anchoring a region beset by civil wars in neighboring Congo and
Sudan, is confident enough to survive a possible change in power that Museveni
fears may stir up religious, tribal and regional divisions of the past.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have changed the state from terrorizing the people to protecting the
people,'' said Hope Kivengere, Museveni's spokeswoman and an architect of the
no-party system. ``(But) we fear the nature of political parties, not political
parties per se.''
</P>
<P>
	   Political referendums in Africa have produced stunning turnabouts, not
always favoring the leaders who organized the ballots. In 1993, voters in Malawi
replaced one-party rule with multiparty democracy.
</P>
<P>
	   In Zimbabwe this week, voters repudiated President Robert Mugabe, turning
away his bid for constitutional reforms that would have strengthened the
president's powers.
</P>
<P>
	   In Uganda, it is impossible to measure Museveni's popularity because the
political playing field is heavily tilted in favor of the Movement, which
behaves like a ruling party despite its insistence on being called a system,
according to diplomats, pundits and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Museveni's base of support is not in Kampala, which is believed to contain
sizable opposition, but in rural Uganda, where many people rely on his army to
ward off rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Ssemogerere, who was Museveni's interior and foreign minister until
resigning in 1995, noted that the Movement and its officials receive state
funding. Money has yet to be dispersed equally among political parties
campaigning in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The referendum is conceived in fraud because the Movement is perceived not
as a party but as a system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ssemogerere's party said it supports multiparty democracy but will boycott
the vote, calling the issue a fundamental political right. The United People's
Congress, the second-leading opposition party, is also boycotting.
</P>
<P>
	   Some wonder if the Democratic Party and the United People's Congress,
tainted by its association with former dictator Milton Obote, can successfully
compete with Museveni.
</P>
<P>
	   And international donors, whose assistance is vital to Uganda, have
criticized the government for delaying a bill that would amend the constitution
to allow campaigning by political parties ahead of the referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1438 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Island Tuvalu Joins U.N.  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The South Pacific nation of Tuvalu, population 9,000,
won support from the Security Council on Thursday for its bid to become the
189th member of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   By a vote of 14-0, the council recommended to the General Assembly that the
nation of nine coral atolls 620 miles north of Fiji be admitted as a member.
China abstained because of Tuvalu's diplomatic ties to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
	   The General Assembly has not set a date to vote on Tuvalu's application.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuvalu's Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana applied for U.N. membership in
January, and the Security Council's committee on admissions backed the
application earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
	   China's Deputy U.N. Ambassador Shen Guofang said his government could not
support Tuvalu's admission because it has not implemented the General Assembly
resolution which recognizes Beijing as China's representative in the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At the same time, proceeding from the long-term interests of the peoples
of China and Tuvalu, and also taking into consideration the requests from
different parties including the South Pacific countries, we are not going to
block this recommendation,'' Shen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Taiwan, under the name Republic of China, held the Chinese U.N. seat until
1971. It walked out of the United Nations just before other members voted to
give its seat to the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
	   China claims Taiwan as a breakaway province with no right to international
recognition.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, Beijing delayed consideration of U.N. membership for the Pacific
island nation of Nauru for a month because of Nauru's diplomatic relations with
Taiwan. Eventually, it abstained when the Security Council voted to recommend
Nauru's membership.
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations also accepted two other South Pacific island nations as
members last year, Kiribati and the Kingdom of Tonga.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuvalu, formerly called the Ellice Islands, was ruled by Britain from the
1890s until 1978 when it became independent.
</P>
<P>
	   It has a total land area of 10 square miles and ranks second to Vatican City
as the world's smallest nation in population and the fourth smallest in area
after Vatican City, Monaco and Nauru.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuvalu subsists on fishing license fees, fishing, income from a national
investment trust fund, earnings by seamen who work on foreign ships and foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
	   It is also believed to earn more than $1 million annually from a ``sex
chat'' telephone service that pays for permission to use Tuvalu's country
telephone code.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1441 </TRAILER>
