<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phone Service for Disabled Expanded  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Phone companies must expand the services they offer to
Americans with disabilities by next spring under federal rules adopted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Communications Commission voted 5-0 to require a new service
nationwide that allows users to speak directly to a special operator -- trained
to identify speech patterns of those with disabilities -- who would relay the
message to the person on the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency is also requiring companies to bolster the quality of existing
services. For example, the commission set a minimum speed of 60 words a minute
for operators handling text telephone or TTY calls -- that are currently
available nationwide. It also ordered that Spanish language relay service be
available for interstate calls.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we are doing is not just for the disabled community but for all
Americans,'' said the agency's chief, William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
	   Commissioner Susan Ness added that while most Americans don't think twice
about using the phone, those with hearing impairments and speech disabilities
may have a tough time making simple calls or even reaching emergency personnel
over the phone.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1990 federal law ordered that phone companies providing voice service had
to ensure that relay services were available throughout the region they serve.
All states now offer TTY services in which the user types a message and an
operator reads it out loud to the person on the other end.
</P>
<P>
	   Ten states offer the speech-to-speech service already in which people with
speech disabilities can use their own voice or a voice synthesizer to talk on
the telephone, using special relay operators.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the FCC action, phone carriers would have to make available the new
speech-to-speech service by March 1, 2001. Commission officials said they expect
the resulting cost increase to be minimal, possibly adding a few million dollars
to the federal pool of money -- set at $44 million for 2000 -- used to pay for
interstate relay services.
</P>
<P>
	   All telecommunications carriers pay into that fund and typically recover the
costs from consumers. Their contribution is less than 0.04 percent of their
gross revenues. Each state handles separately the costs for calls within the
state.
</P>
<P>
	   Regulators also are encouraging -- but not requiring -- providers to offer
video relay interpreting services. A live demonstration at the commission's
Thursday meeting highlighted the possibilities for using the service: Using a
video camera, a young boy communicated to a specially trained operator in sign
language. The operator, in turn, interpreted the message for a relative on the
other end.
</P>
<P>
	   The video system is particularly useful for young children who may have a
hearing impairment but may not yet be able to write or use TTY.
</P>
<P>
	   The FCC also sought comments on ways to bolster public awareness of relay
services among all callers. Those who offer such services say outreach is
important so that people know they are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week,
at no direct cost.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's really important to get the word out,'' said Gil Becker, director of
the telecommunications access project of Maryland, which offers both text
telephone and speech-to-speech services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1443 </TRAILER>
