<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton and Gore to campaign together  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore will campaign
Sunday in New York in the same place, at the same time, for the first time this
year as they appeal for minority votes crucial to them both.
<P>
	   Aides said Thursday that the two will attend a church service Sunday morning
in Albany that is a highlight of the annual weekend gathering of the state
Legislature's black and Hispanic legislative caucus. Both are expected to speak
at the service.
</P>
<P>
	   While Gore is planning to leave after the service to prepare for Monday's
debate in New York City against former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Clinton
expects to stay in Albany through the day and attend the caucus' banquet Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
	   The caucus weekend annually brings together hundreds of the state's top
black and Hispanic leaders. The minority community in New York is an
increasingly powerful voting bloc. Blacks and Hispanics made up 15 percent of
voters in the state's 1998 election for governor and U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   A big test of that minority voting power comes in the state's March 7
presidential primary, considered a major showdown for Gore and the former New
York Knicks basketball star. Both have made major appeals to minorities in their
bids for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that presidential candidate Gore and Senate candidate Clinton
haven't yet campaigned together in New York has raised some eyebrows. It
prompted a front-page article in Thursday's editions of The New York Times that
carried the headline: "Gore and Mrs. Clinton Keeping A Wary Distance as
Candidates."
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, Gore was asked if he and the first lady would be crossing paths
in Albany. "Don't know," he responded. Asked if he would like to, he said:
"Sure."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said there was no intentional
distancing of the two candidates and Gore's New York team appeared ready
Thursday to embrace the first lady, at least until after March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   "For the next 19 days, she helps us tremendously," one Gore adviser said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. "Her numbers are just off the charts with
Democratic primary voters."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked recently why they hadn't been campaigning together, Gore told one
television interviewer that, "It's a matter of scheduling. Not just me, but also
her."
</P>
<P>
	   Both have made it clear that they feel they must step out of the shadow of
President Clinton. As part of that effort, Hillary Rodham Clinton has become
simply "Hillary" in campaign posters and news releases.
</P>
<P>
	   The two candidates have had nice things to say about each other.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm all for her. I think she's going to win," Gore said recently. "I think
she will be a great senator. I look forward to campaigning with her."
</P>
<P>
	   "I will do whatever I can in whatever way is open to me in supporting his
candidacy because I truly believe he would be the best person we could have to
lead our country into this new century," she said last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Key members of their New York campaign staffs have close relationships from
past campaigns and their offices are located in the same Manhattan office
building, three floors apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
