<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge blocks Woodbridge ordinance banning ATM fees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - At the request of bankers, a federal judge on
Thursday blocked a Woodbridge ordinance that sought to keep banks there from
charging non-customers for using their automatic teller machines.
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Joseph A. Greenaway Jr. said the banks provided
"overwhelming evidence" that the ordinance was pre-empted by federal and state
banking laws.
</P>
<P>
	   In issuing a temporary restraining order, Greenaway also ruled that the
banks would have no way to recover those fees if the ordinance went into effect
and was later overturned.
</P>
<P>
	   The restraint is to last until April 10, after which Greenaway will consider
additional arguments and decide whether to issue a preliminary injunction that
could lead to the law being permanently blocked.
</P>
<P>
	   The Woodbridge ordinance was adopted on Tuesday and would have become
effective next month. It set fines of $1,000 a day for each ATM that charged
fees. More than 25 ATMs would be affected.
</P>
<P>
	   Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey, reached after the hearing, said he proposed
the ordinance because Congress has been unable to pass similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   "Today, the average ATM transaction cost for a bank is approximately 10
cents, as against the average $2.43 which is charged to a consumer by one's own
bank, as well as the bank where the ATM is located," said McGreevey, whose
Middlesex County municipality is the fourth-largest in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   A banking association representative was not immediately available Thursday
to comment on ATM costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The Woodbridge law is the first of its kind in New Jersey, said William K.
Heine, spokesman for the state Department of Banking and Insurance. The Newark
City Council this week began considering a similar rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Such ordinances have been stopped in other states.
</P>
<P>
	   In Iowa, a statewide ban on ATM fees has been upheld only for banks
chartered by the state government. The state Supreme Court in Connecticut
rejected a statewide ban similar to Woodbridge's proposal. In California, the
bans are on hold in San Francisco and Santa Monica while the courts consider the
issue.
</P>
<P>
	   At Thursday's hearing before Greenaway, Woodbridge lawyer Brian M. Hak
contended that New Jersey law permits a municipality to adopt ordinances for the
protection and "well-being" of its residents.
</P>
<P>
	   Timothy J. O'Neill, a lawyer for the New Jersey Bankers Association,
countered that a "vast" network of federal and state statutes and regulations
trump the "general catchall provision" cited by Hak.
</P>
<P>
	   Hak said the township would consent to a restraining order if the judge
permitted the text of the ordinance to be published as a legal advertisement in
newspapers, which is required to occur 20 days before the law can take effect.
</P>
<P>
	   The banks objected, arguing that even if the ordinance were restrained,
publication could subject them to consumer fraud lawsuits if they continued to
charge fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Greenaway banned publication, saying that if the ordinance is ultimately
found acceptable, the township can publish it then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 1451 </TRAILER>
