<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic: End NATO Kosovo Mission  </HEADLINE>
   By DUSAN STOJANOVIC Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic rallied his
supporters Thursday at a Socialist Party congress, calling for an end to the
NATO-led Kosovo peace mission and blasting his opponents as ``weaklings and
thieves.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the congress, the first since NATO intervention left the country divided
and isolated, Milosevic sought to portray Yugoslavia as strong and stable under
his leadership, and his aides denounced America in fiery language. But opponents
said there was nothing to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
	   The largest opposition party, the Serbian Renewal Movement, said in a
statement that congress delegates can only applaud ``the ruined country that has
been turned into a concentration camp isolated in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
	   Thousands of Socialist supporters -- waving flags and chanting ``Slobo,
Slobo'' -- were bused in from rural Serbia, Milosevic's stronghold, for a rally
in front of the congress hall. Most were given the day off from work.
</P>
<P>
	   Inside, more than 2,000 delegates and as many guests attended the
conference, the fourth since Milosevic's Socialists mutated from the former
Communist party in 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   Milosevic, the only candidate, was re-elected as party chief. No major
policy change or reshuffle in the ranks resulted from the one-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   In a rare public appearance, Milosevic used harsh language to signal a
possible crackdown on the opposition, denouncing its leaders as pro-Western
``colonizers, toadies and cowards.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``In fact, Serbia doesn't have a real opposition,'' Milosevic said in his
closing speech. ``We have a group of paid weaklings, speculators and thieves
who, using money from abroad and the fact that the population lives poorly,
manipulate the people, especially the young.''
</P>
<P>
	   The opposition charges that Milosevic and his party have turned Serbia, the
dominant republic in Yugoslavia, into a pariah state because of four wars he has
started in the Balkans. The opposition has demanded Milosevic's resignation.
</P>
<P>
	   Serbia has virtually lost control over its southern province of Kosovo after
a 78-day NATO bombing campaign to stop Milosevic's crackdown against ethnic
Albanians there. The economy is ruined and living standards have dropped to
among Europe's lowest.
</P>
<P>
	   Blaming NATO-led peacekeepers deployed in Kosovo for failing to protect
minority Serbs there, Milosevic called for an end to their mission.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This shameful mission of the so-called international community has
suffered a complete breakdown,'' Milosevic said. ``It has to end as soon as
possible and this country has to assume authority over the whole of its
territory.''
</P>
<P>
	   Protest was apparent throughout Belgrade. Several huge party posters
announcing the congress were sprayed over with slogans such as ``The Last
Congress,'' ``Down With Slobo,'' and ``Thieves.''
</P>
<P>
	   A popular anti-Milosevic university students' group called Otpor, or
Resistance, held its own mock ``congress'' across the Sava River in downtown
Belgrade, attended by over a thousand ``delegates'' and several opposition
leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to make a clear distinction between the old and corrupt Serbia at
that (Socialist) congress, and a young Serbia that wants to live in freedom,''
said Ivan Marovic, a Resistance leader.
</P>
<P>
	   In her keynote speech at Milosevic's congress, Socialist Party General
Secretary Gorica Gajevic denounced what she called the ``brutal pressure by the
American administration,'' saying it aimed to split Kosovo and the other
Yugoslav republic, Montenegro, away from the federation.
</P>
<P>
	   She, like several other delegates, denounced Serbia's opposition for
allegedly ``hiding behind'' the Western powers that bombed Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
	   Referring to frequent meetings opposition leaders have had recently with
Western officials, Dragan Tomic, a leading Socialist official, said they are
``kneeling down and kissing hands of the killers of their own people.''
</P>
<P>
	   All journalists working for major independent domestic media outlets were
denied accreditation to cover the congress. Foreign media, however, were allowed
inside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1451 </TRAILER>
