<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Feb. 17, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Greenspan: Inflation Still a Danger
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan today
called the nation's 9 years of economic growth and the current
unemployment rate at a 3-year low remarkable. But he also said
inflation is a danger and indicated to the financial community that
interest rate hikes are highly likely in the future. Greenspan told
Congress that even though inflation has remained relatively low,
the favorable economic conditions cannot last unless growth slows
to less than the 4 percent-plus gains of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasdaq Passes 4,500; Dow Down 50.88
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks moved higher today, carrying
the Nasdaq composite index past 4,500 for the first time, as the
sector was untouched by a warning of likely higher interest rates
from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Blue chips
fluctuated, leaving the overall market mixed. Just before 3 p.m.
EST, the Nasdaq composite index was up 101.78 at 4,529.43. running
past its record close of 4,485.63 set a week ago. The Dow Jones
industrial average, down more than 100 points in earlier trading,
was down 50.88 at 10,510.53.
</P>
