<DOCNO> APW20000217.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Allegedly Rebuilding Army  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is rebuilding his
forces and soon may seek to test his military might again, perhaps in
pro-Western Montenegro, NATO's retiring supreme commander said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Wesley Clark also suggested U.S. peacekeepers may have to stay in
Bosnia and Kosovo indefinitely, or at least as long as Milosevic clings to power
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's still a threat'' Milosevic will trigger another war, the four-star
Army general said in a grim assessment of the situation in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
	   Other than being ousted from Kosovo, Milosevic's Serbian troops, tanks and
artillery came through last spring's 78-day NATO air bombardment relatively
unscathed, said Clark, who leaves his European post in April and plans to end
his 34-year military career at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark told the House Armed Services Committee that Milosevic remains firmly
in power and that his military is training again, with ``some generals talking
about going back into Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clark cited potential ``flash points in Montenegro,'' a mountainous republic
of 600,000 people that affords Yugoslavia its last outlet to the Adriatic Sea.
It has a pro-Western government and a strong independence movement.
</P>
<P>
	   Furthermore, ``There is still Milosevic meddling going on in Bosnia,'' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Milosevic has triggered four wars over the past 10 years and while he
remains in power, people in the Balkans do not feel safe, Clark said. ``Until
he's taken to trial as a war criminal, we're not going to see a resolution to
the problem,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said Milosevic retains a chemcial-weapons capacity.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark's advocacy of a more aggressive campaign in Kosovo often put him at
odds with Defense Secretary William Cohen and other senior Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark, who remains popular on Capitol Hill, is leaving his NATO job in
April, when Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston takes over. Clark, 55, plans to retire
June 30. He has not said what he will do after that.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the Pentagon has a timetable for reducing forces in Bosnia and
hopes to develop a similar one for Kosovo, Clark brushed aside attempts by
committee members to pin him down on when all the troops can come home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me go out on a limb and give you my personal opinion,'' Clark said.
``We're not going to be able to complete that mission and wipe our hands of
responsibility until that regime in Belgrade is replaced by a democratic
government.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. troops have served in Bosnia since late 1995 and now number about
4,600. Overall, there are about 24,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia, mostly from NATO
countries. Of 37,500 peacekeepers in Kosovo, about 5,300 are Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Members of Congress increasingly have been critical about continued U.S.
deployments in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The introduction of ground forces to a peacekeeping operation in Kosovo
and the continuing mission in Bosnia has had a significant negative impact on
the Army,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., the committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark would not join U.S. policy-makers, including Cohen, who have
criticized European allies for relying too heavily on the United States and not
spending enough for their own defense.
</P>
<P>
	   He said European countries are willing to pay more in the future -- and
already contribute the majority of peacekeeping troops in both Bosnia and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   Furthermore, Clark said, the United States continues to have ``vital
interests in Europe. That's the reality. We learned that lesson after World War
II.''
</P>
<P>
	   Conditions in Kosovo remain dangerous, he said. Morale among U.N. forces is
low, sniper attacks continue, civilian police are massively understaffed and
there is no political consensus on the ultimate status of Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
