<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bones May Belong to Ancient Greeks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) -- Archaeological finds uncovered at a construction
site in Athens include human remains, possibly those of citizen-soldiers from
the Peloponnesian War eulogized by Pericles in one of history's best-known
orations.
</P>
<P>
	   The remains have been sent to New York to undergo analysis by Dr. Anagnostis
Agelarakis, a forensic anthropologist at Adelphi University and specialist in
Greek archaeology.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The discovery of state burials containing bones dating from the early
years of the Peloponnesian War brings a new sense of reality to the story of
that crucial time in Greek history,'' Dr. Andrew Szegedy-Maszak, a scholar of
classical studies at Wesleyan University, said in an article in the current
issue of Archaeology magazine.
</P>
<P>
	   Historians believe that the statesman Pericles spoke in 431 B.C. at the mass
burial for Athenian soldiers killed in battle against the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is for such a city, then, that these men nobly died in battle,'' he
declared, ``thinking it right not to be deprived of her, just as each of their
survivors should be willing to toil for her sake.''
</P>
<P>
	   Archaeologists said the evidence is strong that the bones, found three years
ago during excavation for a theater, could be those of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
	   All the remains appear to be those of men. The site of the burials matches
descriptions in literature of the honored burial ground for statesmen, generals
and soldiers who died in combat. Also, the style of pottery dated the tombs to
431 to 421 B.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the cremation of the bodies -- a custom for heroes in classical
Greece -- many recognizable pieces of arm and leg bones, skull and jaw and
vertebra and pelvis fragments can be found among the 200 pounds of bones.
Agelarakis first thought there were 200 to 250 soldiers represented in the
collection, but said Thursday he thinks the number is far lower, although he
refused to estimate.
</P>
<P>
	   Agelarakis, who was chosen by Greek authorities, said further analysis would
focus on determining the age and physical range of the soldiers, their diets,
the diseases and accidents they suffered. He also said he would look for any
evidence of broken bones being treated, as well as traces of heavy metals they
might have ingested.
</P>
<P>
	   He said, however, that cremation would have destroyed organic material in
the bones, including DNA.
</P>
<P>
	   The process is expected to take several years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
