<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Above 4,500; Dow Off 51.19  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks moved higher today, carrying the Nasdaq
composite index past 4,500 for the first time, as the sector was untouched by a
warning of higher interest rates from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
Blue chips were down, leaving the overall market mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   In late afternoon on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was up 98.25 at
4,525.90, running past its record close of 4,485.63 set a week ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, off more than 100 points in earlier
trading, was down 51.19 at 10,454.92. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down
0.26 at 1,387.41.
</P>
<P>
	   Presenting his twice-a-year report on the economy to Congress, Greenspan
said the Fed's four quarter-point increases over the past eight months have had
little effect in slowing the economy. Greenspan attributed his concerns about
the economy to tight labor markets and the possibility that workers will begin
to demand higher wages that could set off inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   Blue chip stocks tumbled as the market interpreted Greenspan's comments as
implying that the central bank is likely to raise interest rates again-- as it
has already done four times since June.
</P>
<P>
	   "Greenspan's commentary sure indicated there is more than one interest rate
hike to come and that's not what market wanted to hear," said Barry Hyman, chief
market strategist at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Nasdaq kept rising as technology stocks, which have been largely
unscathed by recent interest rate concerns, continued their advance. "The Nasdaq
is a different ball game. It's not a credit-sensitive sector," Hyman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Intel, up 4  1/2 to 111  5/8 and biotech giant Amgen, up 3 to 72, powered
the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial stocks were hurt by the prospect of higher interest rates. Dow
component American Express fell 6 15/16 to 146 3/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Retailers also tumbled with Wal-Mart down 3 1/2 to 48 5/8 and Home Depot
down 3 5/8 53  7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Greenspan's comments came after a government report today said wholesale
prices held steady in January as a sharp decline in cigarette prices offset
rising costs for gasoline, heating oil and other energy products. The
performance was a better showing on inflation than analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 828.6 million shares, up from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index, reflecting the performance of smaller-company stocks
including many high-tech issues, rose 8.13 to 555.93.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
