<HEADLINE> Gore, Mrs. Clinton Campaign Together  </HEADLINE>
   By MARC HUMBERT AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore will campaign Sunday
in New York in the same place, at the same time, for the first time this year,
as they appeal for minority votes crucial to them both.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides said Thursday that the two will attend a church service Sunday morning
in Albany that is a highlight of the annual weekend gathering of the state
Legislature's black and Hispanic legislative caucus. Both candidates are
expected to speak at the service.
</P>
<P>
	   While the vice president is planning to leave after the service to prepare
for Monday's debate in New York City against former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley, Clinton expects to stay in Albany through the day and attend the
caucus' banquet Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The minority community in New York is an increasingly powerful voting bloc.
Blacks and Hispanics made up 15 percent of voters in the state's 1998 election
for governor and Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   A big test of that minority voting power comes in the state's March 7
presidential primary, considered a major showdown for Gore and the former New
York Knicks basketball star. Both have made major appeals to minorities in their
bids for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that presidential candidate Gore and Senate candidate Clinton
haven't yet campaigned together in New York has raised some eyebrows. It
prompted a front-page article in Thursday's New York Times headlined: ``Gore and
Mrs. Clinton Keeping a Wary Distance as Candidates.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asked recently why they hadn't been campaigning together, Gore told a TV
interviewer: ``It's a matter of scheduling. Not just me, but also her.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said that there was no intentional
distancing of the two candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Both have made it clear that they feel they must step out of the shadow of
President Clinton. As part of that effort, Hillary Rodham Clinton has become
simply ``Hillary'' in campaign posters and news releases.
</P>
<P>
	   The two candidates have had nice things to say about each other.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm all for her. I think she's going to win,'' Gore said recently. ``I
think she will be a great senator. I look forward to campaigning with her.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said last summer: ``I will do whatever I can in whatever way is open
to me in supporting his candidacy because I truly believe he would be the best
person we could have to lead our country into this new century.''
</P>
<P>
	   Key members of their New York campaign staffs have close relationships from
past campaigns and their offices are in the same Manhattan office building,
three floors apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1526 </TRAILER>
