<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Wants Sri Lanka Boy in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW WELSH-HUGGINS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Relatives of an 11-year-old Sri Lankan boy are
fighting to keep him in the United States, fearing he will be forced to fight in
a civil war if he is sent back to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
	   His aunt and uncle won permanent custody Wednesday, giving them a second
avenue to fight deportation, said Dennis Muchnicki, an attorney representing
Senthan Mahendrarajah.
</P>
<P>
	   Senthan has been in the United States since June and is in fifth grade in a
suburban Columbis public school.
</P>
<P>
	   His uncle, physicist Ambalavanar Thavendrarajah, has said the boy will be
killed if he is deported to Sri Lanka, where his mother still lives.
</P>
<P>
	   The Immigration and Naturalization Service detained Senthan in June at
Sea-Tac International Airport in Seattle because he had entered the United
States without a valid visa, court papers say. He was brought to Columbus after
relatives posted $2,500 bail.
</P>
<P>
	   By seeking custody for a U.S. relative, Muchnicki is trying a tactic used in
the case of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy the INS ordered returned from
Miami to his father in Cuba. One big difference is that the surviving parent in
Sri Lanka is said to want Senthan to be here, while Elian's father wants him
back in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   An INS hearing for Senthan is scheduled in Cincinnati next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Hansen, district director with the INS in Cleveland, said an
immigration judge will decide whether the custody decision has any bearing on
the case.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Generally, it doesn't have an impact, but I can't speak specifically to
this case,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Senthan was traveling alone and changing planes on his way to live with a
relative in Canada when he was detained, said his aunt, Dr. Vasanthy
Thavendrarajah. Both she and her husband have been in the United States since
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   Senthan's father died last year as a result of inadequate medical treatment
for a failing kidney, Mrs. Thavendrarajah said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Senthan and his family belong to the Tamil ethnic minority in Sri Lanka,
where the Sinhalese majority controls the government. Tamil rebels recruit boys
to assist military and terrorist operations in the island nation south of India,
papers filed in juvenile court said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Abduction and summary executions of young Tamil boys is a common tactic
employed by Sinhalese security forces,'' according to the papers.
</P>
<P>
	   In Sri Lanka, Senthan was jailed on suspicion of being an accomplice of a
Tamil rebel group, the court filings say. He was beaten in jail and told he
would either have to become a counter-informant or be killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Relatives in Sri Lanka sold their possessions to raise money to get him out
of the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Senthan's mother, after learning he was in the United States, indicated in a
letter that she wanted him to remain there, court papers said. At Wednesday's
court hearing, his uncle testified that 20 civilians were recently killed in a
market bombing in the boy's mother's village.
</P>
<P>
	   When he first arrived in Ohio, Senthan would hold his hand his hand like a
gun and pretend to shoot things, Mrs. Thavendrarajah has said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He is well-disciplined now. He enjoys playing with games and toys,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1528 </TRAILER>
