<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Son of Watergate Judge Decries Book  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The son of the federal judge who presided over the
Watergate criminal trials is angry over a new book that describes his late
father as corrupt, dishonest and having ``clear ties'' to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
	   John J. Sirica Jr. said Thursday he asked the book's publisher this week to
issue a retraction and remove the statement from future editions of ``Gone: The
Last Days of The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
	   The book by Renata Adler focuses on The New Yorker magazine. Adler wrote
that when she was asked to review a book by U.S. District Judge John J. Sirica
she found that ``contrary to his reputation as a hero, Sirica was in fact a
corrupt, incompetent, and dishonest figure, with a close connection to Senator
Joseph McCarthy and clear ties to organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica, who died in 1992, presided over the main Watergate criminal trials
and ordered the production of the White House tapes that ultimately proved to be
President Nixon's downfall.
</P>
<P>
	   His son said Thursday the allegation that the judge had ties to organized
crime was ``patently false and absurd.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it's not malicious, it's so egregiously ill-informed and without any
checking behind it as far as I can see, to be ludicrous,'' said the younger
Sirica, a Newsday reporter. ``I'm very angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica said it was true that his father had been friends with McCarthy
during the early 1950s and, before he became a judge, turned down an offer to be
chief counsel during what became the Army-McCarthy hearings.
</P>
<P>
	   Editors at Simon &AMP; Schuster, which published the book in December, did not
immediately return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica said he did not know if any legal action was possible because a libel
case cannot be brought on behalf of someone who is dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1531 </TRAILER>
