<HEADLINE> Bush's Get-Out-the-Vote Efforts  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Some of the Bush campaign's get-out-the-vote efforts as the South Carolina
primary nears:
</P>
<P>
	   -- A glowing letter of endorsement from the commander of the South Carolina
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
	   -- A mailing outlining Bush's positions and accusing McCain of waffling,
going to 300,000 Republican, Democratic and independent voters.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Two telephone calls to every voter identified as a Bush supporter, and an
additional telephone call to identified social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
	   -- A taped telephone message from Bush that will be delivered by automatic
dial to thousands of households. A message from his wife, Laura, will hit the
answering machines of women voters. Sen. Strom Thurmond's message will be dialed
into rural households.
</P>
<P>
	   -- A letter of support from former presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole is
being mailed to young women. Older women are getting a letter from Bush's
mother, Barbara Bush.
</P>
