<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Want Rapist Executed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABLUS, West Bank (AP) -- Chanting ``execution, execution,'' some 3,000
Palestinians took to the streets Thursday and demanded that a man suspected of
raping a 5-year-old girl at knifepoint be put to death.
</P>
<P>
	   Gunmen fired shots in the air and marchers carried banners reading, ``Our
children have the right to live in security.''
</P>
<P>
	   The suspect, Bilal Shuko, a 22-year-old baker's assistant, was put on trial
Thursday before a military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
	   Three people have been executed in Palestinian-controlled areas in the past
six years. In two dozen other cases, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat commuted a
death penalty to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat's Fatah group organized Thursday's street protest and distributed
leaflets calling for Shuko's execution.
</P>
<P>
	   With an independent judiciary not firmly established, human rights groups
worry that death sentences are handed to appease the public.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What matters to the Palestinian Authority is to defuse public pressure as
soon as possible,'' said Bassem Eid, a Palestinian human rights activist.
</P>
<P>
	   Shuko was initially to be tried by a civil court, but the case was later
transferred to a military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
	   Eid and other human rights activists have said military tribunals deny
defendants the most basic rights. All death sentences handed down so far were
imposed by military tribunals.
</P>
<P>
	   Nablus police said the 5-year-old girl was raped Monday. The suspect dragged
the victim at knifepoint to a deserted house as she walked home from
kindergarten, said Col. Firas al-Emleh, head of police in Nablus.
</P>
<P>
	   The girl was hospitalized in Nablus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
