<DOCNO> APW20000217.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Israel: Avoid Civilians  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department said Thursday that Israel was
contributing to the suffering of the people of Lebanon by shelling civilian
targets in retaliating to attacks by the militant Islamic group Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first implied criticism of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's handling
of Israel's bloody duel with the Iranian-backed fighters in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We do not believe that Israeli attacks against civilian infrastructure and
populated areas will solve the problem,'' spokesman James P. Rubin said. ``Such
actions only add to the suffering of the people of Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
	   Responding to Hezbollah attacks that have killed seven soldiers, Israel has
struck at power facilities and other civilian installations. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said last week it was Israel's way of signaling that it
wanted to reverse the escalation of violence in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   However, on Thursday, Rubin said ``everything must be done to prevent
civilian casualties.'' More than three dozen Lebanese civilians have been
injured in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin also condemned Hezbollah for firing at Israeli forces from villages,
thereby attracting a response that put civilian lives in danger.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There should be no attacks from populated areas in order to ensure that
there are no attacks against populated areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He declined to say, however, whether Israel was justified in retaliating.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Rubin said Hezbollah had violated a 1996 accord designed
to protect civilians from the fighting by shelling from villages. The fighting
prompted the United States and France to convene the monitoring group
established by the agreement. But Israel walked out when its seventh soldier was
killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin acknowledged Hezbollah had succeeded in suspending any meetings for at
least several days.
</P>
<P>
	   But, he said, ``we are working on ways to have the co-chairmen be in contact
with the capitals to begin to allow this process to take place.''
</P>
<P>
	   This, Rubin said, ``would avoid giving the Hezbollah the opportunity to
wreck the process of peace in Lebanon and the process of peace in the region.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United States and France co-chair the monitoring group. Israel, Syria
and Lebanon are the other members.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said Albright had not approved Israel's tactics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She was studiously neutral,'' he said. ``She merely recounted what the
Israelis say that they were doing. She didn't say that was a good thing, she
didn't say that was a bad thing. She didn't say we supported it, we opposed it.
She was noncommittal on that subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
