<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Highest Since 1996  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mortgage rates continued their upward climb this week
hitting their highest level since July 1996 amid fears that the Federal Reserve
will boost interest rates again next month.
</P>
<P>
	   The average interest rate on 30-year mortgages climbed to 8.38 percent for
the week ending Feb. 18, up from 8.36 percent the week before, according to a
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
	   This week's rate was the highest since a 8.42 percent rate for the week
ending July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing, also rose this
week with an average rate of 8 percent, compared with the average rate of 7.96
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
	   On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an average
initial rate of 6.77 percent this week, up from 6.73 percent the previous week.
</P>
<P>
	   The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which averaged at or
just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three types of mortgages.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is convinced that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates
again" at its March 21 meeting, said Freddie Mac's chief economist, Robert Van
Order. "This has spooked the market driving up interest rates."
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association of America said that mortgage
loan applications for the week ending Feb. 11 decreased 8.6 percent from the
previous week and were down 28.4 percent compared with the same week last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
