<HEADLINE> Suspected Gang Murder in Macau  </HEADLINE>
   By PRISCILLA CHEUNG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MACAU (AP) -- A Hong Kong man linked to the casino business was shot and
killed Thursday, the first suspected gangland slaying since China regained
control over Macau two months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing raised concerns that gang violence, which rocked the former
Portuguese enclave in recent years, would recur despite the new government's
pledge to be tough on crime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm a little worried that this would be just the beginning of more
trouble,'' said Chou Ying-cho, a 39-year-old tailor. ``I'm worried that security
will deteriorate and our life would be back to how it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gunmen fired two shots into the head of Fung Kum-lun, 21, while he was in
his car parked in a residential district, said Joao Manhao, senior assistant
director of Macau's judicial police.
</P>
<P>
	   Fung was found slumped over the steering wheel, blood streaming down his
face, and police discovered a bullet from a Russian-made handgun inside the car.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We initially suspect that (the killing) was linked to an argument over a
private matter or revenge,'' Manhao said. He said he did not know how many
gunmen took part in the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Another police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, that
investigators suspect the killing was linked to a dispute over casino profits.
</P>
<P>
	   The territory's Chinese ``triad'' gangs were believed to be involved in the
killing, but it was not immediately clear whether Fung belonged to any gang, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Fung, a Macau resident, was known to be involved with the Golden Dragon
hall, a VIP gambling room at Casino Lisboa, the largest of Macau's 10 casinos,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
	   Manhao said, however, that it was unclear whether Fung was a casino
employee. Fung had spent the night at a karaoke bar and was waiting in his car
after dropping off a friend, Manhao said.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing was the first suspected gang-related assassination since China
regained control over Macau on Dec. 20, ending 442 years of Portuguese rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Forty people died last year in a spate of shootings, bombings and knife
attacks in a turf war over dwindling casino profits, which plunged during the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief Executive Edmund Ho has pledged to clean up the police force and curb
gang violence. Chinese troops have been stationed in Macau.
</P>
<P>
	   Ines Lam, a government spokeswoman, reiterated Ho's pledge to improve
security, adding, ``it would also be impossible to wipe out crime completely in
any city.''
</P>
<P>
	   Macau is 40 miles west of Hong Kong. The local economy relies heavily taxes
from the casinos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
