<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Life OK'd for U.S. Thrift  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators have given New York Life Insurance
Co., one of the nation's biggest insurers, permission to operate a
federally-insured thrift specializing in trust services.
</P>
<P>
	   The Office of Thrift Supervision announced Thursday its approval for New
York Life, which is owned by its policyholders, to open New York Life Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
	   The move came a day after the federal agency announced it had granted
similar thrift charters to the National Association of Mutual Insurance
Companies, a group representing insurance firms owned by policyholders, and to
AXA Financial Inc., parent of Equitable Life Assurance Society and brokerage
firm Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   New York Life, based in Manhattan, has some $90.4 billion in assets, 3
million policyholders and 10,000 agents nationwide. The new thrift will offer
trust services, which include acting as an investment adviser or custodian of
trust funds or property held in trust, executing wills and acting as guardian of
an estate or trustee of an IRA account.
</P>
<P>
	   Several big U.S. insurance companies have gone public recently or plan to,
transforming themselves from mutual companies owned by policyholders to stock
companies owned by shareholders. The companies are making the move to raise
capital for new acquisitions in the rapidly consolidating financial services
industry, spurred by legislation enacted last November allowing banks,
securities firms and insurers to get into each other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   New York Life, however, has said it plans to retain its mutual structure for
the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal approvals make New York Life and AXA Financial the latest in a
string of insurance companies, securities firms and other businesses outside the
banking industry to get new federal savings and loan charters in recent months.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year the thrift agency, part of the Treasury Department, granted
similar charters to Aetna Inc., one of the nation's largest life and health
insurers, mutual fund giant Fidelity Investments and American International
Group Inc., another major U.S. insurance company.
</P>
<P>
	   So far this year, the thrift regulators have approved online brokerage
ETrade Group Inc.'s acquisition of Telebanc Financial Corp., which created the
first financial services company entirely based on the Internet, and new thrifts
to be operated by Southwest Securities Group Inc. and 1st Virtual Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
