<HEADLINE> Corn Falls; Soybeans Rally  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and corn futures prices fell in dealings
Thursday on the Chicago Board of trade, while soybean futures
rallied -- once again boosted by gains in soymeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat futures prices fell amid long-term forecasts for more rain
in the central Plains growing regions. The thought is that
precipitation could benefit the winter wheat crop, boosting the
supply.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn futures prices dropped after the U.S. Department of
Agriculture released a report showing lower-than-expected corn
exports.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, soybean prices fell early in the day on forecasts for
more rain in key Brazilian growing regions but rallied later in the
day as soymeal prices began to rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 2 3/4 cents to $2.62 1/2 a bushel; March
corn dropped 1 3/4 cents to $2.21 1/4 a bushel; March oats fell 1 cent to
$1.07 1/2 a bushel; and March soybeans rose  1/2 cent to $5.08 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Pork and beef futures prices were mostly higher in trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle rose .25 cent to 71.12 cents a pound; March
feeder cattle rose .45 cent to 83.47 cents a pound; April lean hogs
fell .30 cent to 57.05 cents a pound; and March frozen pork bellies
were up .58 cent to 86.90 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
