<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Son of Watergate Judge Decries Book  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The son of the federal judge who presided over the
Watergate criminal trials is angry over a new book that describes his late
father as corrupt, dishonest and having ``clear ties'' to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
	   John J. Sirica Jr. said Thursday he asked the book's publisher this week to
issue a retraction and remove the statement from future editions of ``Gone: The
Last Days of The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
	   The book by Renata Adler focuses on The New Yorker magazine. Adler wrote
that when she was asked to review a book by U.S. District Judge John J. Sirica
she found that ``contrary to his reputation as a hero, Sirica was in fact a
corrupt, incompetent, and dishonest figure, with a close connection to Senator
Joseph McCarthy and clear ties to organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica, who died in 1992, presided over the main Watergate criminal trials
and ordered the production of the White House tapes that ultimately proved to be
President Nixon's downfall.
</P>
<P>
	   His son said Thursday the allegation that the judge had ties to organized
crime was ``patently false and absurd.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it's not malicious, it's so egregiously ill-informed and without any
checking behind it as far as I can see, to be ludicrous,'' said the younger
Sirica, a Newsday reporter. ``I'm very angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica said it was true that his father had been friends with McCarthy
during the early 1950s and, before he became a judge, turned down an offer to be
chief counsel during what became the Army-McCarthy hearings.
</P>
<P>
	   Adler, interviewed by phone, said the statements in the book were true.
``Naturally I can document them or I wouldn't have put them in,'' she said. She
declined to give details but said, ``I'll just have to document it myself.'' She
said she would do it ``soon and in whatever way seems appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
	   Simon &AMP; Schuster published the book in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Sirica said he did not know if any legal action was possible because a libel
case cannot be brought on behalf of someone who is dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Begins in L.A. Shootout Case  </HEADLINE>
   By LINDA DEUTSCH AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Three years after bank robbers in body armor shot it out
with police in the streets with automatic weapons, a federal jury began hearing
arguments Thursday on whether officers let one wounded gunman bleed to death.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney Stephen Yagman, who brought a civil rights lawsuit on behalf of the
gunman's children, acknowledged in his opening statement that Emil Matasareanu
``did a very bad thing. He robbed a bank and shot a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Matasareanu ``was shot and left to bleed to death on the ground,'' the
lawyer said. ``He bled to death from a nonfatal wound that was survivable.''
</P>
<P>
	   The children are seeking unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial will revisit one of the city's most violent crimes, a Feb. 28,
1997, North Hollywood bank robbery that turned into a 44-minute shootout in
which both robbers died, 11 officers were wounded and a half-dozen civilians
were hurt.
</P>
<P>
	   Matasareanu, 30, and Larry Eugene Phillips Jr., 26, wore full body armor and
fired more than 1,200 rounds from automatic weapons in a shootout with officers
who were mostly armed with handguns. Officers had to reload by snatching rifles
from a sporting goods store nearby.
</P>
<P>
	   The shootout prompted the Police Department months later to acquire more
powerful guns.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips died when he shot himself at the same time a police bullet struck
his head. Matasareanu was finally brought down in a close-quarters firefight
with officers in the middle of a street.
</P>
<P>
	   The city has contended that paramedics were needed elsewhere and that there
was fear that the dying gunman might be booby-trapped.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys representing the city of Los Angeles and the officers named in the
lawsuit told the jury there were attempts to get help for the wounded man. But
they also claimed that he resisted treatment and that his wounds were not
survivable.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant City Attorney Don Vincent said Matasareanu had been shot 29 times
and argued that contrary to the plaintiffs' claims that he lay bleeding to death
for a half-hour, he probably died much earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley Gage, an attorney for now-retired Officer John Futrell, told the
jury that if there was a delay in getting treatment for the dying man, ``the
delay in medical treatment came because of the shootout and the brutality of the
bank robbery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
