<HEADLINE> Kids Share Memories of Tornadoes  </HEADLINE>
   By ERIN McCLAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMILLA, Ga. (AP) -- Thursday was the first day back at school for
7-year-old Lacresha Spooner, and her first assignment was to tell classmates
what she saw when tornadoes tore through Georgia, killing her aunt and 17
others.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The house flew away,'' she said. ``And people died. Babies died.''
</P>
<P>
	   Teacher May Wingate also asked the class to write in spiral-bound notebooks
about what they could do to help.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can help my family,'' 7-year-old Jessica Collins wrote. ``I can help
pick up sticks, and I can help find dead bodies.''
</P>
<P>
	   The three twisters that touched down in rural Georgia early Monday packed
winds of up to 200 mph that flattened homes, cars and trailers.
</P>
<P>
	   In Mitchell County, where the storms were deadliest, the worst damage was in
a small subdivision and a mobile home park less than two miles from Mitchell
County Primary School. The school has 600 students, and about 65 had
storm-damaged homes, Superintendent Charles Stripling said.
</P>
<P>
	   Schools throughout the area called in extra counselors to handle children's
questions about the disaster. They encouraged teachers to hold class discussions
on what happened.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to let them talk about it,'' assistant principal Vicki Hicks said.
``These children are afraid. They're afraid to go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
	   Children react to natural disasters by taking cues from their parents,
school counselor Juanita McCall said. Young children who see adults overcome
with grief or panicking about new storms are likely to do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These kids are already talking about the weather,'' McCall said. ``Parents
are afraid, too. The whole community is afraid.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wingate said she will try soon to return the class' focus to the upcoming
Iowa Test of Basic Skills, an important standardized test.
</P>
<P>
	   But Thursday was a day to talk about the storms, to listen to each other's
stories and to look at the clouds and worry about what they held.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Each of these children will work through things on their own,'' McCall
said. ``This is a pain that lasts a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
