<HEADLINE> Bush Denies Using Texas Funds  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Republican Gov. George W. Bush's campaign said
Thursday that none of the money Bush raised for his Texas political operations
went to his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas campaign finance reports show that Bush's gubernatorial campaign
committee paid thousands of dollars last year to two consultants now working on
his presidential campaign -- chief strategist Karl Rove and media consultant
Mark McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
	   Karen Hughes, Bush's chief spokeswoman, said Bush's two political operations
were careful to keep the state and presidential campaign dollars separated.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Not a penny of gubernatorial money went for a presidential expense. It
would have been illegal for the state committee to subsidize the presidential
effort in any way, and it did not,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the campaign trail, Bush has criticized his chief rival, Sen. John
McCain, for using funds from his Senate account to run for president. Bush on
Tuesday proposed campaign finance changes that would prohibit using money from
one political account to pay for another race.
</P>
<P>
	   According to reports filed with the Texas Ethics Commission, Bush's state
political committee spent about $1.2 million in 1999, the year after his
re-election as Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those expenses were just over $53,100 to Rove, who has been Bush's top
political consultant since his first governor's race in 1994. Payments ranged
from $19,433 in March for consulting to a $19.75 reimbursement in April for
express mail costs.
</P>
<P>
	   McKinnon's Maverick Media received nearly $48,500, all for media production
work. McKinnon made commercials for Bush's re-election campaign and is doing the
same for his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes said Rove was paid from the Texas account during the first half of
1999, when the state Legislature was in session, for providing consulting advice
and newsletters that Bush mailed to Texans. Rove received $222,000 from the
presidential campaign during that period, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes said McKinnon's company was paid for videos from Bush's inaugural and
for other expenses from the governor's 1998 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dallas Morning News, which first reported on Bush's spending, quoted
McCain spokesman Dan Schnur as noting that Bush's consultants continued to get
paid long after the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most consultants stop working when a campaign is over,'' Schnur said.
``This arrangement was obviously instituted before Governor Bush became a
campaign reformer (Tuesday).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
