<HEADLINE> Activists Protest at Laotian Embassy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 200 people protested Thursday at the Laotian Embassy
for better treatment for the Hmong, an ethnic minority in the Southeast Asian
country, and a full accounting of what happened to two Hmong-American men who
disappeared during a visit last spring.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You are guilty of crimes!'' shouted Yer Ly of St. Paul, Minn., whose
father is one of the missing men. ``You should die! Communists will die at the
hands of innocent people!''
</P>
<P>
	   Houa Ly, 56, of Appleton, Wis., and Michael Vang, 36, of Fresno, Calif.,
disappeared last April while on vacation. They were last seen boarding a boat on
the Mekong River that divides Thailand and Laos.
</P>
<P>
	   Hmong-American groups are convinced the communist government kidnapped,
imprisoned and possibly killed the men. Laotian officials say they know nothing
of the men's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My father and his companion -- you have captured them and tortured them,''
shouted Yer Ly, holding a poster with a photo of her father. ``Come out and deal
with us! Chicken! Chicken! Chicken!''
</P>
<P>
	   The Hmong, who live in the mountains of northern Laos, say they are
mistreated by the government. Houa Ly and other Hmong fought with CIA-backed
forces during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
	   Mai Sayavongs, a spokesman for the Laotian Embassy, denied the government
persecutes Hmong and said it has no information about the missing men.
</P>
<P>
	   The demonstration came a day after Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif., pressed
Secretary of State Madeline Albright for more information about the missing men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
