<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Bank of NY Aide Pleads Innocent  </HEADLINE>
    By LARRY NEUMEISTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A former Bank of New York employee pleaded innocent
Thursday to charges that she lied in connection with the government's probe of
money laundering by Russians using the bank's accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   Svetlana Kudryavtsev entered the plea in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
where her former boss at the Bank of New York named her a day earlier as someone
who aided the illegal transfer of money.
</P>
<P>
	   Kudryavtsev's lawyer, Charles D. Adler, declined to comment after the brief
appearance before U.S. Magistrate Judge Douglas F. Eaton.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, Lucy Edwards, the bank's former vice president in the Eastern
European Division, and her husband, Peter Berlin, pleaded guilty to money
laundering charges, admitting they helped Russian bankers funnel more than $7
billion through the accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards said she started the scheme to help launder money after she was
approached by Russian bankers in late 1995. She said she was transferred to
London in 1996 and began paying Kudryavtsev $500 monthly to continue to look
after the money laundering accounts in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "She received these payments from us in return for serving as a point of
contact at the Bank of New York in the event there were problems with transfers
and to send my husband account statements so that he could calculate commissions
we were owed," Edwards said during her plea.
</P>
<P>
	   Kudryavtsev was an associate in the bank's Eastern European division in
August when she was questioned by the FBI as it investigated several bank
accounts, according to a criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   She was later fired as it became publicly known that the Russians allegedly
illegally washed billions of dollars through the Bank of New York, the nation's
15th-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
	   Kudryavtsev remained free on $30,000 bail after Thursday's court appearance.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege that Kudryavtsev lied about whether she or her husband
had ever received any money or loans from Edwards or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
	   In separate developments in Washington Thursday, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa,
chairman of the House Banking Committee, said he planned to subpoena Edwards and
Berlin to testify about the flow of money out of Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bank of New York case "represents a verifiable incident where the
financial system has been corrupted," Leach said in a statement. "It is critical
to review whether this is an (aberration) ... or symbolic of an endemic problem
in the international banking system."
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, Rep. John LaFalce of New York, senior Democrat on the House
Banking Committee, said the guilty pleas by Edwards and Berlin "raise very
troubling questions" about banks' compliance with federal rules designed to
prevent money laundering.
</P>
<P>
	   The Banking Committee held hearings on the case in September at which Bank
of New York Chairman Thomas A. Renyi defended the bank's reputation but
acknowledged "a lapse" by its internal supervisors in allowing questionable
accounts to stay open. Some key figures in the investigation have declined to
testify voluntarily before the panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1632 </TRAILER>
