<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Meeting With Chechens  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to a Russian protest, the State Department on
Thursday defended its meeting with a Chechen separatist leader.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're concerned about the situation in Chechnya. We need to get a wide
range of information,'' department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russian foreign ministry said earlier Thursday that ``contacts between
U.S. officials and Chechen terrorists and separatists are absolutely
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said Chechen parliament speaker Seilam Beshayev met Monday only with
U.S. officials who deal with humanitarian and human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We felt to hold that meeting in our offices that deal with that was
appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department has publicly and strenuously criticized Russia's
military campaign in Chechnya for its impact on civilians. At the same time, the
department has opposed a breakaway of the rebellious province and said Moscow
had a right to try to counter terrorism.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia has reacted hotly to criticism of its offensive and has said other
countries should not receive Chechen representatives, whom it considers
illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We expect the U.S. administration to avoid any official contacts with the
representatives of Chechen terrorists and to practically follow its declarations
about adherence to a joint fight against international terrorism,'' the foreign
ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department officials met with another Chechen official several weeks
ago, prompting a similar protest from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said Thursday, ``we have very carefully calibrated our contact to not
give the impression that it has changed our view on the recognition of Chechnya,
which has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
	   However, he said, ``we're concerned about the situation in Chechnya. We need
to get a wide range of information.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said if Russia permitted journalists to go to the area, ``we wouldn't
all be operating from this vacuum of information, and then we could have less of
a need to seek information from sources they might not wish us to speak to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
