<HEADLINE> Gore Meeting With AFL-CIO Leaders  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- AFL-CIO leaders met with Al Gore on Thursday for the
first time since their fall endorsement of his presidential campaign and got
some reassurances on top union concerns in exchange for the votes they are
promising to deliver.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he will continue to support the Clinton administration's push to
permanently grant China normal trade status this year -- something the AFL-CIO
has pledged to fight because of China's poor worker-rights record.
</P>
<P>
	   But Sweeney said the vice president stressed his sympathy with unions'
position that future trade agreements should include worker protections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The vice president has committed himself to being stronger on core labor
standards in trade agreements when he is president,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
	   United Steel Workers of America president George Becker said that although
unions will work hard to fight the China initiative as it stands, ``We're going
to give the Gore administration an opportunity to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the generally warm reception Gore received, the leaders of two major
unions that have not joined the AFL-CIO's endorsement -- the Teamsters and the
United Auto Workers -- skipped Thursday's closed-door meeting with the vice
president, saying they had other commitments.
</P>
<P>
	   The Teamsters hosted Gore's rival for the Democratic nomination, former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, at a meeting in Atlantic City, N.J., earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   The union is trying plan a private meeting with Gore soon said Teamsters
director of government affairs Mike Mathis.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're listening carefully for the vice president to solidify his
positions,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
	   On another matter of importance to the labor movement, Gore ``committed
himself to support changes in the laws, if necessary, regarding the right of
workers to organize,'' said Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
	   The AFL-CIO has complained that it is too easy for companies to use
harassment and intimidation tactics to thwart workers who are trying to join
unions.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney has promised a no-holds-barred campaign by labor on behalf of Gore
this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Gore's meeting with AFL-CIO leaders, Sweeney took him to shake hands
during an early-morning shift change at the Avondale shipyard, where last fall
workers won a six-year campaign to unionize.
</P>
<P>
	   Recognizing that union members are doing a lot of groundwork for his
campaign, Gore told one well-wisher, ``They always say when you pray, move your
feet.''
</P>
<P>
	   Glenda Southall, who has worked 10 years as an insulator at the shipyard and
is a Gore supporter said, ``I just hope that he can make things better for us
all.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``You see a lot of people on television, but he's the first candidate to
take the time to come here. It makes a difference,'' said sheet metal worker
George Weiss, 39.
</P>
<P>
	   White House Chief of Staff John Podesta, wearing a Gore campaign button,
also met with the union leaders on Thursday, the closing day of their annual
midwinter meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Podesta said the administration and the AFL-CIO share common ground on many
issues, including the need for more money for school construction, patient
protection laws and a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
	   On China, they may have to agree to disagree, Podesta said. But he added,
``I think it's a disagreement among friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
