<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNC Bank CEO O'Brien Stepping Down  </HEADLINE>
    By JEFFREY BAIR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- PNC Bank Corp. chairman and chief executive Thomas H.
O'Brien said Thursday he will retire after 39 years with the banking company.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Brien, 63, will be replaced as CEO on May 1 by James Rohr, the bank's
president and chief operating officer. O'Brien will stay on as chairman for
another year following, at which point Rohr will take over.
</P>
<P>
	   Rohr, 51 said Thursday he will push the bank further into electronic
commerce and try to boost its brand name beyond that of "just a regional bank."
</P>
<P>
	   Only half of the bank's business is now traditional banking, Rohr said. The
rest includes the managing of corporate accounts, financial advice and mortgage
banking.
</P>
<P>
	   "I look at the industry and the pace of change that is going on all around,
and I see it as a tremendous opportunity," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rohr said the advent of Internet banking is the biggest development in the
field in the last 25 years and perhaps the entire century. He has shepherded
projects at PNC including CollegeLink.com, a site where people can obtain
college loans from PNC.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Brien, 63, who has been chairman since 1985, said he was glad the bank was
able to stay independent as larger banks have merged. Rohr said he will try to
keep PNC that way.
</P>
<P>
	   PNC went from 7,000 to 27,000 employees and $15 billion to $75 billion in
assets in 15 years under O'Brien. It is now the 14th-largest bank holding
company in terms of assets in the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't see anything ahead but the continuity of things we have been doing
and gaining momentum," O'Brien said. "I looked on the horizon, and it was clear
that it was not necessary to work until age 65."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
