<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Chief Backs Coverage Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FRAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eliminating the rich from President Clinton's proposal to
provide new prescription drug benefits to all Medicare recipients would save
little money and help open the door to Republican tax-cutting plans, White House
budget chief Jack Lew said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview with The Associated Press, Lew said that if Clinton's plan
were to be reconfigured to make it less costly, ``the vast majority of people
who would not benefit ... are not rich people. They're not the Bill Gateses.''
</P>
<P>
	   He added, ``Having an income cutoff at a very moderate income level is the
only way to save substantial amounts of money.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lew offered no figures. But his defense of the president's program showed
that Democrats see Clinton's prescription drug coverage plan as a political
winner in this election year, whether or not it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
	   Lew also said that given the long stream of budget surpluses the
administration is projecting, the president's universal prescription drug plan
is affordable -- and a wiser use of the surplus than the tax cuts Republicans
want.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a false choice to say we ought to provide prescription drug benefits
to some but not all the elderly,'' Lew said. ``The real debate is, is there room
for a tax cut much larger than we proposed?''
</P>
<P>
	   In the fiscal 2001 budget he introduced on Feb. 7, Clinton proposed $351
billion in tax cuts over the coming decade. Congressional Republicans have not
offered their own tax proposal, but have said Clinton's was too small.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle over how to use projected surpluses will be the focus of this
year's budget fight on Capitol Hill. Generally speaking, Clinton wants to use
much of it for spending, while Republicans want to emphasize tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   After taking no action last year on a similar proposal by Clinton,
congressional Republicans have said they will produce their own prescription
drug plan this year.
</P>
<P>
	   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has said the GOP will focus on aiding
elderly people who lack access to or cannot afford private prescription
coverage. Among the options suggested are tax credits and block grants to
states.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about Lew's comments, Hastert spokesman John Feehery said 70 percent
of America's elderly already have ``very good'' prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The real choice is do you want to have the government take over
prescription drugs, or have a program that helps seniors get drugs they need
without encouraging a government takeover of the prescription drug industry?''
Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats traditionally have opposed proposals to restrict Medicare and
Social Security benefits to lower-income people. They worry that such limits
would risk eroding the two programs' political support, which long has come from
across the income spectrum.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's prescription drug proposal would cost $195 billion over the next
10 years, including $35 billion for extra coverage for seriously ill people
whose drug costs soar. Most of it would be paid for from anticipated budget
surpluses, though about one-third the cost would come from proposed savings to
be extracted from Medicare health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan envisions an optional Medicare drug benefit for the elderly
beginning in 2002. It would cover half of retirees' prescription costs up to a
$5,000 cap by 2009, when it would be fully phased in.
</P>
<P>
	   On other issues, Lew said:
</P>
<P>
	   --Over time, repealing the Social Security earnings limit for thousands of
elderly people would be ``free'' because it would keep extra people working and
paying taxes. Republicans have put a 10-year price tag of $22.7 billion on the
proposal. The plan, supported by Clinton, would end the practice of trimming
Social Security benefits for many people age 65-69 who continue working.
</P>
<P>
	   --Amid rising heating-oil costs, the White House is monitoring energy prices
``carefully'' and will watch whether any long-term economic trends develop as a
result.
</P>
<P>
	   --He hopes the White House and Congress will strike a broad budget agreement
this year on spending, taxes and debt reduction. But if not, he said the
administration priorities are so strong that ``Democrats are comfortable
defending them in the political process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1647 </TRAILER>
