<HEADLINE> Police To Question Netanyahu  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Police will question former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu one more time next week before recommending that he be indicted for
receiving favors and keeping state gifts, Israeli media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Police refused comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Radio and TV reports said Netanyahu is to be questioned Sunday. The
interrogation is aimed at wrapping up loose ends before the file is transferred
to the state attorney with a recommendation to prosecute, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
	   Starting last October, Netanyahu and his wife Sara were interrogated several
times on suspicion of bribery, after a contractor presented the government with
a bill for $100,000 for work he said he did for the couple without being paid.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, gifts received by the couple while Netanyahu was in office were found
in storage. Some of the labels marking gifts as state property were removed,
according to the police.
</P>
<P>
	   Netanyahu has denied wrongdoing, calling the investigation politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
	   Yaakov Weinroth, one of Netanyahu's lawyers, said Thursday that police had
made up their minds from the start to recommend an indictment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Even if Moses himself comes along now and says these things never
happened, the way this investigation was conducted, it won't change anything,''
Weinroth told Israel TV's Channel 2.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision about filing charges is made by the state attorney, who can
accept or reject police recommendations. ``We have full confidence ... that they
will make the right decisions,'' said David Shimron, another Netanyahu attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   Netanyahu, a political hard-liner, was defeated by moderate Ehud Barak in
his bid for re-election last May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
