<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhirinovsky Won't Make Russia Ballot  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM HEINTZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Central Election Commission on Thursday rejected fiery
nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky's application to run for president, saying he
failed to report all his assets.
</P>
<P>
	   Zhirinovsky, whose erratic behavior and hectoring statements in parliament
sessions have made him widely visible, had not been expected to perform well in
the March 26 balloting in which acting President Vladimir Putin is the clear
favorite.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he would appeal the decision to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission rejected his application because it said his assets report
failed to include a small apartment belonging to his son. Candidates have to
report on their family members' financial standing, as well as their own.
</P>
<P>
	   Zhirinovsky, speaking at the commission session, argued that the property
constituted just 1 percent of his declared assets.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Do I cite 99 percent and conceal 1 percent in order to harm myself? I'm
not seeking a ticket to a rest home ... but aspire to occupy the highest post in
the country,'' Zhirinovsky said.
</P>
<P>
	   But commission chairman Alexander Veshnyakov rejected the argument, saying,
``Is it really a problem for normal citizens to take account of their own
possessions?''
</P>
<P>
	   Last fall, the commission rejected the candidate list of Zhirinovsky's
Liberal Democratic Party for parliamentary elections after it found two of the
party's top candidates had provided false information about their assets.
Zhirinovsky reregistered the party under another name.
</P>
<P>
	   The deadline for submitting applications to run in the election was Sunday
and Zhirinovsky is the second of 15 applicants to be rejected. The commission
approved a fifth candidate Thursday: Konstantin Titov, the reformist governor of
the Samara region of central Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission has already registered Putin, Communist Party leader Gennady
Zyuganov, leftist Alexei Podberyozkin and Aman Tuleyev, the hard-line Kemerovo
region governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Zyuganov, Putin's nearest rival in opinion polls, unveiled a hard-line,
socialist economic platform on Thursday, which focused on increased state
support for ailing industries and agriculture, state regulation of energy prices
and promises to boost wages and pensions.
</P>
<P>
	   Zyuganov, who has the support of about 20 percent of voters, according to
recent polls -- compared to around 60 percent for Putin -- alleged Thursday that
the participation of Tuleyev and Podberyozkin was part of a strategy by
unspecified authorities to split the leftist vote, the news agency ITAR-Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   But ``the population is well aware of it and won't rise to the bait
easily,'' he said, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Thursday, the electoral commission rejected a referendum proposed by
the reformist Union of Right Forces that was to have included questions on
possibly limiting presidential powers. The commission said the party had failed
to come up with the 2 million petition signatures necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
