<HEADLINE> Diallo Jurors Mull Lesser Charges  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The jury in the trial of four police officers accused
of murdering an unarmed man in a barrage of 41 bullets will have the option of
convicting them on lesser charges of manslaughter or criminally negligent
homicide, a judge ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Joseph Teresi also ruled the jury can acquit if it believes the
officers thought they were arresting a dangerous criminal.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors had tried to convince Teresi that the evidence showed the
defendants illegally stopped an innocent man and had therefore forfeited the
right to cite the ``justification'' protections the law gives police.
</P>
<P>
	   The four white New York City officers still face second-degree murder
charges for killing Amadou Diallo, a black West African immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   But Teresi granted a prosecution request -- unopposed by the defense -- that
the jury be allowed to consider manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide
when it begins deliberating next week.
</P>
<P>
	   Teresi gave no explanation for his ruling. But both sides appeared to be
hedging their bets -- the prosecution against the exoneration of the defendants,
the defense against harsh prison terms for their clients.
</P>
<P>
	   Barry Kluger, chief assistant district attorney in the Bronx, insisted
prosecutors often ask for lesser charges and ``no special significance should be
given to that.''
</P>
<P>
	   Second-degree murder carries a minimum 15-year sentence, and a maximum of 25
years to life.
</P>
<P>
	   First-degree manslaughter -- intent to cause injury resulting in death --
carries 5 to 25 years. Second-degree manslaughter -- recklessly causing death --
carries a minimum sentence of probation, and a maximum of 5 to 15 years.
Criminally negligent homicide -- failing to perceive the risk of death --
carries a minimum of probation and a maximum of 1 1/3 to 4 years.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants -- Kenneth Boss, 28, Richard Murphy, 27, Sean Carroll, 37,
and Edward McMellon, 27 -- testified this week that they fired at Diallo in the
Bronx a year ago because he refused to stop for questioning, retreated to his
apartment building and pulled out what appeared to be a gun. He was hit 19
times. The object turned out to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution contends the officers never yelled any warnings and
continued firing as Diallo was falling or was down on the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was adjourned until closing arguments Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Teresi agreed with the defense that the jury should be told that it can find
the shooting was justified under state law, which says officers can use force
against anyone they ``reasonably believe'' is committing a crime.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was moved to Albany from New York because of pretrial publicity
and protests alleging widespread police abuse of minorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 1654 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volpe says Wiese, not Schwarz, was there for Louima assault  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In his first sworn testimony about the incident, rogue
cop Justin Volpe insisted Thursday that an officer convicted of helping him
sodomize Abner Louima with a broken broomstick was never in the room when the
brutality occurred.
<P>
	   Officer Charles Schwarz, who faces a possible life sentence on his
conviction for holding Louima down, had no part in the assault, Volpe said.
Another officer, Thomas Wiese, was the only person present in a police station
lavatory during the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   "I never saw Schwarz in the bathroom at any time," Volpe repeatedly told a
packed and tense Brooklyn federal courtroom. "When I was in the bathroom, the
only officer who assaulted Mr. Louima was myself."
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe, sentenced to 30 years after pleading guilty last year to the August
1997 assault, was the first defense witness in the trial of Schwarz, 34, Wiese,
34, and Thomas Bruder, 37, for conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing
Schwarz's role in the attack on the Haitian immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe said Wiese stood by the entire time, making no move to take part or
intercede in the attack. That conflicted sharply with Wiese's assertion, to
detectives and Brooklyn district attorney investigators, that he had entered the
bathroom during the attack and intervened by dragging a prostrate, bleeding
Louima from a toilet stall by his legs.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz faces a possible life sentence after his 1999 conviction for
violating Louima's civil rights by holding him down. Volpe, at his own
sentencing last December, said for the first time that Wiese, not Schwarz, was
the second officer in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   The courtroom was rapt as Volpe, speaking in a voice edged with emotion,
elaborated on his story for the first time during two hours and 15 minutes on
the stand.
</P>
<P>
	   As to why he had not come forward sooner to try to exonerate Schwarz of a
false accusation, Volpe said he could not explain "the horrible things I did
that night" to himself or to his family.
</P>
<P>
	   "I couldn't deal with it, think about it, talk about it. As time went on, I
just kept my mouth shut and blocked it out," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Since being sentenced to 30 years in prison, Volpe said, "part of me
reclaiming my life is telling the truth about what happened that night ... I
want to do my time with a clear mind, with a clear conscience, and I can't live
with myself and do my time in peace, knowing that another man is paying for the
crime that I committed."
</P>
<P>
	   Seeking to counter suggestions that Volpe was only trying to save a cop
crony from trouble, Schwarz attorney Ronald Fischetti asked if the two officers
had socialized during their years on the job in Brooklyn's Flatbush section.
</P>
<P>
	   "We never had a relationship of any kind," Volpe said. "We weren't friends.
... I never knew him as Chuck. I knew him as Schwarz, a guy who worked in my
precinct."
</P>
<P>
	   Nervous and presenting himself as deeply contrite, the 27-year-old ex-cop
told of punching the handcuffed prisoner repeatedly, throwing him to the floor
and threatening the suspect before attacking him with the broomstick.
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe said he mistakenly believed that Louima had punched him during a
street riot outside a Haitian nightclub. When Louima became defiant and profane
after his arrest, Volpe grew "frustrated and angry."
</P>
<P>
	   "I was looking for some answers or an apology," Volpe said under strenuous
cross-examination by Assistant U.S. Attorney Laura Resnick. "But I'm not blaming
Mr. Louima or trying to say it's his fault. I was the one who assaulted him."
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe's dramatic appearance came after the prosecution rested its case, but
was delayed briefly after U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson objected to the
witness showing up in blue prison fatigues and sneakers. U.S. marshals scrambled
to find a dark blue blazer, white shirt and tie that would fit the burly Volpe.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution ended its presentation by focusing on phone records showing
the contacts between the accused officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad briefly recalled an FBI agent who has
testified that the trio made an unusual number of calls to each other in the
days after Volpe attacked Louima.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
