<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of Latest Bradley TV Ad  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   An analysis of Bill Bradley's latest television commercial on abortion:
</P>
<P>
	   TITLE: ''99 percent.''
</P>
<P>
	   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   PRODUCER: Crystal Team.
</P>
<P>
	   AIRING: In states with primaries on March 7 and March 14 -- California,
Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Hawaii, Idaho, Louisiana, Maryland, Maine,
Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, North Dakota, New York, Ohio,
Oklahoma, Rhode Island, Tennessee, Texas, Vermont and Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   SCRIPT: (Female announcer:) ``Of the five men running for president, only
one candidate has been pro-choice for everyone all the time.''
</P>
<P>
	   (Bill Bradley:) This is the kind of issue that you can't straddle. You can't
be on both sides. You have to decide which side you're on. Are you anti-choice?
Or are you pro-choice? And I decided a long time ago that I'm pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
	   KEY IMAGES: Opens with text on screen reflecting announcer's words. Women at
a Bradley rally, Bradley talking with a woman and then mixing with people at an
outdoor gathering. Ends with Bradley speaking directly to the camera.
</P>
<P>
	   ANALYSIS: Almost identical to an ad that ran in New Hampshire, this spot
continues Bradley's assault on Gore's early record on abortion, an issue
important to many Democrats, particularly women. The ad comes the same week that
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League endorsed Gore,
partly, because it was angry at Bradley for trying to drive a wedge between
voters who support abortion rights. Hoping for a big bounce, the Bradley
campaign had local supporters release the ad in 25 cities around the country.
Unclear was how effective the ad will be given that Gore and Bradley have
identical positions on abortion today.
</P>
<P>
	   ACCURACY: Both Gore and Bradley support abortion rights, but Bradley has
tried to raise the public's awareness about Gore's earlier opposition to
government funding for abortions for poor women in Medicaid. Given the nature of
Bradley's dispute with Gore on this issue, when the announcer says Bradley is
the only one who has been ``pro-choice for everyone all the time'' that implies
that others -- including the vice president -- haven't always held the same
position. Bradley's comment that he decided ``a long time ago that I'm
pro-choice'' conveys the message that he's the truest supporter of abortion
rights among the presidential field.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Analysis by Laura Meckler, Associated Press writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2037 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
