<HEADLINE> White Land Seizure Tops Mugabe Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By ANGUS SHAW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- The seizure of white-owned land remains at the top
of President Robert Mugabe's agenda, despite voters' rejection of constitutional
revisions that would have entrenched his powers and allowed land confiscation
without compensation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Voters struck down the revisions over the weekend, providing Mugabe with his
biggest electoral defeat in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   But Mugabe and his colleagues in the Zimbabwe African National Union
politburo promised to push ahead with the land seizures, party spokesman Nathan
Shamuyarira said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The government intends to take nearly half of the 30 million acres of
``prime agricultural land'' from about 4,000 white farm owners and hand it over
to land-hungry blacks, Shamuyarira said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mugabe-backed revisions called on Britain, the former colonial power, to
pay compensation to landowners, mostly the descendants of British settlers. It
asserted Mugabe's government had no obligation to pay.
</P>
<P>
	   The revisions were rejected with 55 percent in opposition and 45 percent in
favor. But party leaders suggested Wednesday that the Parliament, dominated by
the ruling party, could insert a similar amendment into the existing
constitution.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, several farmers were ordered off their properties, but then were
told to return because the government couldn't pay the prices recommended by
state evaluators.
</P>
<P>
	   Only 70,000 black families have been resettled -- far short of the target of
160,000 families to be given land in the first decade of independence.
</P>
<P>
	   Zimbabwe's economy has plunged to its lowest since the country gained
independence in 1980. Shortages of gasoline and power, blamed on government
ineptness and corruption, have crippled transport, agriculture and industry.
Inflation and unemployment are at record levels.
</P>
<P>
	   In South Africa, President Thabo Mbeki praised the peaceful referendum,
saying Thursday it had been ``a demonstration of the strength of the democratic
process there.''
</P>
<P>
	   But, he said, South Africa couldn't stand by and let the Zimbabwean economy
collapse.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It wouldn't be good for the region to have a collapse there,'' Mbeki told
reporters in Cape Town. ``You don't want to see people abandoning their homes in
the hundreds of thousands marching across the border coming to South Africa
because of the crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
