<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Audit: HMOs Selling at Big Discounts  </HEADLINE>
    By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pharmaceutical companies sold a drug to two HMOs for 34
percent less than what Medicaid programs pay, circumventing federal rules
intended to ensure the government is offered the same prices as other customers,
federal investigators concluded.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Health and Human Services' inspector general concluded
that the drug companies' practice of giving favored HMO customers better prices
on drugs could cost taxpayers tens of millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
	   The practice "provides drug manufacturers the opportunity to sell to favored
customers without offering that price to Medicaid," inspector general June Gibbs
Brown wrote Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., who requested the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The inspector general investigates possible waste, fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
	   In the two drug purchases reviewed, the inspector general found that
Medicaid programs would have saved $27.8 million if offered the same prices that
the HMOs paid.
</P>
<P>
	   The names of the drug company and the HMOs were not specified in the letter.
</P>
<P>
	   Gibbs also said that drug companies may have adjusted prices for as many as
175 drugs. The investigation, completed last fall, was reported on Thursday by
The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
	   Under federal rules, state Medicaid programs get rebates from drug
manufacturers in order to bring the prices they pay for drugs in line with
prices offered to private companies, such as HMOs.
</P>
<P>
	   The drug manufacturers get around the rules by taking the position that the
HMOs are buying drugs as "repackagers," which purchase drugs and then sell them
under their own brand name, and not as HMOs.
</P>
<P>
	   Drug companies maintain that repackagers are not subject to the Medicaid
"best prices" provisions, which Waxman says is a violation of federal rules.
</P>
<P>
	   He asked HHS Secretary Donna Shalala to launch a fuller investigation and
recoup any lost discounts to Medicaid programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
