<HEADLINE> Israeli Mayor Supports N.Y. Mayor  </HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The mayor of Jerusalem weighed in on the New York Senate
race Thursday, denouncing Hillary Rodham Clinton and calling Rudolph Giuliani
``the greatest friend of the city of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
	   With Jews making up 12 percent of New York's electorate, a candidate
regarded as being anything less than a stalwart supporter of Israel could be at
a disadvantage in the race.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert said he did not want to poke his nose
into American electoral politics by endorsing a candidate, he did not hold back
on his praise for the Republican New York City mayor. Olmert was also speaking
at a Giuliani fund-raiser Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm looking for a friend of Jerusalem,'' Olmert said during a news
conference with Giuliani at the city's emergency command center. ``I have found
no better friend of Jerusalem in America than Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani supports moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem, an idea that is important to some Jewish groups but opposed by
Palestinians, who want to make the eastern half of the city the capital of their
future state.
</P>
<P>
	   The first lady has said she favors an undivided Jerusalem as the capital of
Israel, but she has been criticized in the past for appearing to side with the
Palestinians on the issue of statehood.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, Olmert and others also criticized the first lady for her
silence during a speech in which Soha Arafar, the wife of Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, claimed that Israeli troops had used poison gas against
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton later repudiated the remarks and said she had feared she would have
caused an international incident by denouncing Mrs. Arafat on the spot. Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak agreed, saying Clinton did the right thing in the
interests of peace.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm sure that Mrs. Clinton considers herself a good friend of Israel,''
Olmert said Thursday. ``I was personally very insulted and upset (by the) lack
of her spontaneous reaction to these horrible things expressed by Mrs. Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's campaign did not immediately return a call seeking comment on
Olmert's comments Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The first lady had criticism of her own for the mayor Thursday, saying
Giuliani's decision to bulldoze a community garden in Manhattan to make way for
low-income housing was an example of a ``difference in leadership styles''
between them.
</P>
<P>
	   The state attorney general had requested an injunction to protect all the
city's community gardens, but the lot was bulldozed before a judge could rule.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The mayor seems to think that you bulldoze first and ask questions later
and I don't think you can bulldoze your way in the Senate,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2101 </TRAILER>
