<BODY>
<HEADLINE> John Hancock's Sales Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BOSTON (AP) -- John Hancock Financial Services said Thursday 1999 sales rose
13 percent, boosting operating profits by 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The results were the first since the company held an initial public offering
of stock in January.
</P>
<P>
	   After-tax operating income was $613.2 million in 1999, up from $500.8
million in 1998. The company estimated earnings per share were $1.93 up from
$1.58, based on an estimated 317 million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenue was $7.65 billion in 1999, up from $6.75 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The company reported strong gains from its insurance, asset gathering, and
institutional asset management businesses, and record sales in individual
variable life insurance, long-term care insurance and retail annuities.
</P>
<P>
	   Adding in the costs of converting the company from a mutual insurance
company to a shareholder-owned company and other one-time expenses, the
company's net income fell to $153.2 million, or 48 cents per share, in 1999,
down from $448.5 million, or $1.41 per share, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen L. Brown, chairman and chief executive officer, called January's
demutualization and initial public offering "the most complex undertaking in our
company's 138-year history."
</P>
<P>
	   For the fourth-quarter, operating income was up slightly to $139.8 million,
compared with $139.1 million a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
