<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Eyes Deeper Scrutiny of Mergers  </HEADLINE>
    By NOELLE KNOX AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of the Federal Trade Commission said Thursday
that the agency's reviews of mergers and acquisitions are now more rigorous to
protect competition in this era of mega-deals.
</P>
<P>
	   In particular, Robert Pitofsky took aim at corporate mergers that require
spinning off or selling assets before the deal can pass muster with his agency.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have seen more frequent proposals that are so extensive and complex that
it is impossible to predict with any confidence that competition will be
restored and consumer welfare will be protected," Robert Pitofsky said in a
speech before international antitrust lawyers in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Just days ago, the commission voted 3 to 2 to block BP Amoco PLC's
acquisition of Atlantic Richfield Co., despite BP Amoco's offer to sell some of
its rights and operations in Alaska, where the company would dominate the
market. Unwilling to back down, BP Amoco is taking the FTC to court.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky wouldn't discuss the case, but he said that the oil industry has
reached a stage of "moderate concentration" following three very large deals,
including British Petroleum's own $48 billion acquisition of Amoco in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky's comments come on the heels of a blockbuster year of mergers and
acquisitions around the world. There were a total of 31,528 deals in 1999 worth
a total of $3.4 trillion, according to Thomson Financial/Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
	   To put things in perspective, the Federal Trade Commission scrutinizes less
than 4 percent of all mergers and acquisitions, and ultimately challenges about
2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the number of mergers has swelled over the past decade, so the number
of cases before the FTC has tripled.
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC says it is taking a harsher stance for two main reasons. The first
is that, unlike the mergers of the 1980s, which were largely corporate raiders
looking for financial gain, today's deals are strategic and changing the
competitive landscape.
</P>
<P>
	   Secondly, federal regulators have learned that despite their efforts to
force companies to sell off operations in order to preserve competition, often
times, it doesn't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, of the mergers that were restructured between 1990 and 1994, about
25 percent ultimately failed to protect competition, Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
	   "To address problems that arise in connection with restructuring
arrangements, the commission has adjusted its process modestly to take those
findings into account," he explained.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky said the commission has already begun stiffening the requirements
placed on corporations that suggest spinning off assets and restructuring
companies to meet antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   "It should be clear that the burden of coming forward with adequate
restructuring proposals should be on the sponsors of the merger," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitofsky's speech was important because the agency is "explicitly saying
what has always implicitly been their policy," said Mark Schechter, a lawyer
with Howrey, Simon, Arnold &AMP; White in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
	   "They are going to look carefully to be sure, in their own minds, that
divestiture relief will be effective."
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC and the Justice Department both have antitrust authority to review
mergers. After a deal is announced, the two agencies typically consult with each
other to determine which has the best cadre of experts to evaluate that
particular case.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent years, for example, the FTC has taken the lead on oil deals, while
the Justice Department has examined phone mergers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Trade Commission asked for a second round of information on a
total of just 90 deals in fiscal 1998 and 1999. Of that total, 19 mergers were
abandoned, 23 were cleared, 38 involved restructuring, three went to court, and
seven are still pending.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the deals in the pipeline, the FTC is reviewing the mammoth $120
billion media deal between America Online Inc. and Time Warner Inc., which also
needs approval from the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
