<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Jewish Demonstrators Urge Canada To Watch Austria's Haider
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Moshe Krause joined about 75 Jewish demonstrators outside the
Austrian Embassy on Thursday and urged the world to closely watch Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has all the symptoms of a Nazi,'' Krause, 77, said of Haider, leader of
Austria's right-wing Freedom party.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I lost all my family in the Holocaust and I don't want to lose more,''
said Krause, who survived two years in Germany's Bergen-Belsen concentration
camp.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 100 of his relatives didn't make it, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We rebuilt and we would like to go on.''
</P>
<P>
	   The protest marked the second day of a mysterious visit to Canada which
Haider, accused by critics of intolerance and extremism, has said is simply
``personal.''
</P>
<P>
	   Haider was in Montreal on Wednesday. He remarked to reporters that things
would be more interesting in Toronto but on Thursday boarded a flight to
Amsterdam at Montreal's Dorval airport.
Aboriginal Group Cites More Allegations of Police Abuse
</P>
<P>
	   SASKATOON, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Saskatchewan's biggest aboriginal group says
it's getting more reports of police abuse in the wake of allegations that
Saskatoon officers may have been involved in the deaths of two native men.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federation of Saskatchewan Indian Nations said it received several calls
Thursday from across the province.
</P>
<P>
	   The calls follow the deaths of two aboriginal men found frozen on the
outskirts of Saskatoon and claims that a third man was driven out of town by
police and forced to walk home as punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People are coming out to us and saying, `You should be aware that two
years ago this same thing happened to me,''' said Darcy McKenzie, a federation
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not isolated. This happened not only in Saskatoon, it's happened
... all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 4., Darrell Night complained to police that two officers had driven
him to the power plant, taken his coat and left him in sub-zero temperatures.
</P>
<P>
	   RCMP spokesman Sgt. Rick Wychreschuk said he hasn't heard of any further
complaints against police but promised the force will act on all leads.
Five Winnipeg Police Service Employees Under Investigation
</P>
<P>
	   WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- A suspect has been charged and five employees of
the Winnipeg Police Service are being investigated after two women were found
dead in their home more than two hours after the women called 911.
</P>
<P>
	   Police arrested William John Dunlop about 12 hours after they found the
bodies of Corrine McKeowen, 52 and Doreen Leclair, 51. They didn't explain the
relationship with the victims but said it was a domestic crime.
</P>
<P>
	   Police have said the call was about a man who was violating a court order,
but they would not say if the suspect was the subject of the order.
</P>
<P>
	   Dunlop, 30, has been charged with two counts of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Chief Jack Ewatski said Thursday that one senior police officer and
four civilian members from the communications center had been placed on
administrative leave while his department's professional standards unit
investigates what went wrong.
Audit Faults System of Awarding Film Grants
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- An internal audit of how the government gives out grants and
tax breaks to the film industry says the system lacks some of the proper
mechanisms to prevent fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   The review, released Thursday by the Heritage Department, looked at four
federal bodies: the Canadian Audio-Visual Certification Office (CAVCO), the
Canada Customs and Revenue Agency, the Canadian Television Fund, and Telefilm
Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Heritage Minister Sheila Copps ordered the audit last December after
allegations were raised that some producers were cheating the system to qualify
for tax credits.
</P>
<P>
	   The report highlights several weaknesses within CAVCO, the body that
evaluates whether a project is eligible for tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, there is no audit process in place to evaluate whether projects
that received the tax breaks actually complied with federal guidelines after
they received the money.
</P>
<P>
	   There is also no independent body that would study applications to CAVCO and
point out the potential risks for fraud or business failure.
Meningitis Child Vaccination Program Expanded
</P>
<P>
	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Bowing to public pressure, health authorities
announced Thursday they will vaccinate another 200,000 children in the Edmonton
region against meningitis over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Public health nurses have already been busy this week giving shots to about
65,000 students between the ages of 15 and 19 in Edmonton and surrounding areas,
following the recent deaths of two teen-agers from the disease.
</P>
<P>
	   But public concern about other age groups has prompted authorities to expand
the free vaccination program to include children from two to 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
	   The move does not mean the risk is higher for the younger age groups than
before, stressed Dr. Gerry Predy, medical health officer for the Capital Health
Authority.
</P>
<P>
	   Health officials said they still consider teens between the ages of 15 and
19 to be most vulnerable to the disease.
Consumer-Friendly Airline Legislation Implemented
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- New consumer laws to prevent price gouging by a dominant Air
Canada took flight Thursday, but there are concerns they may not soar as high as
the federal government expects.
</P>
<P>
	   And if new domestic competitors don't appear in the next few years, Ottawa
may open Canadian skies to foreign carriers, Transport Minister David Collenette
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we have to let the Americans in -- if that's the only way that we can
get competition -- then we'll let the Americans in,'' Collenette said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The long-awaited legislation threatens huge fines and jail terms for
uncompetitive behavior by Air Canada, which now controls 80 per cent of domestic
skies.
Alberta Premier Ralph Klein Lashes Out at Health Care Critics
</P>
<P>
	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- The Alberta government got back to business
Thursday as Premier Ralph Klein lashed out at healthcare critics who say he is
staining the Maple Leaf by pushing plans to extend private, for-profit health
care.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've done a lot of things in this province that are deemed to be
un-Canadian,'' Klein told reporters just before Lt.-Gov. Lois Hole read the
speech from the throne to launch the spring session of the legislature.
</P>
