<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Charitable immunity' may limit damages in any Seton Hall fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Survivors of a fire that killed three Seton Hall
University students and relatives of those who died in the blaze may find it
difficult to win lawsuits against the college because of a legal doctrine
limiting liability for such institutions.
<P>
	   The doctrine of "charitable immunity" sharply limits the amount of damages
that can be assessed in lawsuits against educational and religious institutions
on the theory that they have limited funding and might not be able to survive a
costly court judgment.
</P>
<P>
	   And although no lawsuits have yet been filed against Seton Hall in
connection with the Jan. 19 fire that killed three freshmen in a dormitory,
several New Jersey personal injury lawyers said such litigation is inevitable.
They said they expect Seton Hall to invoke the charitable immunity doctrine in
any such lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   "The lawyers for Seton Hall will no doubt be taking a hard look at a
charitable immunity defense," Morristown attorney Stephen Weinstein told The
Star-Ledger of Newark in Thursday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   University spokeswoman Laurie Pine said Seton Hall would not comment on
possible litigation or any defense tactics it might employ.
</P>
<P>
	   Weinstein noted that a state appeals court reaffirmed Seton Hall's
charitable immunity status when it dismissed a suit by a student who suffered a
fall on campus.
</P>
<P>
	   "It involved a case of a student slipping in a puddle of water in what was
then a university-run pub on the campus," Weinstein said. "The appeals court
held that Seton Hall has immunity and the case was dismissed. The immunity was
extended, mind you, to cover activities at a campus pub."
</P>
<P>
	   Weinstein said applying the immunity doctrine to a student dormitory should
be an easier legal maneuver.
</P>
<P>
	   But he and other lawyers, including Harrison J. Gordon of West Orange,
cautioned that charitable immunity does not always offer absolute protection
from court judgments.
</P>
<P>
	   "It only shields them for what is known as ordinary negligence," Gordon
said. "In the event of gross negligence, a carelessness and negligence above the
usual, they could be held liable."
</P>
<P>
	   He said a jury could find the lack of sprinklers in Boland Hall, where the
fire broke out, constituted gross negligence. Seton Hall has since begun
installing sprinklers in all its dorms, and upgrading existing systems.
</P>
<P>
	   But not all schools are covered by the doctrine. In a related move, two
Superior Court judges on Wednesday ruled that the charitable immunity doctrine
does not extend to New Jersey's public schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Ruling in the case of a student from the Clearview school district in
Gloucester County who left school grounds in February 1994 with an unlicensed,
underage driver and was severely injured in an automobile accident, the judges
rejected applying the immunity doctrine to public schools.
</P>
<P>
	   A lawyer for the school district warned that the decision could have
expensive consequences.
</P>
<P>
	   "It means that a school board will be exposed to runaway verdicts,"
Clearview Board of Education lawyer Edward J. Tucker told The Philadelphia
Inquirer in Thursday's editions. "It means that they don't have the immunization
that public colleges or perhaps other kinds of private schools have."
</P>
<P>
	   Tucker said he did not know if the district would appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-17-00 2132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
