<HEADLINE> US Promotes E-Commerce in Argentina  </HEADLINE>
   By BILL CORMIER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley on
Thursday voiced concern over Argentina's safeguards of intellectual property
rights while on a four-nation trip to promote e-commerce and U.S. business
abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our U.S. companies are truly concerned about their intellectual property
investments and that they be truly protected,'' Daley told a business leaders'
breakfast here.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. authorities perceive Argentine protections for patents and property
rights as inadequate -- an issue that came up during a meeting Thursday with
President Fernando De la Rua, Daley said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said it was also in Argentina's interest to defend its own intellectual
property rights. ``Intellectual property is as important to Argentine companies
as to U.S. businesses.''
</P>
<P>
	   For years, U.S. drug companies have complained that protection of
intellectual property rights in Argentina is among the world's weakest, along
with Egypt and India.
</P>
<P>
	   This week Argentine congressional leaders began reviewing patent and
trademark protections, including regulation of the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Daley was on a four-nation tour of South America. He has visited Brazil and
Uruguay, and on Thursday was to leave Argentina for Chile.
</P>
<P>
	   He brought along 19 companies, including AT&AMP;T, which does $2.7 billion in
business in Latin America, and CMS Energy, which built a 600-mile natural gas
pipeline from northern Argentine to Chile.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The business people with me see the long-term potential of this region,''
Daley said. ``They know not only that the economies will be growing again, but
that within five years, this hemisphere will be a Free Trade Area of the
Americas.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Free Trade Area would unite 34 democracies -- nearly 1 billion people --
in the world's single largest trade zone.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Negotiations in this hemisphere are well on their way to be completed by
the 2005 deadline,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
