<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen early Friday amid
expectations that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board may raise interest rates.
Japanese stocks were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 110.40 yen, up 0.26 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but
below its late New York level of 110.59 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 14.82 points, or 0.07
percent, to 19,776.58 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Thursday,
the average closed up 192.22 points, or 0.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar is expected to keep its recent
bullish tone, as some players interpreted Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's remarks
Thursday as indication that the Fed may raise interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher interest rates tend to make a nation's currency more attractive to
investors as interest-bearing securities yield higher returns.
</P>
<P>
	   In his congressional testimony, Greenspan said he remained cautious that
employers seeking scarce workers may offer higher wages and benefits, increased
costs that could lead to a sharp runup in product prices.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior official of Japan's Finance Ministry, however, said the yen may
still recover against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   "Taking a wide view, the trend of yen strengthening hasn't changed," Zembei
Mizoguchi, the head of the ministry's international bureau, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 109.34 yen, up from 108.73 yen
late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started little changed Friday with investors
focusing on adjusting their positions ahead of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's basically a mixed market," said Masaaki Higashida, general manager of
investment information at Nomura Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 46.84 points, or 0.4
percent, to 10,514.57 at Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 1.98 points, or 0.12 percent, to 1,719.09 points. The TOPIX
closed up 25.99 points, or 1.54 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was unquoted in
early trading. On Thursday, it settled at 1.8500 percent and its priced stood at
98.72. (km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
