<HEADLINE> Cheese Ad Puts NC Race in Limelight  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL NOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- A TV ad touting ``the power of cheese'' in a
make-believe campaign between candidates Taylor and Hayes is having a real
impact in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   That's because there really is a congressional race featuring a Taylor and
Hayes here.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My jaw almost hit the floor the first time I saw it,'' said Mike Taylor, a
Democrat running against Republican Rep. Robin Hayes in the state's 8th
Congressional District. ``In my wildest imagination I could never dream this
up.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the American Dairy Association ad, presidential candidate John Hayes
spurns a piece of cheese, and his jubilant opponent, Peter Taylor, is acclaimed
for announcing he loves cheese.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can't walk down the street without someone asking me if I still love
cheese,'' the real-life Taylor said. ``People ask me about it in the grocery
store.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hayes says he loves cheese, too, but doesn't watch a lot of TV. He learned
about the ad from a friend.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's humorous and kind of fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad, created by the Chicago advertising firm DDB Worldwide, shows voters
protesting and derisively refusing to shake the hand of fictional candidate
Hayes. Bob Dole even weighs in, saying, ``Bob Dole thinks he's a doofus.''
</P>
<P>
	   Fictional rival Taylor jumps on the cheese bandwagon. ``Unlike my opponent,
I love cheese!'' he says as camera flashes pop.
</P>
<P>
	   As the lights go out in a quiet Hayes campaign office, the announcer
intones: ``Ah, the power of cheese!''
</P>
<P>
	   The real-life Hayes said he likes the ad, but dislikes Dole's cameo because
Dole campaigned for him two years ago when Hayes beat Taylor by a slim margin.
He said Elizabeth Dole's family, who are from nearby Salisbury, and his have
been friends for years.
</P>
<P>
	   Adam Glickman, the ad's art director, said he was unaware of the real-life
Hayes-Taylor race until after the ad aired. He said he even previewed it with
Dole, who said nothing about the connection.
</P>
<P>
	   Taylor is thrilled with all the attention the ad has attracted.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's an old saying about lawyers and politicians,'' Taylor said.
``Write what you want about me but spell my name right. Sure, getting my name
out there is helpful.''
</P>
<P>
	   Until Hayes' election in 1998, the 8th District was considered a Democratic
district. Now, Democrats are hoping Taylor can win the district back for them.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I guess we'll find out who the big cheese is this fall,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hayes countered: ``It's going to be a winning race for Hayes, the guy who is
the original cheese head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2213 </TRAILER>
