<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Denies Concession Deal  </HEADLINE>
    By TED BRIDIS AP Technology Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft forcefully denied a news report Thursday that
billionaire chairman Bill Gates offered a key concession to settle his company's
historic antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Bloomberg News said it did a television interview with Gates and moments
after it finished asked whether he would disclose the secret blueprints for the
Windows operating system to competitors to settle the case.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yes, if that's all it took," Gates said, according to Bloomberg. It said
Gates did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   A Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, vigorously denied the report. Gates has
previously rejected any suggestion that Microsoft share the so-called source
code to its flagship product, which has earned the company billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've talked to Bill, and Bill said he never said that," Cullinan said.
"That issue is not even related to this case. All he said was we would try to do
our best to settle this case."
</P>
<P>
	   Bloomberg, a business-oriented news service, said its story was accurate.
</P>
<P>
	   "We stand by our story," Editor-in-Chief Matthew Winkler said. "He was asked
specifically, and the answer that he gave was yes."
</P>
<P>
	   Winkler said Gates' response came after the televised interview and was not
captured on video or audio tape.
</P>
<P>
	   During the interview, Bloomberg asked Gates whether Microsoft would consider
opening the source code, and Gates appeared to rule out the idea.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're not holding back any information," Gates said, according to a
transcript supplied by Microsoft. "In order to have the great reliability that
we promise with Windows, you can't have all these variant versions where
somebody has gone and tinkered with source code here and tinkered with source
code there."
</P>
<P>
	   A Justice Department lawyer in the case declined to comment on Bloomberg's
report. Attorney General Richard Blumenthal of Connecticut, one of the 19 state
officials suing the company along with Justice, also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this week, Microsoft rejected in e-mail sent to Congress any plans
to break the company into pieces as the "worst kind of regulation."
</P>
<P>
	   The message, sent Wednesday by one of its lobbyists in Washington, predicted
that a breakup "would end up being the most onerous type of regulatory remedy."
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft's e-mail also said the company was "serious about trying to settle
this case, and we believe a common-sense settlement should be possible."
</P>
<P>
	   The dispute comes just days before the landmark trial resumes. The next
round of courtroom arguments was set for Tuesday, when lawyers will argue about
which specific antitrust laws the company violated, if any.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson found in November that Microsoft
was a monopoly that had abused its influence in the technology industry. The
company's Windows software runs most of the world's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
	   Settlement talks are continuing in Chicago under the guidance of a federal
appeals judge, Richard Posner, who has agreed to serve as mediator. The sides
are under strict orders not to discuss the talks, but settlement is considered
highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft has previously rejected any suggestion that it disclose the
Windows blueprints to competitors, one of the remedies against the company that
the government has considered.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked specifically about the prospect of opening Windows source code, Gates
told Time magazine last November: "The only thing we know for sure would be bad
for consumers is anything that blocks us from being able to innovate Windows or
anything that made it so that when people buy Windows they don't know what's in
it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2217 </TRAILER>
