<HEADLINE> Cuban Dissident Gets Prison Leave  </HEADLINE>
   By ANITA SNOW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Marta Beatriz Roque, one of four dissidents whose prison
sentences drew international protest last year, was granted a 24-hour leave
Thursday after other opponents worried about her health asked for her release.
</P>
<P>
	   Two others also got 24-hour leaves for unexplained reasons, their relatives
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview at her home Thursday, Roque said she must report back by 10
a.m. Friday to a military hospital, where she is undergoing medical treatment.
She said the government officials who authorized the brief leave confirmed that
her prison term of 3 1/2 years had not changed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In prison, your ideas do not change,'' she said. ``Rather, it serves
political maturity.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 54-year-old economist, first jailed in July 1997, was sentenced last
spring for inciting sedition by encouraging businessmen not to invest in Cuba
and by calling on exiles in the United States to ask their relatives on the
island to undertake acts of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other jailed opponents, lawyer Rene Gomez Manzano and engineer Felix
Bonne, were also given 24-hour leaves, relatives said Thursday. Both men are
serving four-year sentences.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not known why the three were allowed to visit their families. The
move may be aimed at diffusing criticism by human rights activists on the island
about recent detentions of dissidents.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is really strange,'' said Magaly de Armas, the wife of Vladimiro Roca,
the only one in the group who did not get a pass. ``I hope that the day that
Vladimiro leaves jail it will be for good.'' Roca is a former military fighter
pilot and son of a revered Communist Party leader. He is serving a sentence of
five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Local dissidents asked for Roque's release on humanitarian grounds in a
letter delivered Feb. 2 to Cuba's Council of State, the government body of which
Fidel Castro is president.
</P>
<P>
	   Roque suffers from a growth in her breasts which has since spread into her
armpits and arms. She reportedly has been hospitalized numerous times since her
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
	   The Vatican, the European Community, Canada, the United States and others
have called for the release of the four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2235 </TRAILER>
