<DOCNO> APW20000217.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Rips Sydney Organizers  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- A day after their ugly spat over sponsorships, the
boss of the Sydney Olympics and the IOC's top marketing official literally
kissed and made up.
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound blasted Sydney organizing chief Michael Knight on
Thursday for having a ``dysfunctional relationship'' with sponsors of the 2000
Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
	Pound accused Knight of ``bad-mouthing'' the most successful marketing program
in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
	Knight replied by suggesting that Pound's broadside was part of a political
campaign to become International Olympic Committee president.
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the two sought each other out at the IOC executive board meetings
and, with television cameras rolling, Knight planted a kiss on Pound's cheek.
</P>
<P>
	``Dick needed a bit of love and attention,'' Knight said. ``I thought as a good
host it was important to give him some.''
</P>
<P>
	Said Pound: ``It certainly was the most exciting part of my day.''
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch played referee in the dispute, which made
front-page headlines in Australian papers Friday.
</P>
<P>
	``Vice president Pound is absolutely right,'' Samaranch said. ``The marketing
program in Sydney has been the best in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
	``President Knight is also absolutely right because his aim is to raise as much
money as possible to protect the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	``I think also that I am right. The most important thing for all of us is to
ensure the full success of the Sydney 2000 Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, Pound criticized Knight for referring to sponsorship shortfalls
for the games.
</P>
<P>
	``Is there anything about the word `success' you don't understand?'' Pound
said. ``You can't undermine your private sector and sponsors like this.''
</P>
<P>
	Pound said the organizing committee was to blame for its budget problems
because it raised its projections for local sponsorship revenue too high.
</P>
<P>
	``The first time, we thought it was wildly optimistic,'' Pound said. ``The
second time we thought it was foolishly optimistic. The third time we knew it
was nuts and said so. We turned out to be right.''
</P>
<P>
	Knight said Friday that Pound's comments ``might not have been the most
appropriate'' but were useful in focusing attention on the importance of
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
	``Our sponsors are incredibly important to us and we value what they've done,''
Knight said.
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the IOC had full confidence in Knight, and repeated his
assertion that he expects the Sydney Games to be the best ever.
</P>
<P>
	On other issues, Samaranch said he considers the crisis stemming from the Salt
Lake City bidding scandal to be over.
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members were expelled or forced to resign last year for accepting cash,
lavish gifts and other inducements from boosters of Salt Lake's winning bid for
the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Salt Lake problem is in the past,'' Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch reiterated that he feels the IOC and its members were victims of the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC was maybe a victim because we paid a high price for the misconduct of
some of our members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he hopes the investigation into the scandal by the Justice
Department and FBI will be concluded ``as soon as possible,'' certainly before
the Salt Lake Games.
</P>
<P>
	Sydney organizers on Thursday cut $22.8 million from their budget. Knight said
the cuts would balance the books without eliminating any jobs or affecting
sports venues or operations for the games.
</P>
<P>
	``There has been no radical surgery here,'' he said. ``It's nip and tuck rather
than amputations.''
</P>
<P>
	UPS withdrew as Sydney's official Olympic ticket distributor in Australia.
</P>
<P>
	Knight said UPS declined to meet requirements for delivering all tickets
door-to-door and organizers are negotiating with three other companies to step
in.
</P>
<P>
	UPS will continue to deliver tickets from the printer to designated
distribution points.
</P>
<P>
	UPS had proposed a door-to-door delivery system along with an alternative
option to provide convenient ticket pickup locations.
</P>
<P>
	``From an operational standpoint, time ran out,'' said IOC marketing director
Michael Payne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mavericks 106, Pistons 97  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DALLAS (AP) -- Steve Nash scored 14 of his 18 points in the fourth quarter
as the Dallas Mavericks, playing without suspended Dennis Rodman, beat Detroit
106-97 on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Rodman was serving a one-game suspension as a result of his ejection in
Tuesday night's loss to Milwaukee. Rodman also was fined $10,000 by the NBA.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mavericks lost each of the two games Rodman played even though the
controversial forward had a total of 29 rebounds. Dallas has won eight of its
last nine games without Rodman.
</P>
<P>
	   Dirk Nowitzki led Dallas with 22 points, 12 rebounds and five assists.
Michael Finley and Cedric Ceballas each had 21 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Nash's 3-pointer with 6:47 to play gave Dallas an 89-88 lead, and the
Mavericks led the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
	   Detroit got as close as 93-91 on Lindsey Hunter's 3-pointer with 4:40 to
play. But Nowitzki hit a 3-pointer with 4:18 left to trigger a 9-2 run capped by
Nash's consecutive baskets that pushed the lead to 102-93.
</P>
<P>
	   Jerry Stackhouse had 22 points for the Pistons, who had won three of their
previous four. Dallas native Grant Hill scored 18 of his 20 points in the first
half, and Jerome Williams had 17 rebounds for the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pistons held an 80-70 lead with 1:38 left in the third quarter, but
Dallas hit three consecutive 3-pointers, two by Nowitzki. Nowitzki's second came
with 2.6 seconds left in quarter as Detroit took an 80-79 lead into the fourth
quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-17-00 2309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000217.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Carolina RB Daniel Davis Jailed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    STAFFORD, Va. (AP) -- North Carolina running back Daniel Davis returned to
Virginia on Thursday, hoping to clear up a probation violation. Instead, he
ended up in jail.
</P>
<P>
	   During a Circuit Court hearing, Davis, 19, was ordered to serve six days but
could be released on good behavior after three.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis rushed for a Group AAA-record 7,080 yards for Brooke Point High School
and was selected Virginia's AAA player of the year by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   On July 23, he was convicted of failing to appear in court on a traffic
violation issued while he was still in high school, court records show. He
received a 10-day suspended jail sentence, was ordered to perform 50 hours of
community service and pay $36 in court costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Stafford County Commonwealth's Attorney Daniel M. Chichester said Davis made
no arrangements to perform the community service, had missed all five of his
scheduled phone calls from his probation officer and failed to pay the court.
Facing extradition, Davis came home.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was given every opportunity to comply, but he never did," Chichester
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The penalty, worked out beforehand by Chichester and Davis' lawyer, Phillip
Sasser, also obligates Davis to perform his community service here during North
Carolina's spring break. Officials said Davis mostly likely would do the work at
a regional landfill.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very disappointed Daniel did not properly attend to his legal
situation. He turned something that began as a traffic violation into a serious
issue," North Carolina coach Carl Torbush said in a statement. "I have made it
clear to him, as well as our entire team, that situations such as this will not
be tolerated."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
